<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GatesOfHellIII-1stAdd     10-03 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gates Of Hell III - 1st Add,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LUCEDALE: support Fountain.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``They love the man tremendously. If my children said to me,
`Dad, that's not the way it was, they were cruel and abused us,'
I'd be after Brother Fountain,'' he said. ``But they've solidified
my support.''
   About 50 of the children were released to their parents, who
signed a court agreement not to return them to Bethel without the
judge's approval. Protecting the children this way was about all
the state and Judge Oswald could do since Bethel is a private,
unregulated facility.
   Now a dozen parents, including Hicks, are preparing a lawsuit
against the state for its action at Bethel.
   ``I look at this much beyond just an incident that occurred in
the state of Mississippi,'' Hicks said. ``Let's term it religious
harassment.''
   __=
   Life is slow at Bethel these days, with so few children around.
The home remains open, but rows of girls' bunk beds stand empty
except for the stuffed bears and rabbits left behind by former
occupants.
   A few new children have come since the hearings. A few former
residents have returned.
   No winner has emerged from the emotional battle over Bethel,
which begins and ends with a collision of convictions.
   Brittain and his team of investigators, Oswald and prosecutor
Mark Maples consider it a matter of child protection.
   Herman Fountain, his faithful flock and other fundamentalists
who came to lend support have called it an issue of religious
freedom.
   Conservative religious belief courses through Mississippi's
veins and beats fiercely in its heart. The perception that the
state is venturing into the realm of the church makes blood run
hot. But so does the perception that church home operators are
using fundamental religion and the Bible as justification to abuse
and neglect children.
   ``I'm a Christian; they're supposed to be Christians,'' said
welfare investigator Kathy Prine, who teaches Sunday school at her
Baptist church. ``I believe this is wrong. These kids are being
physically abused. These people claim the kids are liars and are
not being abused but are being raised by what the Bible says.
   ``It makes you question your faith and your job. When we went in
there, I asked someone, `Am I hurting the church? Am I hurting
God's work by doing this?' I thought about it, and I said, `No. No,
I'm not.'''
   Oswald, in his order removing the children from Bethel, wrote,
``If there is a conflict of interests between religion and the
protection of children, this Court's decision must be to protect
first the children.''
   Fountain sees it another way. ``I dealt with (Oswald) in
chambers, about his soul. He says, `The laws of the land are first
and that (the) Bible's second,''' Fountain said. ``I said, `That's
wrong, that Bible's first and the law of the land is second.'''
   Mississippi, along with North Carolina, South Carolina,
Louisiana, Missouri and Florida, has no law licensing church-run
boarding homes, although some voluntarily apply for licenses.
   As a result, there is no way to reach many of the children in
such homes, many of whom are denied communication with the outside
for months at a time, or to ensure that basic educational,
sanitation and safety standards are met.
   ``We've had to wait years to collect information in bits and
pieces from runaway children,'' Brittain said. ``We have no way of
knowing what's going on inside those four walls.''
   Maples has filed a court petition to force Bethel to comply with
state laws governing education, safety standards and child labor
laws. The court has yet to act on it. If enforced, such an order
could close Bethel, because Fountain has said he would never
cooperate.
   For the two years he has been welfare commissioner, Brittain has
pushed for a law to open the doors of homes like Bethel; Fountain
has prayed against one.
   This might well be the year that the power of prayer is overcome
by the power of politics: observers agree that outrage over
conditions at Bethel has been so great that the Legislature might
be forced to act.
   Even Fountain agrees, saying, ``It would take an act of God'' to
prevent a licensure law from emerging in the next legislative
session.
   At Bethel, they will be praying round the clock.
   ``They're going against God, and that's their problem. That's
why we're going to win,'' Fountain said. ``The gates of hell ain't
going to prevail against our church.''
</TEXT>
