<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Acronymania     10-03 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Acronymania,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indonesia: Home Of The Rampant Acronym</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   KOPKAMTIB was abolished recently by a
KEPPRES, which created BAKORSTANAS to take its place.
   The acronym _ some would call it alphabet soup _ is alive and
kicking in Indonesia. What happened recently, in translation from
Indonesian acronymania, is this:
   The Operational Command for the Restoration of Security and
Order (KOPKAMTIB, or Komando Operasi Pemulihan Keamanan Dan
Ketertiban) was abolished by a presidential decree (KEPPRES, or
keputusan president), which created in its place the Coordinating
Agency for Assisting the Strengthening of National Stability
(BAKORSTANAS, or Badan Koordinasi Bantuan Pemantapan Stabilitas
Nasional).
   Acronyms and abbreviations are a national craze, used to
condense unwieldy phrases but serving in many other cases to
compound confusion.
   For one thing, it is common, if not preferable, to use the first
syllable instead of the first letter of words, as with KEPPRES.
   The main political party is called GOLKAR, which is short for
Golongan Karya and comes out in English as Functional Groups.
   Headline writers delight in the convenience offered by the
thousands of short forms, but to the uninitiated the front pages of
Indonesian newspapers resemble a lexicographer's nightmare.
   Acronyms also are found in telephone books and on the doors of
government offices. Standard dictionaries offer no help.
   Many say the use of acronyms first spread during the
administration (1949-66) of President Sukarno, known familiarly as
Bung Karno, for Brother Sukarno.
   During the Sukarno years, the habit was applied to English
phrases as well as the national tongue, Bahasa Indonesia.
   The term ``neo-colonial imperialism'' was cut to ``necolim.''
   A sports tournament for Third World athletes became known as
Ganefo _ Games of the Newly Emerging Forces.
   Communist China became CINKOM.
   Blame or credit for entrenching linguistic short cuts is usually
pinned on the armed forces, or the abri.
   As early as 1976, Professor Takdir Alisjahbana warned that the
influential military was coining so many acronyms that the standard
of Bahasa Indonesia might deteriorate. He said such usage added
nothing to the stock of new ideas but only increased the burden on
the memory.
   One magazine editor cautioned his staff about shortening jaksa
agung (attorney general) to jagung, which means popcorn.
   There are acronyms for most government departments and senior
officials.
   The president's personal assistants are aspri _ short for
``asisten pribadi president.''
   The alphabet soup is sometimes flavored with numbers.
   P3 is what people sometimes call the opposition political group
Partai Persatuan Pembangunan (United Development Party).
   Then there's BP-7 _ Badan Pembinaan Pendidikan Pelaksanaan
Pedoman Penghayatan Dan Pengamalan Pancasila.
   That's the Board for Guidance on the Means of Teaching
Guidelines for the True Interpretation and Implementation of the
State Ideology.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0006 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ShipDisaster     10-03 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ship Disaster,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Signs Emerge That More Died, Little Done To Correct Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine months after the Dona Paz sank
in the worst peacetime shipping disaster, the death toll remains a
mystery and secrecy surrounds official investigations into the
cause of the accident.
   The 2,215-ton Dona Paz collided Dec. 20 with the 629-ton oil
tanker Vector off Mindoro island. Both vessels exploded in huge
fireballs.
   Only 26 of the 1,775 people known to be on board the vessels
were saved, but the real death toll may never be known.
   Manifests on inter-island vessels are notoriously inaccurate.
They often record children as ``half passengers'' or disregard them
entirely. Corrupt officials frequently accept bribes to allow
overloading.
   In addition, many victims probably were incinerated when the
vessels exploded and will never be accounted for. Rescuers found
only 108 bodies, many of them charred and mutilated beyond
recognition.
   Sulpicio Lines, owner of the Dona Paz, has never officially
acknowledged that the passenger ship carried more than the 1,583
people listed on the manifest.
   But Vicente Gambito, a Sulpicio Lines vice president, says the
company has paid claims to relatives of 2,748 people. He said each
claimant received $1,500 in exchange for agreeing not to file suits
or seek additional compensation.
   Another 1,642 claims are being processed.
   Uncertainty of just who was on the ship has led to fraud.
Gambito said one man was jailed after receiving a settlement, then
returning with claims for another 13 ``relatives.'' Some
``relatives'' turned up in the United States and were not even
related to the claimant, Gambito said.
   ``What we're trying to play here is a percentage game,'' he
said. ``There is no way that we can, with finality, prove or
disprove that a person was on board. So we are taking chances.''
   The Dona Paz was authorized to carry 1,518 passengers and a crew
of 60. The Vector carried 13 crewmen, two of whom survived.
   Most aboard the Dona Paz were poor people from the islands of
Samar and Leyte who planned to spend Christmas with relatives in
Manila.
   Gambito said payment of claims does not necessarily mean the
company admits the claimants' relatives were aboard the Dona Paz.
He said five applications proved false.
   But Rosario Marasigan, an assistant director of the Department
of Social Welfare and member of the government task force, said she
believes most of the claims settled by the company were genuine.
   Both houses of Congress have completed separate investigations
but have not acted on their findings.
   Both congressional reports found virtually everything about
Philippine shipping wrong. They cited obsolete ships and navigation
charts, poor or non-existent communication and navigational aids,
lax enforcement of safety regulations, and poorly trained crews.
   Officials say there would have probably been no survivors if
three merchant ships had not been in the area when the collision
occurred. They picked up the survivors.
   The Philippine Coast Guard has not released findings of the
official investigation conducted by its Board of Marine Inquiry.
Board members, mostly retired civilian seamen, said they submitted
their findings to the Coast Guard in March.
   The Coast Guard in Manila, 110 miles north of the collision,
received first word of the tragedy eight hours after it happened.
It took another eight hours to launch search and rescue operations.
   One of the many unanswered questions is whether the Dona Paz
sent out a distress call. None of the crew survived, and no radio
station reported any distress signal.
   To check the effectiveness of the receiving system, National
Telecommunications Commission Chief Jose Luis Alcuaz boarded a ship
a few weeks after the disaster and sent an SOS from the collision
site. No Coast Guard station acknowledged receipt.
   Members of the marine board refuse to discuss their findings.
Law requires that findings be forwarded to the Coast Guard
commandant for review and release.
   Lt. Cmdr. Makaraig Cuevas, a Coast Guard spokesman, said the
papers were being reviewed.
   Asked why a report had not been released, Col. Victor Corpuz,
the Coast Guard official reviewing the findings, replied: ``The
commandant has not signed it. Why are you interested?'' He then
hung up.
</TEXT>
