<2ND_LINE>PM-Papandreou,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Premier Recovering From Heart Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAREFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two days after his heart surgery,
Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou of Greece was able to get out of
bed and walk, a Harefield Hospital spokesman said.
   The 69-year-old leader underwent six hours of surgery on Friday
to replace a diseased aortic valve.
   ``He is fine. There are no problems or complications,'' said a
hospital spokesman on Sunday. He said Papandreou was able to walk
around the intensive care unit of the hospital.
   Papandreou was restricted over the weekend to visits from his
three sons, his daughter and his companion, Dimitra Liani. His
wife, whom he said he is divorcing, did not come to Britain.
   If Papandreou continues to make good progress, he could be out
of the hospital in 10 days.
   The Greek leader flew to Britain last month suffering from
narrowing of the main heart artery and underwent treatment to ready
him for the operation.
</TEXT>
