<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Rampage'sIrony     10-03 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rampage's Irony,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman And Cop Lived A World Apart, Died Side-by-Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A policewoman full of life and laughter and a
jobless Vietnam veteran haunted by the horrors of war lived worlds
apart, but their worlds collided when they died side by side in a
bloody rampage.
   Clem Henderson shot Irma Ruiz in the heart in the doorway of the
Montefiore School on the West Side. Minutes later, Henderson fell
fatally wounded just a few feet away, shot by Mrs. Ruiz's partner.
Two other people also died.
   Mrs. Ruiz's partner, Detective Gregory Jaglowski, remembered her
as ``a great woman, best friend. She was the greatest partner you
could ever have.''
   ``Irma made us laugh,'' Officer Dorothy Griffin said in her
eulogy at Mrs. Ruiz' funeral one week ago. ``She loved jewelry and
diamonds, and like a diamond, she sparkled. ... Her sense of humor,
her quick wit, were matched only by her love of family.''
   Both Henderson and Mrs. Ruiz were 40 when they died Sept. 22. He
was the father of three sons; she had three sons and a daughter.
   Henderson harbored a ``passion for the plight'' of Vietnam GIs,
said David Finke, a friend who works for the Midwest Committee for
Military Counseling, a private, non-profit group Henderson was
involved with. ``He felt that nobody wanted to listen, that society
had turned its back.''
   So, he helped other vets, working with the National Black Draft
Counselors and dreaming of creating his own veterans center. He'd
even picked out a building that he talked of buying, Finke said.
   But the day he died, Henderson stalked his neighborhood armed
with a .38-caliber revolver, and vowed to ``kill everybody I see.''
   Henderson's demons likely took him back to Vietnam, friends say.
Psychiatrists call it ``post-traumatic stress syndrome.''
   ``My sense is that once he started shooting, he was just back on
patrol again. He was in the jungle under this detached sense where
you simply turn off your emotions,'' said Finke.
   ``How do we expect them to unlearn those reflexes just because
they are discharged,'' Finke asked. ``You've got a time bomb
situation with embittered people who are feeling abandoned.''
   To know the real Clem Henderson, you have to know his pre-war
life, said Alonzo Jackson, brother of Henderson's ex-wife, Emma.
   ``Before the war, he was open, always happy, and energetic.
After the war, he was different. ... He mostly kept to himself,''
Jackson said at Henderson's burial Friday.
   ``He was a victim of the Vietnam War, plain and simple.''
   Police records show Henderson was arrested 12 times, mostly for
battery and disorderly conduct, and spent more than six years in
jail between 1973 and 1984.
   He found work at a beauty school, but a 1985 gunshot wound to
the head caused seizures that forced him to stop, friends and
acquaintances say. Police records show the wound was
self-inflicted; Henderson's brother, Roger, says he was shot by an
attacker.
   Henderson alternated between living with his mother and his
second wife, Daisy, Finke said. But he also talked of sleeping on
park benches, Finke said.
   Mrs. Ruiz knew the risks of police work, but rarely talked about
the dangers, said brother-in-law Paul Fedrick.
   By all accounts, family and police work were her dreams come
true.
   ``She has approximately 25 nieces and nephews, and she made sure
that every Christmas, every kid had something under the tree,''
said Fedrick, 29. ``She was like the matriarch to the family.''
   She graduated at the top of her class from the police academy in
1976, becoming one of the first Hispanic women on the force, and
won departmental honors since then.
   But her children and family came first.
   ``What stands out in my mind is that whenever we needed a parent
to come in for any reason, she would be there,'' said Sister
Campion Maquire, principal of Christ The King School, which the two
youngest Ruiz children attend.
   ``We were proud to have her in our community,'' said neighbor
and close friend Rose Coleman. ``(I) only wish that everybody had a
chance to know her.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
