<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reporter'sNotebook     10-03 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reporter's Notebook,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ticket? Anybody Got a Ticket to the Dukakis Rally? Check with the
Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ticket to a Michael Dukakis rally
is easier to come by than one for a Boston Red Sox home game or a
performance of ``Les Miserables.'' And a lot cheaper, too.
   What makes a Dukakis ticket unusual is that people need one at
all.
   In fact, they do if they want to be right down front, within
cheering distance of the Democratic presidential candidate.
   Or, in this campaign, it might be more appropriate to say within
heckling distance of the candidate.
   Immediately after Labor Day, Dukakis began encountering intense
heckling, particularly from anti-abortion activists.
   He had to fight to be heard during an appearance in early
September in Niles, Ill.
   The campaign decided something had to be done. Their response
was to rope off the area closest to the podium and require tickets
for admission.
   Even students at Rutgers University needed tickets to get close
to Dukakis when he delivered a speech on the environment.
   In that case, a ticket got a little star quality because actor
Robert Redford introduced the candidate.
   Tickets also were required for rallies in Melrose Park, Ill.;
Jersey City, N.J.; and Greensburg, Pa.
   The tickets were free, obtained from elected and party officials
or from unions.
   So, at each rally, the people down front were reliably
enthusiastic for the candidate and cheered at every jibe against
Republican George Bush, their response usually drowning out the
chants of Bush supporters relegated to the fringes of the crowd.
   Another tool used to control hecklers is loud speakers, the huge
kind, usually found at events like rock concerts.
   A bank of mega-decibel speakers placed at the rear of the crowd
assures that the candidate's voice will be heard above the chants
of any hecklers.
   At Rutgers, someone neglected to provide quite enough speakers
and Dukakis had to contend with a large group of pro-Bush students
who chanted, ``Borrrring, borrrring,'' and recited the Pledge of
Allegiance to the flag.
   But they didn't have tickets, so they were too far from the
podium to effectively disrupt his speech.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   During a campaign stop in Idalou, Texas, reporters traveling
with Dukakis were delighted to receive colorful bandanas, some red,
some blue.
   Several reporters were wearing them when they got off the plane
with Dukakis in Ontario, Calif. The entourage went off to tour the
Stringfellow toxic waste dump.
   The next stop was a nearby high school and a Secret Service
agent asked the reporters to take off their bandanas.
   He said local gangs _ the Crips and Bloods _ wear colored
bandanas to identify themselves. The agent said local police were
concerned that seeing reporters wearing the scarves would encourage
the practice among students.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   For two weeks, Dukakis kept his distance from reporters, a
tactic reflecting concern that responses to questions often were
overshadowing the messages in his speeches.
   When he held a news conference in Dallas, a reporter asked if
the reduced access to the candidate was a shift in attitude.
   The candidate smiled, shrugged and pointed out that he was
answering questions at that very moment.
   ``Take advantage of the opportunity,'' he said. ``You never know
when it will happen again.''
   When the news conference ended and he was leaving the room, a
reporter shouted, ``See you next month, governor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-BigWeek Bjt   10-03 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Big Week, Bjt,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Champagne Flows, So Does Praise, But The U.N. Still Has A Beer
Pocketbook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the United Nations, last week was a
week of champagne and euphoria. Even the U.N. fountain, dry for
three years of financial drought, was splashing again in the autumn
air _ a sign of happy times.
   There was the Nobel Peace Prize for U.N. peacekeeping and the
farewell speech of President Reagan, who finally praised the world
body.
   Reagan and other speakers hailed peace agreements, talks or
prospects of peace in Afghanistan, the Iran-Iraq war, Southern
Africa and Namibia, Cambodia and the Western Sahara _ conflicts in
which the United Nations has played or will play a major role
resolving.
   So popular is the United Nations that Britain and Iran chose it
as the forum to announce the resumption of full diplomatic
relations.
   China and the Soviet Union chose it to announce the first
working visit of a Chinese foreign minister to Moscow since the
1950s, a major step toward a Sino-Soviet summit.
   At the United Nations, Chinese and Soviet foreign ministers also
discussed Cambodia, signaling a new impetus by the communist rivals
to solve the problem of Vietnamese occupation.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and Democratic
Presidential Candidate Michael Dukakis chose the General Assembly
and the nearby Waldorf Astoria to meet.
   Even the fountain in the U.N. Plaza, turned off in a fiscal
austerity drive, was turned on in a sign that the United Nations
has received both a little more money from the United States and
other indebted nations, and a lot more respect.
   The high point of the week was Thursday, when the Nobel Peace
Prize was awarded to U.N. peacekeeping operations worldwide for 40
years. The Nobel Prize committee cited recent U.N. achievements in
mediating an Afghan agreement and in arranging a cease-fire in the
Iran-Iraq war.
   While celebrating the Nobel Peace Prize with champagne, U.N.
officials warned the United Nations still has a beer pocketbook
because the organization owes nearly $600 million.
   The three-week General Debate, a parade of world leaders, began
Monday when President Reagan addressed the General Assembly of 159
nations and, in a dramatic turnabout, conceded the organization he
criticized for seven years was doing a good job.
   ``Yes, the United Nations is a better place today,'' Reagan
said, ``but so, too, is the world.''
   Reagan's administration had debunked the organization for
anti-Western bias, ineffectiveness and wasteful bureaucracy.
   Other speakers lauded the United Nations.
   They also covered the full range of standard problems, from
apartheid to Third World debt but the tone was far less contentious
than in previous years, reflecting the improvement in East-West
relations.
   There was special emphasis on strengthening the existing ban on
chemical weapons and Reagan called for an international conference
in Paris on the outlawed weapons. President Francois Mitterand of
France urged embargos of chemical weapons materials to offending
states.
   The environment was a major topic and for the first time,
Shevardnadze devoted a major portion of his General Assembly speech
to the ozone layer, the biosphere, acid rain, dying seas and dying
fauna.
   For the Soviets, it was a major shift in focus, a joining of the
international ecological movement as it seeks to extricate itself
from regional conflicts and improve relations with Washington and
Beijing.
   But there were problems and embarrassments, too, signs of
limitations of the world organization.
   Just hours after champagne flowed to celebrate the Nobel Peace
Prize announcement, the Soviet Union said the U.N.'s tiny 50-man
observer force in Afghanistan and Pakistan was ``not doing a good
job.''
   Shevardnadze told the permanent members of the Security Council
that the U.N. team has failed to investigate flagrant violations of
the Afghanistan agreements by Pakistan for allegedly training and
arming Afghan rebels.
   And while a U.N.-supervised cease-fire was holding on the
Iran-Iraq war front, talks toward a permanent peace have dragged
into their second month.
   Both sides have been intransigient, after Iraq introduced the
issue of sovereignty over the disputed Shatt al-Arab waterway and
insisted on early U.N. dredging before proceeding with talks on
other issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
