<DOCNO> AP881003-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia     10-03 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Milosevic Strengthens Hand Before Oct. 17 Showdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Serbian leader hailed by
supporters as ``the second Tito'' has moved closer to regaining
Serbian control over two provinces and is strengthening his hand
inside the divided Communist leadership.
   Slobodan Milosevic was given a boost last week with the
resignation of two political rivals and formal party backing for
Serbia's demands to absorb Vojvodina and Kosovo provinces.
   The moves have given Milosevic ammunition that will be useful in
a major political showdown expected at a Central Committee meeting
Oct. 17.
   On Friday, the Communist party's Presidium, or politburo,
approved Serbia's drive to tighten control over the two provinces,
apparently bowing to the pressure exerted by hundreds of thousands
of Slavs at almost daily rallies.
   Late Saturday, the state news agency Tanjug announced the
resignation from the powerful 23-man Poliburo of Bosko Krunic, who
until July held the annually rotating leadership of Yugoslavia's
ruling Communist party.
   Krunic's resignation followed the similarly sudden exit of Franc
Setinc, a Communist leader from the liberal northern republic of
Slovenia, last Monday.
   Setinc resigned in a public letter attacking the ``insanity'' of
emotional mass rallies by Milosevic supporters, who frequently have
called for the ouster of Krunic and other Communist leaders.
   Ostensibly, the rallies _ which drew at least another 100,000
Slavs on to the streets this weekend _ are held to express support
for the Serbs and Montenegrins in ethnically troubled Kosovo, where
Slavs allege daily harassment by the Albanian majority.
   The emotional crowds wave portraits of the 47-year-old
Milosevic, lauding the leader of Serbia's Communist party for his
drive to reimpose full Serbian control over Kosovo and Vojvodina.
   Since the rallies started in July, however, they have become a
vehicle for expression of popular discontent with the party's
inability to end a protracted economic and social crisis.
   The annually rotating collective leadership of the country and
the party bequeathed by the late Josip Broz Tito before he died in
1980 has failed to come to grips with Yugoslavia's problems.
   This weekend, inflation officially hit 217 percent. Unemployment
stands at 15 percent. An austerity program adopted last May to
repay the $21 billion foreign debt is to be modified next week,
with the government again trying to stave off worker unrest by
giving way to demands for higher wages to cope with spiraling price
hikes.
   In this chaos, Milosevic has skilfully used the emotional issue
of Kosovo to unite many hundreds of thousands of Serbs behind him
and to appear to them as the strong political leader needed to rule
as effectively as Tito.
   Arguably Yugoslavia's most backward region, Kosovo was once the
heart of Serbia's medieval empire. To the mostly Christian Slavs,
it symbolizes Serbia's most glorious days.
   But the province is now dominated by mostly Moslem ethnic
Albanians, who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people and
have the highest birthrate in Europe.
   The Slavs resent how the Albanians have used Tito's 1974
constitution, which granted broad powers to the autonomous
provinces of Kosovo and Vojvodina.
   Serbs allege that the Albanians seek even greater autonomy in
the form of a full-fledged republic. If this happens, Serbs argue,
the republic would instantly secede and unite with neighboring
Communist Albania, precipitating Yugoslavia's disintegration.
   By taking up the cause of Kosovo's Serbs, Milosevic can thus
argue that he is acting not simply for the benefit of the Slavs but
to preserve the six republics that comprise Yugoslavia.
   In the republics of Slovenia, Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina,
party leaders are suspicious of Milosevic and traditionally wary of
Serbia, the largest of Yugoslavia's republics.
   Bosnia-Herzegovina posted police on its borders last month to
stop potential pro-Milosevic demonstrators from rallying there.
   DANAS, an influential Croatian weekly, wondered aloud in its
latest issue ``Who Will Say Enough?'' to protest rallies.
   Both the state presidency and the party Presidium have urged
Yugoslavs not to attend the massive rallies.
   But Milosevic never asked his supporters to go home and his
recalcitrance now seems to have paid off.
   At Friday's Presidium meeting, state president Raif Dizdarevic
said the proposals for changes granting Serbia greater control are
``an acceptable basis'' for discussion.
   Replied Milosevic: ``It is with great satisfaction that we heard
encouragement today.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ShuttleWatchers 2ndLd-Writethru a0844 10-03 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Watchers, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0844,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Seek Glance at Shuttle Landing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE crowd size; picks up 9th graf,
``NASA and ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motor homes, many
festooned with American flags, stretched for four miles along a dry
lake bed Sunday as thousands of people camped out waiting to see
space shuttle Discovery land.
   ``This is what America's all about,'' said Vic Failla, 61, of La
Verne, a World War II veteran who brought his brother Tony to see
the shuttle end its four-day flight at this air base in the Mojave
Desert 80 miles north of Los Angeles.
   Touchdown is scheduled for Monday at 9:37 a.m. PDT.
   Recreational vehicles streamed into the eastern shoreline of
Rogers Dry Lake on a ribbon of heat-rippled two-lane blacktop lined
by twisted Joshua trees and surrounded by rattlesnake-infested
desert.
   Across the dry lake bed, the Air Force Base hangars glistened in
102-degree heat. As night fell, temperatures dipped into the 70s
and the bright lights of the base could be seen across the lake bed
from the spectator encampment.
   Many of the campers enjoyed candlelight dinners inside their
motor homes while others gathered around hibachis outside to roast
hot dogs and hamburgers by lantern light.
   ``The flags just make you feel terrific,'' said Alice Brakke,
who sold small American flags for $2 each. ``Families come up and
get one for each member.''
   A speaker on her stand, one of dozens lining the viewing area,
blasted a non-stop broadcast of the late Kate Smith singing ``God
Bless America.''
   Air Force spokesman Lt. Col. George Neiss said that by Sunday
night 10,950 vehicles, carrying an estimated 38,500 people, had
arrived.
   NASA and the Air Force predict as many as 200,000 people will
watch the shuttle land, and their numbers will include Vice
President George Bush, who will greet the astronauts as they
descend from the orbiter.
   The record crowd for a touchdown was 500,000, the number who
joined President Reagan in welcoming home the crew of Columbia on
July 4, 1982.
   Skateboarders and bicyclists rolled across the cracked and
buckled lake bed. Crowds wandered shirtless and in shorts, enjoying
Hawaiian shaved ice and picking over souvenirs that included models
of the secret Stealth bomber at $12 each, Stealth coffee mugs at
$5, and sun glasses for $10.
   Hundreds of youngsters tossed footballs and teen-age boys eyed
young bikini-clad girls parading in small groups.
   NASA speakers, broadcasting news from the Johnson Space Center
in Houston, hung alongside flags on hundreds of the motor homes
that mushroomed in the Mojave Desert overnight. Campers came from
as far away as Alaska and Connecticut. Big rigs from as away as
Kentucky brought truckers who spent the waiting swilling beer and
trading road yarns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
