<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     10-03 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Not Worried About Making Gaffes in Debate, But Says He'll
Be Nervous</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle, conceding he could make one of his celebrated gaffes at
Wednesday's debate with Lloyd Bentsen, says he'll be fighting off
butterflies but will be ready for the critical confrontation.
   ``I will be prepared. I'll be ready,'' he vowed during a
pre-debate interview with The Associated Press.
   Polls show many voters are skeptical about Quayle's
qualifications, and Quayle said he sees the debate as his ``golden
opportunity'' to resolve their doubts. But the Indiana senator
sought to play down the debate's impact on the election.
   ``It is important and the American people will be able to see
the two vice presidential nominees,'' he said. ``But when they go
in that voting booth they're going to be voting for a president of
the United States, and that's where their attention is going to be
and that's where the election is going to be decided.''
   Quayle will focus his attacks on Democrat Michael Dukakis rather
than the Texas senator, whom Quayle sees as more in tune with
Republicans than Democrats.
   ``The opponent for me is Michael Dukakis. He's the one that's
running for president. He's the one that if he would get in, I
think it'd be very difficult time for this country. The senator
from Texas is the vice presidential nominee, and my target and my
discussion and my focus that evening will be on the governor from
Massachusetts,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle will field the first question from the panel of
journalists at the Omaha, Neb., debate. He has been closeted with
top advisers at an undisclosed location in the Washington area
boning up on the issues and conducting mock debates with Bentsen's
stand-in, Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore.
   He admits to some nervousness, but says that should evaporate.
   ``I won't really get the butterflies going probably until
Wednesday. But they'll be there. There's no doubt,'' he said,
adding that he expects to be ``very much in control'' by the time
the debate begins.
   Quayle's embattled tenure as George Bush's running mate has been
marked by intense media scrutiny into his military service,
academic record and personal life. He has made a number of
high-profile gaffes _ telling reporters at one point ``I didn't
live in this century,'' among other things.
   ``The problem is that every time there's just one little miscue
it gets amplified as if this is the standard operating procedure,
which it's not,'' he said.
   But Quayle said he is not worried about making such ``miscues''
on Wednesday.
   ``The reason I'm not is because it's going to be questions and
answers. There's always that possibility, but I'm a very confident
person,'' he said. ``And the American people will be able to see me
in an unedited version for the first time since New Orleans, and
it's going to be a great opportunity for me.''
   GOP strategists have said that because Quayle has been portrayed
as a caricature and lightweight candidate he should benefit from
the low expecations for his performance. In essence, they suggest,
anything short of a major blunder will allow him to come away
looking good.
   ``I'm treating it as an opportunity to get up there, respond to
the questions, tell the American people where I want to lead this
country with George Bush ... and articulate a vision for the
future. So I don't look at it as low expectations, high
expectations. I'll leave that to others,'' Quayle said. ``What I
perceive this debate as is a golden opportunity for me to just be
myself.''
   Aides have said they want Quayle to tone down his boyish
exuberance so he will appear dignified and mature beside the
67-year-old Bentsen. They are said to be advising him to speak
slower and perhaps to rein in the wild gesticulating he sometimes
exhibits.
   But Quayle said he is not worried about looking less experienced
than Bentsen, who has 18 years in the Senate and speaks with a
dignified and patrician air.
   ``Age alone is not the only qualification for vice president or
president. You have to look at experience, you've got to look at
judgment, you've got to look if you can make a difference. I
believe I can make a difference ... like I have made a difference
in areas like job training and national defense,'' he said.
</TEXT>
