<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary-Youth     10-03 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Youth,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Independent Youth Group Says Gorbachev's Changes Will Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of the Soviet bloc's only
independent national youth group said the group would benefit from
the sweeping political changes engineered by Mikhail S. Gorbachev
in the Soviet Union last weekend.
   Gabor Fodor of the Union of Young Democrats, or FIDESZ, said the
strengthening of Gorbachev's power in the Soviet Union would boost
the reform wing of Hungary's Communist Party, which would in turn
give the youth group freer reign.
   ``They (the authorities) won't attack FIDESZ as hard and will
allow it to work,'' Fodor said Sunday.
   Gorbachev, the Soviet Communist Party leader, engineered a major
overhaul of the Soviet power structure in which he also assumed the
presidency, the top government.
   FIDESZ was established in March as an alternative to Hungary's
communist youth group, KISZ, which had lost thousands of members in
recent years. Communist officials initially branded FIDESZ illegal
and pressured it to cease its activities.
   Later, authorities softened their criticisms.
   About 700 people attended a two-day meeting over the weekend at
Budapest's Jurta theater to discuss the statutes of FIDESZ. Fodor,
a member of the group's six-man governing body, said the first
congress was a ``school of democracy for us.''
   He said the political weight of the organization is stronger
than its membership of about 1,500 indicates.
   ``The authorities are afraid of us because we are young and have
a clean slate,'' Fodor said.
   Janos Lukacs, a member of the ruling Communist Party Politburo,
told a Central Committee meeting last week that FIDESZ was
attempting to ``thwart dialogue'' and rejected what he called the
``aggressive stand'' of the group.
   Laszlo Koever, another founder of FIDESZ, countered that the
party leadership should be happy about the spread of grassroots
organizations and should recognize FIDESZ's readiness for dialogue.
   FIDESZ hopes to become fully legal under a new law of
association and assembly to be passed by parliament in December.
   Fodor said FIDESZ supports the reform wing of the Communist
Party, most closely identified with Politburo members Imre Pozsgay
and Reszo Nyers.
   On Sept. 12, Pozsgay, who was promoted to the Politburo in a
power shuffle in May, received a five-member delegation from FIDESZ.
   Fodor, who was a member of the delegation, said Pozsgay advised
the group not to press certain issues he said they could not
achieve progress on now, such as a re-evaluation of the 1956
anti-Communist revolt or a withdrawal of Soviet troops.
   However, Pozsgay did not suggest the group stop its activities,
Fodor said.
   FIDESZ is to hold a second congress in November to adopt a final
political program.
   Peter Veres, a spokesman for the group, said FIDESZ advocates a
multiparty system and decreased defense spending and would like to
field candidates for parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
