<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mandela     10-03 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mandela,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Tight-Lipped About Report Of Mandela's Impending
Freedom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has declined to
confirm or deny reports that President P.W. Botha promised to free
imprisoned black activist Nelson Mandela.
   In a joint communique released after Botha's meeting Saturday
with President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire, Mobutu said he was
``encouraged by the flexible approach'' taken by Botha regarding
Mandela.
   Mobutu was quoted Sunday in The Washington Post as saying, ``I
obtained from Botha a firm commitment that Mandela will soon be
freed without any conditions, that he will be allowed to return to
his home without any constraints.''
   A French news report also said President Botha told Mobutu he
would release Mandela.
   The report was at first denied by Roland Darroll, a Foreign
Ministry spokesman. Darroll said Mobutu, if quoted properly, was
overstating the gist of the summit discussion.
   However, a statement issued later by Foreign Minister Pik Botha
avoided contradicting Mobutu and left open the possibility
President Botha may indeed have made some type of promise.
   The statement said: ``The only agreed version of the discussion
concerning Mr. Mandela's release is contained in a joint communique
issued at the conclusion of the talks.''
   Mandela, 70, is considered the most popular leader among South
Africa's disenfranchised black majority. He has been jailed since
1962 and is serving a life term for sabotage and conspiracy to
overthrow the government.
   The Post quoted Mobutu as saying in a telephone interview that
Botha gave his ``solemn promise'' he will not send Mandela back to
prison once he recovers from tuberculosis in a Cape Town nursing
home.
   Botha frequently has said he would release Mandela in exchange
for Mandela's renunciation of violence. Mandela has refused to
repudiate the violent tactics of the outlawed African National
Congress, the main group fighting South Africa's government.
</TEXT>
