<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget     10-03 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Lauds Congress for Getting Down to Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan doesn't like everything he
sees in the new spending measures for 1989, but he says Congress
still deserves a pat on the back for getting its work done on time
this year.
   Reagan, who signed the last of 13 major spending bills on
Saturday _ the first day of fiscal 1989 _ said ``For the first time
in years, all the government's budgetary work is done.''
   ``The last of the government's 13 appropriations bill have been
delivered to me and I have signed them,'' he said in his weekly
radio address, just hours after Congress approved the money to keep
federal agencies operating.
   The usually rancorous budget process was eased this year because
Congress and the White House had cut deals that virtually
guaranteed approval of the spending bills even before Reagan
introduced his budget.
   It was the first time since 1976 that the House and Senate, both
controlled by Democrats, had passed the bills separately and on
time.
   ``Congress deserves a pat on the back for completing all 13
separate appropriations bills for a fiscal year,'' Reagan said.
``They worked long and hard to meet this year's deadline.'
   But Reagan criticized as minimal the amount of humanitarian aid
Congress granted the Contra rebels of Nicaragua, and chided
lawmakers for approving a ``protectionist'' textile bill that he
vetoed earlier in the week.
   Had Reagan signed all the bills before 12:01 a.m. EDT Saturday
as he had hoped, it would have been the first time since 1948 that
all appropriations bills were enacted before the start of the new
fiscal year.
   Last year Reagan signed a $600 billion catchall spending bill,
but he threatened to exercise his veto if a similar measure was put
on his desk this year.
   Reagan signed six appropriations bills Saturday, including a
$282 billion defense spending bill and a $14.3 billion foreign aid
measure. The other bills were signed earlier.
   The usual ferocity over spending priorities was tempered by the
desire of the administration and congressional Democrats to avoid a
repeat of last year's embarrassing budget finale.
   But it remained to be seen if the spending measures would fall
in line with strictures of the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law,
which requires a deficit of $146 billion for fiscal 1989.
   If the deficit should surpass $146 billion when it is measured
on Oct. 15, spending would have to be cut across-the-board by at
least $10 billion, an amount that would cause political pain for
lawmakers in an election year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
