<HEAD>Firefighters Nearly Contain 10,665-Acre Wildfire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with control of latest fire in
Angeles National Forest, CORRECT that Texas blaze is 80 percent
contained, sted 100 percent; picks up last graf, `Another arson
...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters nearly surrounded a
10,665-acre wildfire Sunday that burned one home in a four-day
rampage through the San Bernardino mountains and put out a small
blaze in the Angeles National Forest.
   ``All they're doing right now is mopping up,'' Ken Schmidt, a
California Department of Forestry fire dispatcher, said of the San
Bernadino blaze.
   The fire, dubbed the Texas blaze, was set by an arsonist
Wednesday on Texas Hill. Fanned by strong, dry Santa Ana winds, it
closed nearby Interstate 15 at times, and forced hundreds of
residents to flee their homes.
   One luxury ranch home burned, and six people were injured.
   The fire was 80 percent contained Sunday afternoon with full
containment expected by Monday evening. Full control was expected
by Thursday, said Forestry Department dispatcher Andrew Avila. The
force of 950 firefighters was being reduced.
   In the Angeles National Forest, three air tankers were sent up
to help about 200 U.S. Forest Service firefighters fight a fire two
miles south of the Little Rock Reservoir, said forest service
dispatcher John Grabowski.
   The fire, which started about 3 p.m., burned five acres in
steep, inaccessible terrain, 35 miles northeast of downtown Los
Angeles, he said. There were no reports of injuries and the blaze
was doused in about 30 minutes.
   Another arson fire in Millcreek near Yucaipa charred 135 acres
of heavy brush north of Highway 38, about 75 miles east of downtown
Los Angeles, authorities said. It was under control Sunday, but
three firefighters were injured in the process.
</TEXT>
