<DOCNO> AP881003-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Estonia     10-03 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Estonia,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Estonians Demand Control over Land and Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLINN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of members of an Estonian
nationalist group demanded greater autonomy for their republic and
charged the Kremlin with sapping Estonia's agricultural resources,
causing suffering and food shortages.
   Soviet authorities ``are to blame for our suffering here, the
lack of food here,'' delegate Albert Danielson told more than 3,000
members of the fledgling People's Front Sunday at the group's first
congress in Tallinn, the picturesque capital of this republic on
the Baltic Sea.
   Some speakers objected to what they called the Moscow's
``colonialist'' policy in which the government siphons off
Estonia's agricultural output and manufactured goods.
   ``We have been reduced to the level of slaves in a manor,''
farmer Enno Peets told the cheering delegates.
   The blue, black and white flag of the independent Estonian
republic that existed between the two world wars was brought to the
Town Hall stage during closing ceremonies Sunday that featured
singing of the nationalist song ``Fatherland.''
   The two-day conference opened Saturday with an address by
Estonia's Communist Party chief, Vajno Vyalyas, who greeted the
group in the name of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Official sanction for the meeting was an indication of the
changing attitudes of authorities, who until recently would have
jailed those espousing nationalist sentiments.
   The issue of ethnic relations is an important one for Gorbachev,
who is beset by unrest among the Soviet Union's more than 100
ethnic groups.
   Unrest has been particularly troublesome here and in two other
Baltic republics, Lithuania and Latvia, as well as in the southern
republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   The Soviet Union took over the Baltic republics under a 1939
agreement with Nazi Germany.
   The People's Front, formed in April, says it does not challenge
the authority of the Communist Party and is not interested in
breaking away from the Soviet Union. But some members say privately
that their ultimate goal is independence.
   The group claims membership of 60,000 of Estonia's 1.5 million
people.
   Vyalyas told a news conference that the republic's reforms ``are
always favorably accepted'' by Gorbachev, but that some proposals
go too far.
   ``Our wills and wishes have certain limits ... when fantasy goes
too far from reality we must stop these things,'' he told reporters.
   A clear sign of recent liberalization was the presence at the
congress of an Estonian nationalist who has spent much of his life
in labor camps for his views.
   Mart Niklus, released in July after serving eight years in his
most recent term, could be immediately spotted in a sea of business
suits by his dark gray and black striped camp uniform. The
54-year-old Niklus said some ideas expressed at the congress were
similar to those that sent him to the camps.
   The delegates passed nearly two dozen resolutions Sunday,
including one demanding that the 1939 agreement in which Estonia
became part of the Soviet Union be renounced.
   Another resolution urged the Estonian government and the
Communist Party to stop the flow of people of other nationalities
into the republic, where ethnic Estonians make up 60 percent of the
population.
   The resolutions have no legal force, but the Communist Party and
government already have endorsed many of the group's demands.
   In a speech Saturday, Vyalyas strongly backed demands to wrest
control from government ministries in Moscow over the republic's
economic and cultural affairs.
   Peets, in remarks that brought delegates to their feet, said he
had been a collective farmer for 34 years and was incensed that
Soviet leaders, including Gorbachev, propose renting state land to
farmers to spur productivity.
   He said his ancestors bought land when Estonia was independent
and that it was the state that should have been paying him rent.
   Without naming the People's Front specifically, Gorbachev and
the Kremlin leadership have expressed support for populist
movements and endorsed Estonian-proposed reforms for putting the
republic's economy in the hands of local managers and preserving
the native culture and language.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
