<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Urges Next President To Boost Spending For Non-Nuclear
Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bipartisan group of legislators says the
next president should increase spending for non-nuclear weapons and
meet military budgets by cancelling new weapons instead of cutting
training.
   ``We seem to believe that our `big guns' _ our strategic nuclear
missiles, our proposed space weapons _ will somehow save us from
all problems, all foes,'' the study released Saturday warned.
   The report was released by the Congressional Military Reform
Caucus, a seven-year-old bipartisan group of senators and House
members who have pushed for improvements in U.S. defenses. Reps.
Charles Bennett, D-Fla., and Tom Ridge, R-Pa., are chairmen of the
group.
   The study called for shifting money from long-range nuclear
weapons and Star Wars anti-missile research into conventional
forces, such as armor and tanks. No figures or force levels were
recommended.
</TEXT>
