<HEAD>More Than 1,000 Prisoners Released Under Amnesty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 prisoners, including
52 political offenders, were released today under a special amnesty
marking South Korea's National Foundation Day, a major national
holiday.
   The amnesty, however, was criticized by opposition parties, who
have been demanding the release of ``all political prisoners.''
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung said his party, along with other
opposition parties, would try to enact a special law to win the
release of other ``prisoners of conscience.''
   Kim, president of the main opposition group, the Party for Peace
and Democracy, gave no overall figures but said ``only one-tenth of
the prisoners of conscience'' were freed.
   Those freed today included Lee Tae-bok, a 38-year-old publisher
whose release was demanded by delegates attending the World
Congress of PEN here in early September. PEN is a London-based
world organization of literary figures.
   Lee was arrested in 1981 on charges of plotting to organize a
leftist underground movement and formenting a communist rebellion
through a publishing company he owned, PEN said.
   He was sentenced to life, which was later commuted to 20 years
in 1983.
   PEN sought the release of three other writers also in jail for
political reasons, but they were excluded in the amnesty.
   Government officials said the other writers, mentioned by PEN,
were directly involved in arson that resulted in deaths or
anti-South Korea activities in favor of communist North Korea.
</TEXT>
