<DOCNO> AP881003-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma     10-03 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Heed Government Order to Return to Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of civil servants and factory
workers heeded stern official warnings and returned to work today
as the military government appeared to have broken Burma's first
general strike in 26 years.
   Attendance figures were not available but some government
officials said about 80 percent of the workers were expected to be
back at their jobs rather than face dismissal or other punishment.
   ``Anyone who prevents, obstructs or interferes with workers
returning to work on Oct. 3 will be dealt with sternly,'' the
government warned in press and radio announcements Sunday. The
government had earlier warned that workers who did not report back
today could be fired.
   Opposition parties have urged strikers to stay away from their
jobs, hoping to pressure the current government, which was formed
following a Sept. 18 military coup lead by hardliner Gen. Saw Maung.
   Western diplomats say a general strike, which began Aug. 8,
appears to be the last effective weapon of pro-democracy forces in
Burma which since late July have tried to topple an entrenched
authoritarian system.
   ``We have to go back. We need money, our salaries, and the
special rations of rice and oil,'' one returning government clerk
said.
   Some government employes returned to work last week and drew
their September salaries on Sept. 30. They were also given special
rations of rice and edible oil _ both in short supply in Rangoon as
a result of the political upheaval and strike.
   The strike was the first mass labor agitation since strongman Ne
Win seized power in 1962 and instituted a military-backed,
one-party system which advocated socialism. Trade unions were
hastily formed after the Aug. 8 strike but without funds to support
striking workers or real organizational experience.
   Still, it appeared unlikely that the government machinery and
state-owned factories would regain momentum in the near future.
   Some civil servants were seen loitering near shops after signing
attendance registers in their offices. Asked why they were in the
streets instead of at their desks, one said: ``There is no work in
the office at the moment.''
   Virtually all of the country's more than 1,000 factories had
ceased operations because of the strike and are faced with lack of
spare parts and raw materials. A large number have been ransacked
by looters who have taken away or destroyed machinery and materials.
   A recent television report showed cigarette factories and a soap
factory in northern Rangoon totally destroyed. Looters of many
enterprises even stripped off tin roofs, which are selling at
inflated prices on the black market.
   Banks reopened but only to handle salaries and pensions of
government employes. Servicing of private accounts has not begun.
   Already in crisis when the anti-government movement began,
experts say Burma's economy is shattered.
   Burma's major aid donor, Japan, has stopped sending assistance
in recent weeks while West Germany and the United States have
frozen all but humanitarian aid in reaction to the ruthless
suppression of dissent by the authorities.
   By official count, about 425 persons have been killed since the
Sept. 18 coup. Western diplomats and opposition figures say
casualties were far higher, while several thousand are reliably
believe to have died as the military put down earlier
demonstrations.
   The government has promised general elections and allowed
political parties to register, thus formally breaking the monopoly
on power held by the Burma Socialist Program Party since 1962.
   However, this party, now renamed the National Unity Party, is
solidly entrenched and has a nation-wide organizational network.
The strongest of the opposition groups, the National League for
Democracy, does not even have a central office and virtually no
funds.
   The league has not yet announced whether it would contest the
elections.
   Ne Win resigned in July and was replaced by Sein Lwin, a
hard-line military man. He too resigned after massive
anti-government protests and was replaced by Maung Maung, a
civilian. Saw Maung ousted Maung Maung.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
