<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-KGB     10-03 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-KGB,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New KGB Chief Kryuchkov Is Secret Police Veteran</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Kremlin Shake-Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's newly appointed KGB chief is a
veteran of the secret police force, but unlike his predecessors he
was not given a seat on the Communist Party's ruling Politburo.
   Vladimir A. Kryuchkov, 64, was named KGB chief Saturday by the
Supreme Soviet shortly after the nation's parliament elected
Mikhail S. Gorbachev president.
   Kryuchkov replaced Viktor M. Chebrikov, a full Politburo member
since 1985 and KGB chief since 1982. Chebrikov remained on the
12-man Politburo, but he was shifted to responsibility for legal
affairs in a newly streamlined apparatus of the party's
policy-making Central Committee.
   The 300-member Central Committee also added Alexander V. Vlasov,
who as interior minister is in charge of uniformed police, to the
non-voting Politburo members. That move could enhance the status of
the uniformed police over the KGB in Gorbachev's new power
structure.
   Few details are known about Kryuchkov, who became deputy
chairman of the KGB in November 1978.
   In a four-paragraph biographical sketch, the official news
agency Tass said Kryuchkov, who holds the rank of an army general,
held senior posts on the security force for more than 20 years.
   Tass said he trained as a lawyer and worked several years as a
prosecutor. He also served on the Central Committee staff from 1959
to 1967.
</TEXT>
