<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico-68 1stLd-Writethru a0434 10-03 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-68, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0434,0801</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protests of 1968 Student Movement Reappear 20 Years Later</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 15-last, bgng, ``About 500 ...,' with 11 grafs to
UPDATE with Sunday's demonstration.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For two months in the summer of 1968 the
student movement gained momentum. ``Mex-i-co, Li-ber-ty!'' they
shouted. On Oct. 2, army machine guns silenced them, 10 days before
the city's Olympic Games.
   That night, the Night of Tlatelolco, was one of the bloodiest
ends to the protests that shook the world in 1968. Officials put
the death toll at 29, but students said hundreds were killed.
   The movement withered and seemed to die. But 20 years later,
festering discontent with a political system governed by a single
party reemerged in an unprecedented vote against the still-dominant
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
   ``At the very high price of lives, of blood, of prison for many
people, the '68 movement opened a democratic channel that kept
swelling until it overflowed in 1988,'' said Gilberto Guevara, one
of the principal leaders of the movement.
   In the July 1988 general elections, the opposition made
unprecedented gains in Parliament against the PRI, in power since
1929.
   Mexico in 1968 was still in its ``miracle years'' of economic
expansion. The authoritarian government dominated unions, campesino
organizations and the press.
   Despite the growth, ``distances between the classes also were
growing and that wasn't the heritage expected of a government that
said it came from a revolution,'' said Lorenzo Meyer, a leading
political analyst who teaches at Columbia University.
   On July 26, two student marches, one commemorating the Cuban
revolution, merged and headed toward Zocalo Plaza, site of the
National Palace and the Metropolitan Cathedral. Police blocked them
and the clash lasted several hours.
   In the weeks that followed, students battled police with
slingshot-launched rocks and Molotov cocktails. Police countered
with clubs, guns and fixed bayonets. Soldiers fired a bazooka to
break down the door of one high school.
   More than 250,000 students went on strike. Demands emerged _
elimination of riot police, firing of the police chief, freedom for
political prisoners and abolition of a law on political crimes.
   The students also called for fundamental changes _ democracy,
political participation, respect for basic freedoms _ and began
directly attacking President Gustavo Diaz Ordaz.
   The army occupied the National University, site of the 1968
Olympic Stadium, in violation of its autonomy. With the Oct. 12
opening of the Games approaching, it pulled out on Sept. 30.
   On Oct. 2, more than 6,000 students rallied in the Plaza of the
Three Cultures, known as Tlatelolco.
   As the demonstration began, there was the whump of a mortar and
red and green flares flashed.
   ``There was an infernal shooting,'' said Guevara, who was on a
fourth-floor balcony with other student leaders. ``Bullets,
bullets, bullets. Until suddenly a tank began to fire at the
building. The building caught fire.''
   The official death toll was 29. Students placed it at 200 to
300. Only two were soldiers. Many of the casualties were people in
apartments or stores.
   About 300 people, including Guevara, Alvarez and other leaders,
were jailed for 2{ years.
   The students never gained significant support from labor or
peasants. But when the problems they pointed out weren't corrected,
other sectors joined their criticisms.
   ``It's 20 years later, through the electoral process, when
everything explodes again, now without violence, but in a much more
massive way,'' Alvarez said. ``The great contribution of '68 was to
show that political activity was respectable and necessary.''
   Indeed, Sunday, more than 100,000 people chanting ``Don't Forget
Oct. 2'' filled the Plaza of the Three Cultures to commemorate the
student movement.
   The meeting also was a rally in support of the left, which has
numerous leaders from the '68 movement and has the backing of the
current National University student organization.
   Raising their arms in clenched fists or ``V'' for victory, they
yelled ``Death to the PRI.''
   ``This is a reencounter of the revolutionary, democratic,
progressive forces to tell (President-elect Carlos) Salinas de
Gortari and (President) Miguel de la Madrid that this nation is not
going to continue tolerating imposition,'' said Heberto Castillo, a
leader of teachers who supported the students in 1968.
   Castillo ran for president for the Mexican Socialist Party, then
withdrew in favor of Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
   ``'68 marked our lives and determined our destinies,'' Guevara
said. ``All those from '68 took on themselves an enormous burden of
responsibilities ... politics took deep roots in us ... in a sense
of commitment, commitment to construction of democracy, commitment
to the people, to the poor. `68 is almost a religion, an ethic.''
</TEXT>
