<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Election     10-03 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Election,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters in Veracruz Put Opposition, Ruling Party To Test</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-68, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>XALAPA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early returns in Veracruz state elections
showed Mexico's ruling party losing 15 of 203 mayoral seats in the
first local balloting since the opposition scored unprecedented
gains in July.
   The Excelsior news service said opposition parties, hoping to
continue inroads made against the ruling party in the July general
elections, claimed victories in more than 20 municipalities in the
Sunday vote.
   Official returns were scheduled to be made public on Oct. 9.
   Veracruz, a lush, productive state on the Gulf of Mexico, is a
key petroleum center with 3 million registered voters.
   In the 1985 municipal elections, the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, ran unopposed or against mostly token
opposition and won all but five of the 203 races. This time,
opposition parties fielded candidates in 177 races.
   State authorities said there were isolated incidents of violence
but did not give any details.
   Fraud was an issue in the July 6 general election, won by the
PRI's presidential candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari. He begins
his term Dec. 1, taking over from President Miguel de la Madrid.
   The opposition, made up of the leftist Democratic Front and the
rightist National Action Party, made its strongest gains ever in
the Chamber of Deputies and the Senate.
   The opposition claims the balloting was rigged by the PRI, in
power since 1929. The PRI denies the allegations.
</TEXT>
