<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-03 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar And Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar weakened against the Japanese yen on the
Tokyo foreign exchange market today while share prices slumped on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   After opening at 133.78 yen, the dollar moved in a narrow range
of 133.72-133.95 yen in light trading before closing at 133.90,
down 0.40 yen from last Friday's close of 134.30 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the most widely
followed barometer on the exchange, lost 154.60 points, or 0.56
percent, from last Saturday's close, to end the day's trading at
27,545.53.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange, where most
major shares are listed, slackened to 650 million shares compared
to 1 billion last Friday.
   Exchange dealers said the weaker dollar reflects the poor
showing of the currency in overseas markets.
   ``It opened lower than last week's level, but there were no new
incentives to push down the dollar further,'' said an exchange
dealer at a major Japanese bank.
   ``Insurance firms and institutional investors would start buying
the dollar if it declined to the mid- to lower 133-yen level
anyway, so I don't expect it to go down too much further than where
it is now for a while,'' said the trader, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Securities dealers attributed the sluggishness in share prices
and trading volume to a lack of fresh incentives in the market.
   ``The market environments are not necessarily poor,'' said a
dealer at a major securities firm, referring to stable exchange
rates and the strong performance of the world economy. ``But the
market had no direction this morning.''
   They also said news of Emperor Hirohito's weakening condition
last Saturday is affecting the market negatively.
   ``It's been a pattern that share prices slump every time we hear
about a worsening in the condition of His Majesty the emperor,''
said a broker at a major securities firm.
</TEXT>
