<DOCNO> AP881003-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-MemorialTranscript     10-03 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Memorial Transcript,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Statement Read By Astronauts in Tribute to Challenger Crew</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the tribute
by the Discovery astronauts Sunday to the crew of space shuttle
Challenger. NASA said the astronauts wrote the statement
themeselves and took turns reading it.
   David C. Hilmers:
   We'd like to take just a few moments today to share with you
some of the sights that we've been so privileged to view over the
past several days.
   As we watch along with you, many emotions well up in our hearts
_ joy for America's return to space, gratitude for our nation's
support through difficult times, thanksgiving for the safety of our
crew, reverence for those whose sacrifice made our journey possible.
   John M. Lounge:
   Gazing outside, we can understand why mankind has looked toward
the heavens with awe and wonder since the dawn of human existence.
We can comprehend why our countrymen have been driven to explore
the vast expanse of space, and we are convinced that this is the
road to the future, the road that Americans must travel if we are
to maintain the dream of our Constitution to secure the blessings
of liberty to ourselves and our posterity.
   Richard O. Covey:
   As we, the crew of Discovery, witness this earthly splendor from
America's spacecraft, less than 200 miles separates us from the
remainder of mankind. In a fraction of a second our words reach
your ears. But lest we ever forget that these few miles represent a
great gulf, that to ascend to this seemingly tranquil sea will
always be fraught with danger, let us remember the Challenger crew
whose voyage was so tragically short.
   George C. Nelson:
   With them, we shared a common purpose; with them we shared a
common goal. At this moment our place in the heavens makes us feel
closer to them than ever before.
   Those on the Challenger who had flown before and seen these
sights, they would know the meaning of our thoughts. Those who had
gone to view them for the first time, they would know why we set
forth.
   They were our fellow sojourners, they were our friends.
   Frederick H. Hauck:
   Today, up here where the blue sky turns to black, we can say at
long last to Dick, Mike, Judy, to Ron and El and to Christa and
Greg: Dear friends, we have resumed the journey that we promised to
continue for you. Dear friends, your loss has meant that we could
confidently begin anew. Dear friends, your spirit and your dreams
are still alive in our heart.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Editors: The seven Challenger crew members were Richard Scobee,
Michael Smith, Judith Resnik, Ronald McNair, Ellison Onizuka,
Christa McAuliffe and Gregory Jarvis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
