<DOCNO> AP881003-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0505EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MilanFashions     10-03 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Milan Fashions,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armani and Gigli Give a Young Start to Summer Collections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 spring-summer ready-to-wear shows
have gotten off to a young start with Giorgio Armani's trendy
Emporio girls and the romantic maidens of Romeo Gigli.
   Both designers used teen-age models Sunday to underline the
youthful look of their collections, but whereas Gigli's girls
looked like they walked out of a Degas ballet scene, the Armani
kids wore jeans and sweatshirts with slogans and designs printed
everywhere.
   The Emporio line was invented several years ago by Italian
ready-to-wear genius Giorgio Armani to satisfy the needs of the
younger set in both style and pocketbook. But it does not exclude
those who are merely young at heart.
   There are plenty of neat cotton pant suits, with small jackets
and loose trousers, long skirts, demure blouses and stand-by
blazers to enhance an older woman's town and country wardrobe too.
   Slogans and designs on clothing are the big thing among Italian
youth these days and Armani picked up on this trend. The phrase
``100 Percent Summer'' can be read on T-shirts, blouses and even
earrings.
   Animals are a favorite design with llamas and elephants
stitched, painted or pinned on shirts, pants and jackets.
   The choice of animals reflects the folklore inspiration of the
collection. Armani draws on India for his sari-type skirts,
super-loose pants and glittery beaded jackets, while from Peru he
borrows geometric designs and bright colors, as well as the popular
Indian flat-topped bowler hat.
   Bright shades always seem a strain for Armani, used to the muted
tones of his native industrial Milan, and when not involved in
folklore fantasy he reverts to his standard beiges, grays and navy
blues.
   Except for a few micro-mini tube dresses and some very short
shorts, Armani pulls his hemlines right down to the ankle for next
summer.
   Whereas the lengthened hemline at Armani marks a change from
last season's mini, the look at Gigli is long and drab as per usual.
   His jackets in cotton, jersey or linen had that old thrift-shop
look, oversized, with maddeningly long sleeves that always looked
like they needed hemming.
   Pants were trim and vaguely tailored, the most modern item in
the collection.
   The newest look at Gigli's is the knot, with which he tied
together hemlines, bodices and waistlines. Aside from enhancing the
Orphan Annie look of the collection with make-do mending, the Gigli
knot could become the latest rage in geometric puzzles. In fact it
takes either a genius or a good set of instructions to figure out
where and how to tie them.
   The five day semi-annual Milan ready-to-wear shows will end
Thursday, and will include the new spring-summer collections of
such fashion favorites as Ferre, Krizia, Versace and Missoni in
addition to Italy's ``numero uno,'' Armani.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
