<HEAD>Duchess Overcomes Fear of Reptiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOWNSVILLE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Duchess of York overcame her
much-publicized fear of reptiles long enough to linger today at a
pool full of dangerous sea snakes.
   ``I dont want to leave because I am fascinated by these
creatures,'' the former Sarah Ferguson told her husband, Prince
Andrew, at the Townsvilles Great Barrier Reef Aquatic Wonderland
soon after the Royal couple started their four-day tour of
Queensland state.
   The Duchess grimaced as she tentatively touched a live sea
cucumber, a marine inhabitant of tropical waters, in a special open
``touch'' tank at the multi-million-dollar tourist attraction.
   The royal couple were greeted by sweltering tropical heat when
they touched down at Townsvilles Airport today after spending four
days in Sydney on their bicentennial tour.
   Sarah and Andrew will fly to the remote towns of Cloncurry and
Mount Isa on Tuesday before going to Brisbane Wednesday.
