<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Peru-USEmbassy     10-03 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-US Embassy,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Reportedly Foil U.S. Embassy Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police thwarted a planned guerrilla attack on
the U.S. Embassy, arresting two armed men while the others fled,
according to a newspaper report.
   Two guerrillas armed with guns and explosives were detained
outside the heavily guarded downtown embassy at about noon
Saturday, Deputy Interior Minister Agustin Mantilla said. He was
quoted Sunday in the daily El Comercio, Peru's leading newspaper.
   There were no reported injuries during the arrests.
   Mantilla, head of Peru's anti-subversion effort, would not
identify the guerrilla group involved. The embassy and its
installations have been the targets of more than a dozen attacks in
the past decade by leftist guerrillas, who accuse the United States
of conducting imperialistic policies toward Peru.
   Mantilla told El Comercio the guerrillas planned to attack the
walled, half-block embassy complex with several accomplices who
escaped. The newspaper did not provide further details.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Charles Loveridge told The Associated
Press that embassy security staff were unaware of the incident. He
said the embassy was investigating the report.
   Loveridge said U.S. government installations are considered at
high risk and are heavily guarded with U.S. Marines, privately
hired security staff and Peruvian police guards.
   In the last attack against the embassy, rebels of the pro-Cuban
Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement in June fired mortar rounds at
U.S. Ambassador Alexander Watson's residence compound, damaging the
roof but causing no injuries.
   The Maoist Shining Path guerrilla organization also has been
linked to attacks against U.S. government installations.
</TEXT>
