<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpaceLetter     10-03 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Letter,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brooklyn Teen-Ager Proud His Letter Read From Shuttle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Brooklyn teen-ager says he'll do his homework
``a little more often'' now that space shuttle Discovery's
commander has read one of his assignments in space.
   Philip J. Morgan wrote a letter to shuttle commander Frederick
H. Hauck last May as an assignment for his eighth-grade science
class at St. Mark's Catholic School.
   ``I am a worried 14-year-old that is worried about the future,''
he wrote. ``I feel that some of America's future is riding on you
and your crew's shoulders. I give you all the inspiration I can
give you because your ride this fall means so much to me.''
   Hauck interrupted the crew's schedule Saturday to read the
letter. He said he hoped it would show young people that ``we are
back on track and we have a lot of technological benefits that will
come in the future.''
   Interviewed Sunday after he came in from playing football with
friends, Morgan, known as ``P.J.,'' said Hauck had eased his fears
``a lot,'' but he is still worried ``because there are always
risks'' in any space mission.
   Morgan's teacher, John D. Santoro, said he gave the assignment
as a way of introducing current events into the science class. Of
85 letters, Morgan's was the only one to draw such a personal
response, Santoro said. Other students received autographed
pictures from the astronauts they wrote.
   ``I thought the fact they had gotten pictures was great,''
Santoro said. ``But when he read the letter yesterday _ this was
unreal.''
   Hauck called Morgan last week and said he might read the letter
from space.
   ``I didn't think he'd really read it. I didn't think there would
be enough time,'' the youngster said.
   Morgan said he was surprised at the attention his letter has
attracted. ``It was meant as a homework assignment. I didn't even
imagine it would go this far.''
</TEXT>
