<DOCNO> AP881003-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0637EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VermontScandal     10-03 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vermont Scandal,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Official at Center of Rare Vermont Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RUTLAND, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concern about official wrongdoing in Vermont
was once so minimal that from the 1930s to the 1960s a Statehouse
window was kept open for officials and others who'd forgotten their
keys.
   Then came the Bennington school scandal.
   ``As far as I can tell, never in the state's history has there
been something of magnitude,'' said state archivist Gregory
Sanford. ``The cases have always involved an individual, not a
network.''
   So far it has led to four convictions, including the school
district's treasurer and a school board member, numerous
resignations and the decertification of six educators.
   At the center is George Sleeman, who served for 13 years as
superintendent of the Southwest Vermont Supervisory Union, the
state's largest school union.
   He faces four trials, the first of which began last week. In
all, he is accused of 37 counts of embezzlement and perjury.
   His reign is compared to those of the old ward bosses in big
cities outside Vermont, who managed to get dead people to vote on
Election Day. Sleeman is accused of running classes that never met
and had at least one dead person as a student.
   ``George Sleeman took money for his own purposes, money that was
in his care because he had the trust of the people who put him in
that position; money that was intended to go to help in the
education of children,'' state prosecutor David Suntag told jurors
as Sleeman went on trial for nine of 37 counts of embezzlement and
perjury.
   The issue in the first trial is whether Sleeman improperly paid
himself $8,000 from school funds for increased rent on an office.
   Sleeman's lawyer, William Sessions, said Sleeman believed he was
authorized to receive the increased rent. He blamed the problems on
poor bookkeeping.
   ``There were no rules, no regulations, nothing on how accounting
should be,'' Sessions said as he described one of the accounts.
   Sleeman, suspended in 1985, has refused comment on any of the
charges against him.
   But the rent checks form a small part of the school scandal,
which began June 7, 1984, with the announcement the school system
had a deficit of $1.7 million.
   As auditors and investigators began looking into the deficit,
offices were burglarized and financial records disappeared.
   A break-in at Sleeman's office in which crucial records were
taken ``was not a burglary, but an attempt to make us believe it
was a burglary,'' a Bennington police detective said.
   Auditors said Sleeman ran a ``shell game,'' using about 140 bank
accounts for a school system that typically would have 10.
   The alleged corruption included bidding practices, which some
said were rigged to favor Sleeman's friends, and the food service
program.
   The food service program's former director, Donat Ratelle, said
he wrote checks to Sleeman because he told him to.
   ``You don't question the superintendent,'' Ratelle said.
   Asked why, he said, ``You don't know George Sleeman.''
   ``George searched for power, to be a ward boss,'' said Richard
Chapman, who served as interim superintendent following Sleeman's
suspension.
   Sleeman oversaw 4,400 students, 350 teachers, two dozen
administrators and at annual budget of $20 million.
   ``In this community, what George said, it came as authority. If
you didn't agree with him, he could do something to you,'' Chapman
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
