<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     10-03 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased in early European trading today
and foreign currency traders said the market had calmed following
the dollar's sell off Friday in New York.
   Gold prices barely moved.
   The dollar tumbled Friday following U.S. Federal Reserve
Governor Martha Seger's warning against a higher currency, and on a
sharp drop in oil prices.
   Traders in Frankfurt, West Germany, said they were disappointed
that Friday's surge of activity did not continue on Monday.
   ``We were really optimistic this morning, and we thought the
movement would continue with profit-taking, but it has fizzled out
again,'' said one dealer at a West German bank.
   ``There is surprisingly little interest among traders and
(commercial) customers. It looks as if we'll have the same story as
last week, but on a slightly lower level.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 133.90. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 133.80 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.8687 West German marks, down from 1.8725
   _1.5840 Swiss francs, up from 1.5830
   _6.3580 French francs, down from 6.3700
   _2.1057 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1185
   _1,392.10 Italian lire, down from 1,396.50
   _1.2137 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2171
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6937, slightly more
expensive for buyers than late Friday's $1.6905.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $393.25 an ounce, down
from $394.45 bid late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $394.20.
   ``This market has the look of no interest about it,'' said the
head of bullion at one London trading firm. ``There is very little
activity.''
   In Zurich, the bid price was $396.00, unchanged from late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.31 to close at a bid $397.91.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.11 an ounce,
little changed from Friday's $6.14.
</TEXT>
