<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-GenerosoPope     10-03 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Generoso Pope,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Enquirer Owner Generoso Pope Jr. Dead at 61</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Chrnaz CQ in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANTANA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Generoso Pope Jr., who built an empire on
The National Enquirer's splashy brand of journalism, was remembered
fondly by employees after his death of a heart attack at his
beachfront home. He was 61
   ``He was the paper,'' Enquirer Managing Editor Nat Chrnaz said.
``It's shattering. It really is.''
   Pope was taken to John F. Kennedy Medical Center on Sunday,
where he was pronounced dead, said hospital spokesman Larry
Schwingle.
   Pope had a fortune estimated at more than $150 million by Forbes
magazine.
   Known as a tough boss, he pushed his highly paid reporters _
many from Britain's Fleet Street _ to keep cranking out ``what
inquiring minds want to know.''
   ``He was not a person who was isolated in an ivory tower,'' said
Enquirer reporter Roger Capettini. ``The man rarely, if ever, took
vacations. He was involved in every aspect of the Enquirer. I think
Mr. Pope was a creative genius.
   ``It's a very sad occasion,'' Capettini said. ``He truly was
loved by his employees. He demanded a lot of us, but he rewarded
and compensated us.''
   While the Enquirer flourished, its style has many critics, and
several celebrities have sued the publication. Among them were
Carol Burnett, who sued for libel in 1981 and won $800,000; Frank
Sinatra, Cary Grant, and actress Shirley Jones all settled out of
court.
   Pope was a native of New York City and his father was the
founder of the Italian-language daily, Il Progresso.
   The younger Pope graduated from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology at 19 and at age 25 bought the struggling New York
Enquirer with $75,000 he borrowed.
   ``I took over, then discovered the paper was about a week away
from bankruptcy,'' Pope said in a December 1985 interview. ``There
was just one employee and me. It took six years before we finally
broke even in 1958.''
   By changing the paper's format and adopting its glitzy, style,
he turned it into the best-read supermarket tabloid with a
circulation of 4.5 million.
   Pope said the paper evolved when ``I discovered that gore would
sell _ gory pictures, gory stories.'' He later shifted the focus
towards celebrity news and gossip, health tips and the bizarre. His
more sensational Weekly World News has another 1.1 million readers.
   In 1971, Pope brought his newspaper to Lantana, a coastal town
of 10,000 about nine miles south of Palm Beach. He put up and
decorated a 126-foot fir tree, a Christmas tradition ever since.
The tree draws thousands of people each year.
   Pope, Lantana's largest employer, was known for his generosity
to the community. He recently endowed the town with a rescue
vehicle, and was on the board of trustees for the hospital where he
died.
   Pope, who has six children, was married three times. His widow,
and wife of 29 years, is Lois Pope.
   A funeral Mass was scheduled Wednesday morning at Holy Spirit
Catholic Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
