<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nepal-JapaneseClimber     10-03 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nepal-Japanese Climber,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese, Sherpa Swept Away By Avalanche</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese climber and a Sherpa guide
were swept to their deaths last week by an avalanche, the Nepalese
Tourism Ministry said today.
   Akihiko Mori, 43, of Tokyo and Ang Dawa Sherpa, 27, were
descending from 5,900 meters on Mount Annapurna I last Thursday
after having carried up food supplies and tents when the accident
occurred, the ministry reported.
   The two were about 30 minutes from their expedition's Camp One
when they were swept away by the avalanche, the ministry said.
   It said another Japanese, Tsuyoshi Ono, 43, from Saitama
prefecture near Tokyo was also with the two alpinists and escaped
injury but had to spend the night in the snow.
   Ono managed to reach one of the expedition's other tents Friday
morning to report the incident.
   The remaining seven members of the Japanese expedition and their
Nepalese staff started a search that continued until Saturday, but
the two missing mountaineers could not be found, the ministry said.
   Mori was the leader of the expedition tackling the 26,538-foot
Himalayan peak. The expedition reportedly abandoned its attempt
Sunday.
   It was the third fatal accident in the Nepalese Himalayas in the
current post-monsoon climbing season, which lasts from September to
November.
   Last month a Nepalese member of a British expedition died on
Mount Annapurna III and another Nepalese accompanying a Spanish
expedition died on Mount Everest, the world's highest peak.
</TEXT>
