<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-Strauss 2ndLd-Writethru a0510 10-03 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Strauss, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0510,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bavarian Leader Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with liver function collapse.
EDITS to conform. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bavarian Gov. Franz Josef Strauss, a
leading ultra-conservative, died today after suffering a heart
attack that doctors said was likely caused by other internal
problems, the state government said.
   He was 73.
   The Bavarian government said in a statement released to the news
media that Strauss died at 11:45 a.m. (6:45 a.m. EDT) in a hospital
in the city of Regensburg.
   Strauss, one of West Germany's most colorful politicians who
helped organize the country after World War II and served in its
first Parliament, collapsed during a hunting trip Saturday.
   Strauss' daughter Monika and sons Franz-Georg and Max-Josef
joined political associates who gathered at Regensburg's Brothers
of Charity hospital, about 65 miles northeast of Munich, capital of
Bavaria.
   Dr. Rolf Manz, head of the medical team that had cared for the
governor, said Strauss had suffered a mild heart attack brought on
by an undetermined internal disorder.
   Strauss' thick Bavarian accent, coupled with his sharp tongue,
made the outspoken, stocky state governor one of West Germany's
most recognized and controversial politicians.
   He was the head of the Christian Social Union, the Bavarian
sister party of the nationally dominant Christian Democrats, which
are headed by West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   He served in a number of Cabinet posts, including minister of
defense and minister of finance. He left Parliament in 1978 when he
was elected Governor of Bavaria.
   In recent years, the outspoken Strauss often used his base in
Bavaria to steal the show from Kohl.
   In 1949, the year West Germany was founded, Strauss was elected
to the federal Parliament controlled by the conservatives under the
country's first Chancellor, Konrad Adenauer.
   His wife, Marianne, died in a 1984 automobile accident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
