<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CadetAmputee     10-03 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cadet Amputee,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cadet, Expelled After Amputation, Disappointed But Resigned To
Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old man expelled from the Air Force
Academy because he lost part of his leg in an auto accident says he
believes the decision was a mistake, but now just wants to ``get on
with my life.''
   Dan Korslund lost his right leg 8 inches below the knee after
the June accident near the academy in Colorado. He walks with the
aid of a cane, and will soon be fitted with a prosthesis.
   Air Force Secretary Edward ``Pete'' Aldridge refused last week
to waive a Pentagon rule that calls for ``disenrollment'' of any
service academy cadet who loses all or part of a limb.
   Korslund, a cadet third class who would have been a sophomore
this year, said he didn't blame Aldridge or the Air Force, but
added that the decision was a disappointment because ``I felt I
should have had the chance to prove to them that I could have done
it.''
   He said he would try to return to the academy if there was an
opportunity to appeal Aldridge's decision, ``but I'm not going to
hold my breath. Now I just want to get on with my life.''
   Korslund said he intends to attend college and major in biology,
branching off into sports medicine.
   Sens. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., and William Armstrong, R-Colo.,
had pressured Aldridge to keep Korslund in the academy. Armstrong
said he would ask President Reagan on Tuesday to consider the case.
   Korslund, who was discharged from the Seattle Veterans
Administration Hospital on Friday, is living with his mother in
Tacoma.
</TEXT>
