<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Chad-Libya 1stLd-Writethru a0526 10-03 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chad-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chad, Libya Restore Diplomatic Relations After Years Of Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with details from joint statement,
reax from France. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya and Chad, after years of bitter fighting,
announced today they have restored diplomatic relations and said
they will settle their territorial dispute in a responsible and
understanding manner.
   In a statement carried by the Libyan news agency JANA, which
said it was issued simultaneously in the capitals of Libya, Chad
and Togo, the two countries said they intended to ``establish
relations of good neighborliness and cooperation.''
   Diplomats from Togo were reportedly instumental in bringing
together Libya's Col. Moammar Gadhafi and President Hissene Habre
of Chad, long bitter enemies, to restore ties.
   In the statement, Chad and Libya said they would respect the
Sept. 11, 1987, cease-fire that ended their fighting in the
mountainous deserts of northern Chad and ``deal with their regional
disagreement in a peaceful way.''
   By the end of October, Chad will send an ambassador to Tripoli
and Libya will open a ``People's Bureau'' _ as it calls its
embassies _ in N'Djamena, the statement said.
   Habre ousted a Libyan-backed government in 1982 but only
succeeded in driving Libyan troops out of most of the country early
last year, in a series of lightning attacks by Chadian soldiers in
light trucks.
   The remaining territorial dispute concerns the Aouzou Strip, a
45,000-square mile band of land thought to be rich in uranium,
along the border between the two countries. Libya continues to
occupy the strip, which it contends was ceded by France to Italy in
1941 before Chad and Libya became independent.
   Libya had annexed the territory in 1973.
   Habre's government received extensive French and American
military aid for his battle with Libya. France sent several
thousand troops, equipped with anti-aircraft weapons and Jaguar and
Mirage warplanes to deter Libyan attacks on southern Chad,
especially N'Djamena.
   In Paris, the French government said in a statement it ``is
pleased by this decision which will open an era of peace between
the two countries.''
   Defense Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement told reporters that
France would consult with Chad before withdrawing the French force,
now down to about 1,200 men. He noted that the French presence ``is
not there to stay forever,'' and could be reinforced very quickly
from French bases in the neighboring Central African Republic in
case of renewed threat.
   Chad has been wracked by war almost continuously since it became
independent from France in 1960. When former rebel leader Goukouni
Oueddei was president from 1980 to 1982, he invited the Libyans
into the country, and they sent 7,000 men. Gadhafi announced plans
to merge the two countries.
   Habre ousted Goukouni in 1982, sending him fleeing to the north.
The following year Goukouni started a military drive on N'Djamena.
After Libyan troops became directly involved, France sent in an
intervention force and halted the advance.
   President Francois Mitterrand of France and Gadhafi signed a
mutual troop withdrawal agreement in late 1984 and the French
pulled out. Gadhafi reneged, to Mitterrand's embarrassment, and the
French sent their troops back to Chad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
