<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Candidate-TWAFlap     10-03 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidate-TWA Flap,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colorado Democrats Disavow Congressional Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional candidate accused of linking an
airline and the AIDS epidemic became a man without a party when the
Colorado Democratic Party executive committee disowned him.
   Party officials voted 33-1 on Sunday to deny John Mitchell the
use of the name Democrat in his campaign after he failed to respond
to allegations stemming from a lawsuit filed against him by Trans
World Airlines.
   The airline has accused Mitchell, a Colorado Springs teacher and
real estate agent, of distributing posters connecting TWA with AIDS.
   ``The party needed to deal with this openly. Don't flinch, don't
blush, just do business, and I think that's what we've done here,''
said state Democratic Party Chairman Buie Seawell.
   Mitchell did not attend Sunday's meeting and has not been
available to talk with state party officials since the lawsuit was
filed Sept. 19 in U.S. District Court at Denver. He failed to
return calls to his home telephone answering recorder made Sunday
night by The Associated Press.
   According to TWA's lawsuit, which seeks $500,000 in damages,
Mitchell sent a poster to the airline's New York offices in July
saying ``Thousands of these have been sent around the country. Our
staff is working on a new poster. They will continue to be sent
until TWA corrects the hurt you have caused-cost me.''
   The posters, according to the lawsuit, said ``AIDS is Spread
Through TWA,'' ``Today's TWA Means AIDS'' and ``TWA: Travel With
AIDS.''
   Mitchell was unopposed for the nomination to run against
incumbent Republican Rep. Joel Hefley in a GOP-dominated district
which encompasses the Colorado Springs area. It was his first try
at political office.
   The 5th District Democratic Committee on Sunday issued a
complaint against Mitchell that later was accepted by the executive
committee and resulted in the party's disavowal of his candidacy.
   The complaint said Mitchell's failure to respond to the
controversy has hurt the campaigns of other Democratic candidates
in the district.
   The party's vote won't affect the ballot itself, which already
has been printed. Only a court order could have gotten Mitchell's
name off the ballot. Party officials said they preferred not to
take such a measure.
   Rick Daily, the party's attorney, said the party wasn't making a
judgment on TWA's allegations against Mitchell but was moving
against him only ``because of Mr. Mitchell's failure to act like a
responsible candidate and step forward and deal with those issues.''
   Mitchell's squabble with TWA apparently began in 1983 when he
took the airline to small claims court in two separate cases in
Colorado Springs to recover ``frequent flyer'' benefits he believed
he deserved.
   Mitchell won one case but lost the second one. Shortly
afterward, TWA said it received posters and stickers anonymously
connecting the airline with AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
