<HEAD>Police Arrest Armed Man Who Stormed Moroccan Consulate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROTTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armed man stormed the Moroccan
consulate today and threatened staff in the building before
surrendering to police, authorities said.
   No injuries were reported in the incident, but several staff
members were still hiding in the building, according to police
spokesman Hans Stoop.
   The man rushed the consulate in the city's port district and
surrendered after negotiating with police shortly afterward, Stoop
said.
   He had been carrying a firearm and used it to threaten consulate
staff, several of whom had fled the building, Stoop said.
   However, an undetermined number of workers had fled upstairs,
Stoop said.
   Heavily armed police entered the consulate to make sure they
were safe and there were no other attackers, he added.
   It was not immediately clear what the man's motives or his
nationality were, Stoop said. The weapon was also not immediately
identified.
   There have been occasional reports of friction among the
180,000-member Moroccan guest worker community in the Netherlands
and their government.
