<DOCNO> AP881003-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Lotteries     10-03 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Lotteries,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Decide Lottery Ad Issue in Minnesota Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether the federal government may continue to bar newspapers from
carrying advertisements for privately run lotteries and other games
of chance.
   The justices said they will study a Minnesota Newspaper
Association challenge to a postal law effectively prohibiting such
advertising.
   The court also said it will judge the validity of the postal
law's effective ban on newspapers publishing lists of lottery
winners.
   A federal judge in Minnesota last Dec. 31 upheld the ban on
newspaper advertising but struck down as unconstitutional the ban
on publishing lists of lottery winners.
   The Minnesota newspapers group's appeal said the ban on
advertising violates free-speech rights.
   In a separate appeal, Justice Department lawyers asked the high
court to reinstate the ban on publishing lists of lottery winners.
   Federal postal law contains an exemption for a state-conducted
lottery published by a newspaper in that state or in an adjacent
state.
   The controvery acted on today focuses mainly on lotteries and
other gaming, such as bingo and raffles, sponsored by non-profit,
charitable organizations and others.
   Lawyers for the Minnesota newspapers said, ``The revenue
generated by charitable gaming is very sustantial. In Minnesota
alone it appears to exceed $200 million per year.''
   Postal laws prohibit use of the mails to disseminate information
about any lottery not run by a state. Since nearly all newspapers
rely on the mail for at least a portion of their distribution, the
postal laws apply to them.
   U.S. District Judge Paul A. Magnuson upheld the ban on lottery
advertisements even though he acknowledged that the ads are a
constitutionally protected form of commercial speech.
   He said Congress has two substantial interests in the ban:
preserving the states' power to prohibit or limit gambling within
their borders and restricting the interstate growth of private
lotteries to reduce the threat of organized criminal involvement.
   But Magnuson ruled that newspapers cannot be barred from running
lists of private lottery winners unless such lists are found in
advertisements.
   ``Lists of prizes awarded do not fit the definition of
commercial speech. A prize list also has value as news,'' the judge
said.
   The cases are Minnesota Newspaper Association vs. Postmaster
General, 87-1943, and Frank vs. Minnesota Newspaper Association,
87-1956.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
