<DOCNO> AP881003-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Pipeline     10-03 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Pipeline,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Weigh Pipeline Fee Case from Oklahoma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case that could bear
on a wide range of federal fees and taxes, today agreed to judge
the validity of a 1986 federal law imposing ``user fees'' on
pipeline companies.
   The justices said they will hear a Reagan administration
challenge to an Oklahoma court ruling that struck down the law. A
pipeline company that transports hazardous liquids had attacked the
law as unconstitutional.
   Administration lawyers said a number of recently enacted user
fees could be affected by the case.
   They cited the authority of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission to
assess nuclear power plants for licensing and inspection and the
authority of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission to impose
fees to finance its regulatory programs.
   Directly involved in the case acted on today are fees _ or taxes
_ imposed on pipeline companies that transport hazardous waste and
natural gas.
   The government is seeking to collect about $8.5 million a year
from the companies to pay for federal pipeline safety programs run
by the Department of Transportation.
   At issue is whether the assessments are fees or taxes and
whether the law grants the secretary of transportation too much
discretion in determining how much money the companies must pay.
   U.S. Magistrate John Leo Wagner in Tulsa, Okla., ruled last year
that the assessments are taxes, and therefore the law improperly
gives the transportation secretary power to set tax rates.
   ``Where no request for an agency's services is made and no
specific benefit is conferred upon the one being assessed, the
assessment cannot be labeled a fee,'' Wagner said.
   He added that the law gives the secretary so much discretion
that ``the amount to be assessed each company could be almost any
figure from zero to 100 percent of the entire'' cost of the safety
program.
   The assessments may be based on how many miles of pipeline a
company operates, the quantity of natural gas or liquid and how far
it is shipped, or the gross revenue of the company.
   The law was challenged by Mid-America Pipeline Co., assessed
$53,000 in 1986.
   Wagner said that depending on what formula the transportation
department chose, Mid-America could be required to pay from 5
percent to 28.3 percent of the $8.5 million total to be collected.
   The case is Burnley vs. Mid-America Pipeline, 87-2098.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
