<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-FSLIC,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Hear Case on Failing Illinois Savings and Loan
Association</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to study the
power of federal courts to decide some disputes in which a federal
agency takes charge of a failing state-chartered financial
institution.
   The justices said they will hear a Reagan administration
challenge to a ruling from Illinois limiting federal court
jurisdiction in cases involving the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp. (FSLIC).
   Justice Department lawyers said the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruling could have serious consequences for the FSLIC, under
financial strains to insure deposits in failing thrift institutions.
   The FSLIC and its parent agency, the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board, reported in September that they had added more than $12
billion in outstanding debt since mid-August while shutting down,
merging or finding new owners for 46 insolvent savings insitutions.
   At issue in the case acted on today was whether the FSLIC can
sue in federal court when it seeks to collect money, potentially
hundreds of millions of dollars, allegedly owed to the failing
thrift institutions.
   The 7th Circuit court ruled in November 1987 that the federal
courts lack authority when the alleged violations of federal law
are subsidiary to related allegations of state law violations.
  peals courts elsewhere have given broader
authority to federal courts to decide such suits.
   Justice Department lawyers said the 7th Circuit court ruling
could undermine efforts by the FSLIC to sue those who owe money to
failing savings and loan institutions.
   For example, the government's appeal said, it is now too late to
sue the Manning directors in Illinois state courts because of that
state's statute of limitations.
   The former directors urged the Supreme Court to reject the
appeal.
   The case is FSLIC vs. Ticktin, 87-1865.
</TEXT>
