<HEAD>Two Toddlers Killed, Father Critically Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUMMING, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two toddlers died of severe head injuries
and their father was found dazed and seriously injured in a roadway
minutes after a family quarrel.
   The three all received ``blunt trauma injuries'' early Saturday
while walking on a county road about half a mile from their home,
said Sheriff Wesley Walraven. Authorities had no suspects but said
it was unlikely that they had been hit by a car.
   Brandon Miles Frix, 2, was dead at the scene; his 3-year-old
brother, Jarrett, died later at an Atlanta hospital.
   The boys and their father, 27-year-old Charles A. Frix, left
their home on foot about 3:50 a.m. Saturday after the father and
his wife apparently quarreled, Walraven said. A passing motorist
found them lying in the road minutes later.
   Walraven said investigators have not found any evidence the
three were struck by a car. He declined to comment on other
possible causes until investigators are able to interview the
father.
   Michael Thomason, a volunteer firefighter, said Frix seemed
dazed and told rescue workers ``it don't matter'' when they asked
whether he and his sons has been hit by a car.
   ``He said, `Lord Jesus, take my hand, for I have sinned' _
that's all we could get out of him,'' Thomason said.
   Frix, who suffered head injuries, was listed in serious but
stable condition Sunday.
   There apparently were no witnesses, the sheriff said. Forsyth
Sheriff's Department Detective David Bennett said authorities
``just honest to God do not know how it happened.''
   The boys' mother told police she did not know what happened on
the road, Bennett said.
