<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Mak     10-03 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Mak,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Conviction in Chinatown Massacre Upheld</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kwan Fai Mak, convicted of 13 killings in what
Seattle prosecutors called the ``largest robbery-related mass
murder in American history,'' lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court let stand rulings that Mak received a fair trial and
properly was sentenced to death.
   Mak and Benjamin Ng were convicted of murdering 13 patrons of a
Chinatown gambling club in Seattle during a Feb. 18, 1983 robbery.
   Prosecutors said Mak planned and supervised the ``Wah Mee Club
massacre,'' and that one of his objectives was to leave no
witnesses.
   All patrons and employees present in the club during the robbery
were bound and, in turn, shot in the head from close range. One
patron, 61-year-old Wai Chin, survived to testify against Mak and
Ng.
   The Washington Supreme Court, in upholding Mak's conviction and
death sentence, said his crime ``set a new gauge for cowardly
murder in this state.''
   Mak, who emigrated from Hong Kong to Seattle when he was 15, was
21 when the crime was committed.
   His appeal contended that the state Supreme Court wrongly failed
to order an evidentiary hearing to determine whether Mak was denied
effective legal help.
   The case is Mak vs. Washington, 88-5114.
