<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Skyscraper     10-03 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Skyscraper,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mnhattan Developer Ordered to Remove Top Floors Loses Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York City developer ordered to remove
the top 12 floors of a 31-story condominium building in Manhattan's
fashionable upper East Side lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that the
building's height must be reduced even if construction was
permitted through a mistake by city officials.
   The developer, Parkview Associates, said it will lose more than
$9 million if forced to remove the top 12 floors of the building
located at the southeast corner of Park Avenue and 96th Street.
   The company bought the site in 1982 and received a construction
permit from New York City's Department of Buildings in 1985.
   Department officials misinterpreted a zoning map in permitting a
31-story building. The error was discovered in 1986, and the
department ordered the owners to stop work _ after the building had
been topped off at 31 floors.
   The New York Court of Appeals, the state's highest court, ruled
last February that ``the original permit in this case was invalid''
because it authorized construction above 19 floors.
   But the state court said the owner must share in the blame.
   ``Even if there was municipal error in one map and in the
mistaken administrative issuance of the original permit, those
factors would be completely outweighed in this case by the doctrine
that reasonable diligence would have readily uncovered'' the
correct limitations, the state court said.
   It also rejected arguments by Parkview Associates that the
city's order to reduce the building size is an unconstitutional
taking of property without due process.
   That issue cannot be addressed now because the builders have not
applied for a zoning variance, the state court said.
   Lawyers for Parkview Associates said it is the victim of
``grotesque mistreatment,'' stuck with a vacant building and
mounting losses while unable to get any income from the property.
   The case is Parkview Associates vs. New York City, 87-1837.
</TEXT>
