<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Frazee     10-03 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Frazee,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Rule on Illinois Decision About Working on the Sabbath</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider,
for the second time in two years, the authority of states to deny
unemployment benefits to people who refuse to work on their Sabbath.
   The court said it will decide whether Illinois officials
lawfully refused to pay benefits to a man whose refusal to work was
not based on the doctrine of any established religious body.
   William Frazee of Peoria was disqualified from receiving
unemployment benefits after turning down in 1984 a temporary job
assignment that would have required him to work on a Sunday.
   Frazee said his understanding of the requirements and tenets of
Christianity is that non-emergency work on Sundays is forbidden.
   The Illinois Department of Employment Security State ruled that
Frazee's rejection of the job offering disqualified him from
receiving unemployment benefits. State officials said a refusal to
work due to religious convictions must be based ``on some tenets or
dogma accepted by the individual of some church, sect or
denomination'' _ and not on individually held religious scruples.
   A state appeals court rejected Frazee's appeal. ``The injunction
against Sunday labor must be found in a tenet or dogma of an
established religious sect. (Frazee) does not profess to be a
member of any such sect,'' the appeals court ruled.
   In three previous rulings, the Supreme Court has barred states
from denying unemployment benefits to people who refuse certain
work because of religious scruples. But in all three cases, the
workers' refusal was based on the teachings of an established
religious sect.
   The Supreme Court in 1963 struck down a South Carolina law that
kept a Seventh-day Adventist from collecting unemployment benefits
after she was fired for declining Saturday work.
   The court in 1981 ordered Indiana to pay unemployment benefits
to a Jehovah's Witness who quit when transferred by his employer to
a job producing turrets for military tanks.
   And in early 1987 the justices said Florida authorities had
violated a Seventh-day Adventist's religious freedom by denying her
unemployment benefits because she refused to work on Saturdays.
   The Illinois appeals court said the distinction between Frazee's
case the previous Supreme Court cases ``may be a thin and fragile
line.'' But it said the fact that Frazee's refusal to work on
Sunday is not tied to any established church ``is a dividing line
which we deem significant.''
   The Illinois Supreme Court refused to hear Frazee's appeal last
Feb. 3.
   The case is Frazee vs. Department of Employment Security,
87-1945.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Citrus     10-03 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Citrus,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Must Pay for Destroyed Trees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today left intact a ruling
that states must compensate tree nursery owners required to destroy
healthy citrus plants that may have been exposed to an infectious
disease.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Florida
officials who say the ruling could force the state to pay $250
million to nursery owners.
   The Florida Supreme Court ruled in January that the state must
pay two nurseries for destruction of their trees.
   The state court ordered a trial to determine how much money is
owed Mid-Florida Growers Inc. and Himrod & Himrod Citrus Nursery,
both based in Hardee County.
   During two weeks in 1984, the state agriculture department
burned 137,880 of Mid-Florida's trees and budwood, and 143,594 of
Himrod's.
   State officials said they were worried the plants were infected
with citrus canker that could spread if the trees were sold to
citrus growers.
   The nursery owners said the tree-eradication program was less a
means of preventing public harm than a way of maintaining public
confidence in the state citrus industry.
   The state Supreme Court agreed that ``destruction of healthy
trees benefited the entire citrus industry and, in turn, Florida's
economy, thereby conferring a public benefit rather than preventing
a public harm.''
   The state court also said there is a distinction when officials
destroy decayed fruit, unwholesome meat or diseased cattle. In
those cases, the property is worthless, the state court said.
   There was ample evidence the destroyed trees were healthy, the
state court said, adding that 50,000 citrus plants from the two
nurseries were sold to customers and no canker ever was discovered
on the buyers' premises.
   The state court said the nursery owners are entitled to just
compensation as required by the Constitution's Fifth Amendment when
officials seize private property.
   Florida officials said they could end up being forced to pay
$250 million to all nursery owners in the state whose trees were
destroyed to prevent the canker disease from spreading.
   The state's appeal was supported by Florida citrus growers and
officials from nine other states who said the nursery owners are
not entitled to compensation.
   The states are Idaho, Louisiana, Mississippi, Oklahoma, South
Dakota, Tennessee, Vermont, Virginia and Wyoming.
   The case is Department of Agriculture vs. Mid-Florida Growers,
87-2123.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
