<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-RockConcerts     10-03 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Rock Concerts,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court To Hear New York Case on Noise levels From Rock Concerts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City officials concerned about
ear-splitting noise levels at Central Park rock concerts won a
Supreme Court hearing today.
   The court said it will review a ruling that the city cannot
control the volume at concerts by using its own sound system
operated by a city-designated engineer.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last June ruled that the
city's approach violates performers' freedom of artistic expression.
   The appeals court said, ``In the highly subjective realm of
music, legitimate regulation of noise levels does not justify
standardization. The required use of the city's system and
technician forces each performer and sponsor to filter its sound
quality, tone, mix and other aesthetic factors through the city's
technician and sound system.''
   City officials said the ruling is unrealistic, and they hinted
the ruling might even cause a riot if it leaves officials with no
other choice than ``pullling the plug'' on loudspeakers in the
middle of a concert.
   At issue are rules for concerts in Central Park's Naumburg
Bandshell, an amphitheater that is the city's most frequently used
park facility.
   The noise-control campaign is aimed at protecting visitors to
the park's neighboring Sheep Meadow, a 13-acre area decreed a
``quiet zone'' by Mayor Edward Koch in 1985.
   Park officials were concerned that rock groups unable to mix
their sound very well would resort to loudness to compensate for
that lack of skill. So the city hired a consultant to install and
run the sound system.
   The constitutionality of the plan was challenged by music groups
and Rock Against Racism, which sponsors an annual bandshell program
of speakers opposing racism.
   City officials noted that the organization's sound engineer,
when asked what should be the limit on noise, said, ``I think a
volume that causes people's ears to bleed would be too loud.''
   The 2nd Circuit court said the city may regulate the volume at
the concerts. But it said that could be enforced without requiring
the use of the city's sound system and engineer.
   If all else fails, the appeals court said, ``The plug can be
pulled on the sound to enforce the volume limit.''
   City officials replied, ``Pulling the plug during a concert
before a large, excited audience is not a practical alternative.''
   The case is Ward vs. Rock Against Racism, 88-226.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
