<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BombDeath     10-03 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bomb Death,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Test Bomb That Killed A Boy, Injured Five Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City and federal investigators plan
laboratory tests in an effort to determine the origin of a pipe
bomb that exploded, killing a 9-year-old boy and injuring five
other children.
   ``It was a terrible situation,'' said fire department Lt. R.C.
Swan. ``It was quite an explosion.''
   Max Herrera was killed and his brother, sister and three
neighbor children were injured Sunday evening when the 6- to
8-inch-long bomb they believed was a ``big firecracker'' exploded.
   Fire Capt. Roy Knight said the children may have found the bomb
along their street. But the dead boy's older sister, Rosie
Arredonda, 24, told the Fort Worth Star-Telegram that ``some kid
gave Max the bomb. Max lit it and it went up.''
   ``We've heard the kids were passing it around, trying to light
it with matches,'' said Fire Department District Chief David Carr.
``They had it in their hands. Whether they lit it or not, we don't
know. ... They were playing with it, but we can't be sure at this
time where it came from.''
   In spite of the strength of the blast that threw debris up to
150 feet away, nearly 75 percent of the bomb remained intact.
   ``We've got the whole (bomb),'' said Lou Iliano, agent of the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. ``There's quite a
bit of physical evidence. I was surprised at how much there was
left.''
   Shannon Hartigan, a pediatric nurse, was among the first on the
scene.
   ``I saw that little boy,'' Ms. Hartigan said of Max. ``I was
going to help him and I couldn't, of course, because there was
nothing to do to help.''
   She said the five injured children were coherent at the scene.
``All they kept asking was `Are we going to die?''', Ms. Hartigan
said.
   Two of the injured children were treated and released. One was
in fair condition after surgery to repair broken bones, one was in
serious condition after surgery for facial and eye injuries, and
one was in fair condition with head injuries, hospital officials
said.
</TEXT>
