<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Parents     10-03 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Parents,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal of Pennsylvania Couple Convicted in Son's
Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected the appeal of
a Pennsylvania couple criminally convicted in their young son's
death for trying to heal him through prayer rather than seeking
medical care.
   The court, without comment, let stand William and Linda
Barnhart's convictions for manslughter and endangering the welfare
of a child stemming from the 1981 death of their 2-year-old son,
Justin.
   The Barnharts, members of a fundamentalist religion who live in
Beaver Valley, Pa., received probationary sentences.
   Their appeal asked how the Barnharts could be held criminally
liable ``for putting their faith in God with the reasonable
expectation that the First Amendment would protect them?''
   The Constitution's First Amendment guarantees religious freedom.
   A state appeals court, in upholding the convictions, said there
is ``no easy answer'' in the Barnharts' case.
   In the late spring of 1981, the Barnharts detected a small lump
in Justin's abdomen. The lump grew over the summer, and by his
death on Sept. 10 Justin's abdomen had become quite large and
distended.
   An autopsy ordered by the Cambria County coroner indicated that
Justin's death was caused by a Wilm's tumor that weighed nearly
five pounds.
   The tumor's presence, and its effect on Justin's organs,
resulted in his death by starvation.
   The Barnharts made Justin's condition known to fellow members of
the Faith Tabernacle Congregation, who joined in prayer for him.
The child's abdomen was anointed with oil by the church's pastor.
   The appeals court, noting that three generations of the
Barnharts' family have adhered to the church's
healing-through-prayer beliefs, said, ``The question becomes one of
degree: to what extent may a parent impose these beliefs on a minor
child?''
   It concluded: ``Faced with a condition which threatened their
child's life, the parents had no choice but to seek medical help.''
   The appeals court, however, said its upholding the criminal
convictions was not meant to denigrate the Barnharts' religious
beliefs.
   The Pennsylvania Supreme Court refused to hear the Barnharts'
appeal last Jan. 14.
   In seeking help from the nation's highes court, the Barnharts'
appeal said, ``A significant number of Americans adhere to the
(same) religious principles, and they along with the (Barnharts)
look to this court for guidance.''
   The case is Barnhart vs. Pennsyvlania, 87-1722.
</TEXT>
