<HEAD>Court Kills Lawsuit Against Penthouse by Four Rhode Island
Schoolgirls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today killed a $7.5 million
lawsuit against Penthouse magazine by four Warwick, R.I.,
schoolgirls and their parents.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that the 1986
publication of a photograph of the four girls and an accompanying
headline did not amount to libel or intentional infliction of
emotional distress.
   In the autumn of 1985, the principal of Warwick's Oakland Beach
Elementary School decided to segregate the sexes during recess
periods because of fighting between boys and girls.
   In its reporting of the trouble, the Providence Journal-Bulletin
published a photograph showing Leslie Fudge, Jennifer Ann Merritt,
Tina Marie Oliver and Renee Vincentbs-down sign to
show their disapproval of the principal's decision.
   A story and the photo of the four girl giving the thums, who ranged
in age from
8 to 12, were distributed nationwide by The Associated Press.
   The April 1986 issue of Penthouse published the photograph over
a headline that read ``Little Amazons Attack Boys.''
   In a brief article, the school principal was quoted as saying
the recess segregation was enforced to protect the school's boys
from its girls.
   ``They kick them in the shins, pull their hair and kick them ...
well, in various places,'' the principal was quoe issuance of the original
permit, those
factors would be completely outweighed in this case by the doctrine
that reasonable diligence would have readily uncovered'' the
correct limitations, the state court said.
   It also rejected arguments by Parkview Associates that the
city's order to reduce the building size is an unconstitutional
taking of property without due process.
   That issue cannot be addressed now because the builders have not
applied for a zoning variance, the state court said.
   Lawyers for Parkview Associates said it is the victim of
``grotesque mistreatment,'' stuck with a vacant building and
mounting losses while unable to get any income from the property.
   The case is Parkview Associates vs. New York City, 87-1837.
