<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-DioxinClean-Up     10-03 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Dioxin Clean-Up,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Force Company to Pay for Dioxin Cleanup in
Missouri Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to force an
insurance company to help pay for cleaning up dioxin, a highly
toxic chemical, disposed of in various Missouri locations in the
early 1970s.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that an
insurance policy held by the chemical firm responsible for the
pollution did not make the insurance company liable for clean-up
costs.
   Dioxin has been linked to cancer, liver and immune system
disorders and a serious skin condition called chloracne.
   In 1982, the federal government bought out homes and property in
Times Beach, Mo., because of dioxin contamination. What was once a
town of 2,240 residents ceased to exist in 1985 when Times Beach's
aldermen voted to disincorporate the town.
   In the appeal acted on today, Missouri Attorney General William
A. Webster said his state faces spending tens of millions of
dollars to clean up the dioxin.
   ``As of November 1986, Missouri already had spent nearly $3
million to clean up the dioxin contamination ... and clean-up is
ongoing,'' Webster said. ``The state's projected share of the cost
to clean up ... primary dioxin-contaminated sites in Missouri is
$20 million.''
   The dioxin, a waste product from a Verona, Mo., plant owned by
the now-defunct ortheastern Pharmaceutical and Chemical Co.
(NEPACCO), was disposed of in various ways.
   In 1971, NEPACCO arranged to dispose of at least 85 55-gallon
drums of wastes in a trench near a Verona farm.
   In 1971 and 1972, dioxin-contaminated wastes from the Verona
plant were spread on the Bubbling Springs Stables in Fenton, Mo.,
and roads in Times Beach to control dust.
   From 1970 to 1972, NEPACCO was insured by Continental Insurance
Companies. Its policy required Continental to pay ``all sums which
the insured shall become legally obligated to pay as damages...''
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency sued NEPACCO in
1982, alleging that it had caused ``endangerment to health and the
environment.''
   The chemical firm was held liable for certain clean-up costs.
   Missouri sued NEPACCO in 1983 in an effort to recover other
clean-up costs, sparking Continental to sue NEPACCO to protect
itself against insurance claims.
   The full 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last Feb. 26
that the word ``damages'' in the NEPACCO insurance policy did not
apply to clean-up costs, a form of ``equitable relief.''
   The case is Missouri vs. Continental Insurance, 87-1953.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Hughes     10-03 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Hughes,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Leaves Intact $48 Million Judgment Awarded TWA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today left intact a $48.3
million judgment awarded Trans World Airlines against a company
founded by the late billionaire Howard Hughes.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments by Summa Corp.
and William R. Lummis, administrator of the Hughes estate, that the
award should be thrown out.
   The Delaware Supreme Court upheld the award last April 4 in a
case that began in 1962.
   Summa Corp., formerly called Hughes Tool Co. or Toolco, owned 78
percent of TWA stock when Toolco was sued by other TWA shareholders.
   The minority shareholders said TWA was denied an opportunity to
be competitive and profitable because Toolco refused to allow the
airline to purchase its own jets in the 1950s. TWA was forced to
lease jets and buy some from Toolco, the suit said.
   ``For reasons clearly attributable to the eccentric or
idiosyncratic business methods of Howard Hughes, TWA was unable to
establish a jet fleet as quickly as its competitors,'' the Delaware
Supreme Court ruled.
   It upheld a lower court ruling that awarded TWA more than $17.2
million plus interest of about $31.1 million.
   Hughes began acquiring TWA stock in 1939 and increased his
holdings to 78 percent by 1958.
   The Civil Aeronautics Board, which was interested in Toolco's
experimental work in developing airplane parts for the military,
approved the acquisition of TWA.
   The nation's highest court ruled in 1973 that Toolco did not
violate federal antitrust laws when buying up TWA stock.
   But the TWA minority shareholders then sued in state court in
Delaware, charging Toolco with violating state corporation laws
that require companies to seek the best interest of stockholders.
   After more than a decade of pre-trial maneuvering, a state court
found Toolco violated its fiduciary duty to TWA.
   The Delaware Supreme Court, in upholding the verdict, said the
1973 U.S. Supreme Court decision did not give Toolco ``blanket
immunity'' from being sued.
   The state Supreme Court said, ``As a whole, Toolco acted for its
sole benefit at the expense of its fiduciary duties to TWA's
minority shareholders.''
   The state court said Toolco, through the lease and sale of
planes to TWA, ``accrued substantial profits, reportable as capital
gains, as well as other tax benefits. Furthermore, Toolco
structured the transactions to minimize its exposure to risk at the
expense of TWA's profits. Such conduct hardly comports with basic
concepts of fair dealing.''
   The state court also rejected Toolco's argument that it delayed
TWA's acquisition of jets in the 1950s because it was waiting for
jets with true trans-Atlantic capability.
   Other airlines were buying the jets for their trans-Atlantic
routes until the later models were available, the state court said.
   In the appeal acted on today, Summa Corp. said the Delaware
court ruling is a threat to ``the supremacy of federal statutes and
(federal) agency orders.''
   The case is Summa Corp. vs. TWA, 88-149.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
