<HEAD>Drugs, Kiddie Porn, Parental Leave Still on Congressional Agenda</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 2 grafs on textile bill after 8th graf pvs, ``What
could</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before the 100th Congress shuts down, its
members likely will be fighting old battles against illegal drugs
and child pornography, and new ones over child care and mandatory
parental leave from work.
   Congress also may approve legislation to apply the first-ever
anti-lobbying restrictions on former members of Congress, and the
House could change its rules to extend civil rights protections to
its own employees.
   With the possibility of Congress adjourning for the year this
week, there's no guarantee that any controversial measures will
pass. But many often do in the last-minute frenzy that usually
accompanies the end of a congressional session.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas said a hybrid
pornography-child care-parental leave bill is less important than
the anti-drug measure.
   ``If you asked the American people which is more important, the
drug bill would be on everybody's list,'' he said Friday.
   The social issues in the parental leave bill have ``yet to be
defined'' by the presidential candidates, Dole said, adding, ``It
seems to me these issues ought to be looked at in the full light of
day in 1989.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., agreed ``the
drug bill is exceedingly important,'' but said the other three
issues should be approved before lawmakers leave.
   ``What could be more important than these?'' he said. Contending
that the presidential campaign should not influence Congress, Byrd
said, ``Let us remove them from the national debate. Let's enact
them now. The responsibility is ours. Why put it off so the
presidential and vice presidential candidates can debate who is
more pro-family.''
   The House has scheduled a vote, probably Tuesday, on overriding
President Reagan's veto of the Textile and Apparel Trade Act. The
legislation would limit the growth of textile and apparel imports
to 1 percent per year, and hold footwear imports to 1986 levels.
   Countries that increase their purchases of U.S. agricultural
goods could be given preference in the awarding of the quotas.
Senate Democratic leaders have not announced their plans on an
override.
   The House on Sept. 22 voted 375-30 for its version of the
anti-drug bill, which authorizes some $2 billion in new spending
and includes provisions to punish recreational users and murderers
alike.
   But the legislation includes a number of get-tough provisions
that may face court challenges, and there's no telling whether the
Senate will accept them. If the Senate does approve a bill, the two
houses could get bogged down in conference.
   The Senate bill will have a similar price tag, but includes a
number of differences. It does not include House provisions for
strong civil fines against drug users; the death penalty for those
who kill during drug-related crimes; and language to admit evidence
in federal court that was seized illegally by officers acting in
``good faith.''
   The parental leave component of the Senate legislation would
require businesses with more than 50 employees to give workers at
least 10 weeks of leave to cope with a newborn, newly adopted or
seriously ill child or a worker's own serious illness.
   Some of the most adamant opponents of the leave measure added it
last week to a bill strengthening laws and penalties against child
pornography and obscenity.
   The child care section would be modeled on the Act for Better
Child Care Services, a Democratic initiative centered on subsidies
to help families pay for day care.
   The anti-lobbying measure not only would place restrictions on
recently retired members of Congress, but on former presidents and
vice presidents.
   It also would expand current lobbying restrictions on former
executive branch officials.
   The Senate already has approved its own set lobbying
prohibitions for those who quit the executive branch or leave
Congress. Both measures are aimed at those who leave the government
and then immediately lobby their former colleagues _ usually on
issues with which they were involved.
   The House also is slated to vote on a proposed rules change to
extend civil rights protections to all employees of the House. The
measure would establish an internal enforcement process.
   The rule would provide all House employees and job applicants
with protection against discrimination based on race, color,
national origin, religion, sex, handicap or age. The language is
patterned after federal civil rights law.
   The Senate is preparing to consider a bill that would make
hundreds of changes and create some protections for taxpayers
involved in IRS disputes.
   Unlike most of the other tax bills of the 1980s, there is little
in this legislation to draw the concern of the average family. Most
of the changes are intended to clear up ambiguities or correct
errors in the 1986 tax overhaul. But there are tidbits for some
farmers, oil drillers, free-lance writers, first-time homebuyers,
banks and workers who receive educational assistance from their
employers.
   Appearing doomed as the session headed toward an end were Clean
Air Act revisions that advocates say would step up the nation's
battle against urban smog, acid rain and airborne toxic chemicals.
   Attempts by George Mitchell, D-Maine, to put together a
consensus in the Senate were far from successful last week, with
deep regional divisions over acid rain provisions the main
stumbling block.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
