<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Spillane     10-03 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Spillane,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mickey Spillane's Ex-Wife Fails to Alter Nevada Divorce Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Mickey Spillane's ex-wife failed today
in a Supreme Court bid to alter her divorce settlement.
   The justices, without comment, let stand Nevada court decisions
dismissing Sherri Spillane's lawsuit contesting the $18,000
settlement she received in 1983 from Spillane, creator of the
fictional detective Mike Hammer.
   The couple had been married in California in 1964, but according
to court records they did not live together after 1979. During that
time, Spillane resided in Murrell's Inlet, S.C., and his wife lived
in California.
   Spillane, whose books have sold more than a million copies
around the world, for years has been a familiar figure in
television beer commercials.
   Sherri Spillane, who appeared on the covers of several of
Spillane's books, tried to have their divorce settlement altered in
1985. She contended, among other things, that Spillane fraudulently
concealed community property assets.
   One state judge noted that the former Mrs. Spillane obtained a
marriage license to marry Michael Standing 20 minutes after her
divorce from Spillane was final.
   The judge said that while still married to Spillane, Sherri
Spillane had a longterm love affair with Standing.
   ``The court will not pass judgment on morality, but such actions
certainly are not those of a caring, faithful, loving spouse,'' the
state judge said.
   The Nevada Supreme Court threw out the lawsuit last year.
   The case is Spillane vs. Spillane, 88-45.
</TEXT>
