<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Alamo     10-03 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Alamo,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Religious Group Must Pay Arkansas Sales Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial religious group seeking to
avoid paying an Arkansas state sales tax on goods and services it
furnishes to members lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the Alamo
Foundation must pay the taxes on meals, clothing, goods and
services provided to its members, who in turn work for the
foundation.
   The foundation _ also based in California _ runs a restaurant, a
grocery store, two service stations, a clothing store and an auto
repair shop in Arkansas. The businesses are run for profit, and
foundation members _ also called associates _ work there without
receiving salaries.
   The Arkansas Supreme Court ruled last March that the members are
``paid'' by having their material needs met by the foundation.
   For example, the state court said, the Alamo Restaurant had
total sales of $2.3 million from Sept. 1, 1977 through Aug. 31,
1980. During that period, $1.4 million worth of food was sold to
the general public and the balance was consumed by Alamo members
and their families.
   The state court said that the food was transferred to the
members in exchange for their work, and therefore the foundation
must pay taxes on the transfers.
   ``The simple fact that the Alamo Foundation is a religious and
charitable organizae split between the two contending sponsors.
   The party commission also was awarded the sponsorship of the
debate this Wednesday in Omaha, Neb., between Democratic vice
presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen and his Republican
counterpart, Dan Quayle.
   The league had already signed contracts for a hall in Los
Angeles and made other arrangments for the second Bush-Dukakis
debate.
   But knowledgeable sources said there was no agreement about the
stage, podiums or panel of questioners for the second debate, and
that the campaigns had not discussed final arrangements with the
league by late last week.
</TEXT>
