<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Bork     10-03 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Bork,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Declines to Hear Case Alleging Impropriety by Bork</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today turned away an appeal
accusing defeated high court nominee Robert H. Bork of improperly
participating in a case just before he quit as a federal judge.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that Bork's
failure to disqualify himself from a libel case violated the
conservative Liberty Lobby group's due-process rights.
   Liberty Lobby sued The Wall Street Journal for $50 million over
a 1984 article and a 1985 column that appeared in the newspaper.
   The column was written by Suzanne Garment, a Journal writer
whose husband, Leonard Garment, is a longtime friend of Bork's.
   Garment, a Washington lawyer, served as Bork's chief spokesman
during an unsuccessful campaign to win Senate confirmation of
Bork's nomination to the Supreme Court.
   The Senate rejected Bork by a 58-42 vote last October.
   Bork's participation in the Liberty Lobby case was challenged
because of his relationship with the Garments.
   In both the article and column, Liberty Lobby was referred to as
``anti-Semitic'' and was linked to books authored by an advocate of
racial betterment through genetic selection.
   Although Liberty Lobby admits to being an anti-Zionist
organization it denies being anti-Semitic. The lawsuit also denied
any links with the author's works.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, whose participation
in the case also was challenged, dismissed the lawsuit in 1986.
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here
upheld the libel suit's dismissal last Feb. 5, in an opinion
written by Bork.
   Bork quit the federal bench that same day.
   In his opinion for the appellate panel, Bork said, ``We tend to
agree with the district court that if the term `anti-Semitic' has a
core factual meaning, then the truth of the description was proved
here.''
   The appeals court also rejected Liberty Lobby's denial of a link
to the mentioned books, published by Noontide Press in Torrance,
Calif.
   ``The record evidence that both (group treasurer Willis Carto)
and Liberty Lobby exercise substantial financial and editorial
control over the publishing activities of Noontide is, in our view,
compelling,'' Bork wrote.
   The full court of appeals last Feb. 25 denied Liberty Lobby's
request to have its lawsuit revived and Bork disqualified.
   The case is Liberty Lobby vs. Dow Jones & Co., 87-2053.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
