<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ManBurned     10-03 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Man Burned,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Dies After Being Set On Fire; Incident Possibly Drug-Related</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with two vials of crack and a record of
arrests for drug possession was doused with a flammable liquid and
fatally burned on a sidewalk near Madison Square Garden, police
said.
   The man, who identified himself as Michael Howard and said his
nickname was ``Scandalous Mike,'' died Sunday morning at New York
Hospital-Cornell Medical Center, about 10 hours after the attack
Saturday evening.
   Capt. William K. Roe said nobody had been arrested and police
did not have a motive for the attack. Howard, who police records
said was 29, had three arrests for drug possession on his record
but none for selling.
   ``It's narcotics-related to the extent that the man had
narcotics on his person, but that doesn't necessarily mean that's
why he was killed in this manner,'' Roe said Sunday.
   Howard had two crack vials in his mouth, ``which is where people
who sell crack keep it,'' he said.
   ``So the indications are that it is a possible narcotics dealer
dealing crack in the area, although he has never been arrested for
selling,'' Roe said.
   Detective Joseph McConville, a police spokesman, said three or
four men approached Howard from behind, poured a liquid over him
and ignited him.
   Howard managed to cross the street before collapsing. He who
told police, ``You know me, I'm Scandalous Mike,'' as he was
removed from the scene. He also indicated that he knew who his
assailants were.
   He died at New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center from
second-and third-degree burns over 98 percent of his body, said
Solomon Torres, a hospital administrator.
   His fingers were so badly burned that it was difficult to
confirm his identity through fingerprints, Roe said.
   Amtrak police at Penn Station said they were familiar with
``Scandalous Mike,'' Roe said. Two of the man's three
drug-possession arrests took place at the station, where many
homeless and street people congregate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
