<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0456 10-03 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kinnock Defeats Party Leftists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with defeat of bid to block policy,
other details. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `In a ballot...'
^By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition Labor Party leader Neil
Kinnock, who crushed a left-wing attempt to unseat him as his
party's leader, today defeated a bid to block apolicy review that
supports the role of private enterprise.
   Kinnock kicked off the party's annual weeklong convention Sunday
night by crushing a challenge for his job by the doyen of the party
left, former Cabinet minister Tony Benn.
   The more than 1,000 conference delegates today rejected the
attempt to kill the policy review _ which would push the socialists
toward the center _ by a vote of more than 10-to-1.
   Kinnock ordered the review after Labor's third successive
election defeat by Conservative Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in
1987.
   In a break with traditional party ideology, the review abandons
a previous commitment to renationalize all the industries sold by
Mrs. Thatcher since she came to power in 1979. In addition, it
drops some of the left wing's favorite causes by partially
accepting Mrs. Thatcher's curbs on labor unions.
   A series of left-wing speakers accused Kinnock of putting
forward what one called ``a pompous document which rejects
socialism.''
   In a ballot at the start of the conference Sunday evening,
Kinnock, 46, overwhelmingly defeated his challenger, Tony Benn, 63.
Kinnock appeared certain to use the victory as a new mandate to
push the party toward the center.
   Kinnock received 88 percent of the votes of an electoral college
composed of labor union leaders, legislators and local constituency
parties. Benn has pledged to continue trying to stop what he calls
the ``virtual repudiation of socialism'' at the Blackpool
conference.
   The final stages of the policy review will be presented to the
party's annual conference next year, along with the documents
debated today.
   In another vote Sunday, Kinnock's deputy Roy Hattersley also
defeated on the first ballot with a two-thirds majority a bid to
unseat him by two leftists, John Prescott and Eric Heffer.
   Kinnock hailed the votes as a ``great honor and a great trust.''
   ``It imposes a great duty, too,'' said Kinnock. ``We want to use
this great victory to secure a greater victory at the next general
election.''
   Benn has scheduled a series of fringe meetings through the
weeklong conference in this northeast England resort to press home
his argument that Kinnock, in the hope of averting another election
defeat, has ditched Labor's fundamental policies. These include a
commitment, at least on paper, for the government to control all
means of ownership and production.
   Kinnock had been expected to defeat Benn's challenge by a wide
margin. In addition to getting virtually unanimous backing from the
labor union leaders, who comprise 40 percent of the electoral
college, he also received majority support from the often hostile
Labor constitutency parties.
   All but 35 of the party's 228 parliamentary legislators voted
for Kinnock.
   Latest opinion polls show Labor narrowing its big gap with the
ruling Conservatives but still trailing them by between 9 and 5
points, despite a fall in the Conservatives' popularity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
