<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Irish     10-03 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Shoots Man It Claims Was Police Informer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a Roman Catholic
man in his home Monday, and the extremist group that claimed
responsibility said the man was slain because he was a police
informer.
   But the family of Henry McNamee, 33, denied he was an informer,
and the Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police force,
refused comment.
   The Irish People's Liberation Organization claimed
responsibility for McNamee's death in a statement to news media.
   The organization is a splinter group of the Irish National
Liberation Army, itself an extremist offshoot of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army.
   Police said gunmen burst into a west Belfast home just before 3
a.m. and shot McNamee at close range before escaping in a hijacked
car. The car was later recovered nearby, police said.
   ``My brother is innocent of that accusation (of being an
informant),'' said Joe McNamee. ``It is as simple as that.''
   ``He has been in jail before due to the circumstances and the
situation in Northern Ireland but he was not an informer.''
   The IRA is fighting to drive the British out of Northern Ireland
and unite the predominantly Protestant province with the mainly
Catholic Irish Republic.
   In south Belfast, four children aged 1 to 12 and their
grandmother escaped injury Monday when several gunmen fired about
20 shots into their house, police said. They said they were not
aware of any motive for the attack.
</TEXT>
