<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Columbus     10-03 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Columbus,140</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today put in a plug for the
forthcoming 500th anniversary celebration of Christopher Columbus'
voyage to America, but confessed he has a little trouble with the
observance's name.
   ``It's called the quincentenary, and it may take another 500
years before I can say that easily,'' Reagan told a crowd in the
White House East Room as he signed a proclamation declaring Oct. 10
as Columbus Day.
   Later in his remarks, the president stumbled over the word,
referring to the`` Christopher Columbus Quincentenni - centenary
Commission'' that he appointed to make plans for the 1992
observance.
   Next time he came to the word, he paused, grinned, and got it
right: ``Quincentenary.''
   Whatever you call it, said Reagan, ``it will be a time when
Americans from all backgrounds look back on all that voyage has
meant to mankind over the past half millenium.''
</TEXT>
