<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SuniaAide     10-03 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sunia Aide,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aide to Samoan Delegate Draws Three-Month Term for Payroll Padding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A one-time top aide to Aerican Samoa's former
non-voting delegate to Congress received a three-month prison term
Monday for masterminding a payroll padding scheme that netted
$130,920.
   Matthew Iuli, who was chief aide to former Del. Fofo I.F. Sunia,
was sentenced by U.S. District Judge Stanley Harris on his guilty
pleas to conspiring to defraud the government and filing a false
payroll claim.
   Sunia, 51, a Democrat who had represented American Samoa since
1981, resigned his seat after pleading guilty Aug. 3 to a single
conspiracy charge. He could receive a five-year prison term and a
$250,000 fine when sentenced Tuesday by Harris.
   The judge rejected a defense request _ unopposed by prosecutors
_ that Iuli be placed on probation because he had not personally
benefited from the scheme and had fully cooperated with prosecutors.
   ``I think that probation is not appropriate in your case,''
Harris said, noting the extent of the crime.
   ``A period of incarceration is not necessary to deter you or
rehabilitate you, but to deter others,'' Harris said. ``There are
an awful lot of other offices up on Capitol Hill.''
   Iuli could have received two five-year sentences.
   As part of his guilty plea, Iuli agreed to pay the government
$25,000 as restitution and has already made a $10,000 payment,
defense lawyer Richard Saltsman told Harris.
   Both Andary and Saltsman noted that Iuli did not personally
benefit from the scheme, under which he arranged for paychecks to
be issued to Samoans who were falsely listed as working for Sunia.
   Between February 1983 and August 1986, 78 paychecks worth
$130,920 were issued by the government as a result of false payroll
vouchers submitted by Sunia's office, according to court papers.
</TEXT>
