<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     10-03 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 1,000 Prisoners Released Under Amnesty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Monday released more
than 1,000 prisoners, including 52 political offenders, under a
special amnesty marking South Korea's National Foundation Day, a
major national holiday.
   Opposition parties, who have demanded the release of ``all
political prisoners,'' criticized the amnesty. Opposition leader
Kim Dae-jung said his party, along with other opposition parties,
would try to enact a special law to win the release of other
``prisoners of conscience.''
   Kim, president of the main opposition group, the Party for Peace
and Democracy, gave no overall figures but said ``only one-tenth of
the prisoners of conscience'' were freed.
   Those freed Monday included Lee Tae-bok, a 38-year-old publisher
whose release was demanded by delegates attending the World
Congress of PEN in Seoul in early September. PEN is a London-based
organization of literary figures.
   Lee was arrested in 1981 on charges of plotting to organize a
leftist underground movement and fomenting a communist rebellion
through a publishing company he owned, PEN said.
   He was sentenced to life, which was later commuted to 20 years
in 1983.
   PEN sought the release of three other writers also in jail for
political reasons, but they were excluded in the amnesty.
   Government officials said the other writers, mentioned by PEN,
were directly involved in arson that resulted in deaths or
anti-South Korea activities in favor of communist North Korea.
   Also Monday, 150 actors, actresses and other film workers
protested outside a Seoul cinema against the independent
distribution of U.S. films.
   Protesters gathered in front of a downtown movie theater showing
the U.S. film ``Fatal Attraction'' and sat in the entrance.
   Some sang songs or held placards asking fans to boycott the
theater in order to ``guard our culture and our industry.''
   Billboards advertising the movie were peppered with black
splotches from paint bombs, part of an earlier protest. Statements
passed out to bystanders claimed that direct distribution of
American films was ``an attempt to seize complete domination'' of
South Korea's film industry.
   Police reported no arrests and the protest was peaceful.
   American films have been available in South Korea, but under a
new trade liberalization law U.S. filmakers are being allowed to
distribute movies directly to South Korean cinemas instead of
through South Korean producers.
   Local film producers say the new regulations will wreck the
local industry.
</TEXT>
