<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis     10-03 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Tells Pupils That Bush `Puts You to Sleep'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis bantered with
pupils at a public elementary school today and told one of them
that Vice President George Bush was like a drug that ``puts you to
sleep.''
   The Massachusetts governor began a campaign swing that aides
said would tie together various themes he has been sounding over
the past few weeks, particularly education.
   Speaking with fourth- and fifth-grade pupils at the Alfred E.
Burr Elementary School here, Dukakis talked about drugs and asked
the students if they knew the names of bad drugs. One child
declared, ``Bush is a drug.''
   To that, the Democratic joked, ``Puts you to sleep, right?''
   Dukakis told the students that his goal was making the United
States ``No. 1 and staying No. 1.''
   ``If we are going to be the best then we are going to have to
build a very strong future,'' Dukakis said, urging the youngsters
to consider careers as teachers or scientists.
   Dukakis also talked about the landing today of the Discovery
space shuttle at Edwards Air Force Base, Calif., which his
Republican rival attended.
   From the school, Dukakis headed for a rally at the Connecticut
statehouse and planned to fly to Detroit to observe the destruction
of an illegal drug cache.
   Dukakis adviser Kirk O'Donnell said the nominee's focus during
campaign appearances this week ``will be on the future ... and
children are a good way to do it.'' He said Dukakis would be
visiting other schools to press that theme.
</TEXT>
