<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     10-03 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Ends In Burma, Government Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government said nearly all
civil servants and factory workers obeyed an order to return to
work Monday, ending a monthlong general strike aimed at ending 26
years of authoritarian rule.
   The state radio announced that attendance at 18 ministries and
various departments was about 95 percent, while all civil servants
returned to their jobs in the second largest city of Mandalay. The
strike began Aug. 8.
   The radio said security forces killed four more people, who were
looting a gasoline station in eastern Rangoon, bringing to about
430 the number of people who by official count have died since Gen.
Saw Maung seized power in a military coup Sept. 18 and ruthlessly
put down anti-government demonstrations.
   Although tens of thousands of workers returned to their jobs,
many left after drawing their salaries and signing attendance
sheets. The government had earlier ordered a resumption of work
under penalty of dismissal.
   The only acts of defiance reported in the capital Monday were
several small hit-and-run demonstrations by students.
   The strike was the first mass labor agitation since strongman Ne
Win seized power in 1962 and instituted a military-backed,
one-party system.
   Despite the apparent end of the strike, it appeared unlikely the
government machinery and state-owned factories would regain
momentum in the near future.
   Most of the country's more than 1,000 factories had ceased
operations and are faced with lack of spare parts and raw
materials. A large number have been ransacked by looters who stole
or destroyed machinery and materials.
   Several thousand students, who spearheaded the anti-government
protests, have fled to remote border areas under the control of the
Karen and other ethnic minorities who are also fighting the central
government.
   Associated Press newswoman Molly Yong, reporting from the Karen
guerrilla camp of Thay Baw Bo, said rebel leader Gen. Bo Mya Monday
appealed for international aid to 3,500 students who have fled to
his rebel bases.
   Bo Mya said the Karens would allow the students to set up
independently run camps where the rebels would provide military
training and arm the students for a war against the military-run
government in Rangoon.
   The Karens are among a dozen major ethnic minority groups in
Burma, a country of 38 million people. The Karens, who live largely
along the Thai-Burmese border and in the Irrawaddy delta, number
about 2 million.
   During the colonial period large numbers were converted to
Christianity by American missionaries and enjoyed relative freedom
under the British rule.
   Feeling that the promise of autonomy within a federal system
after independence had been broken, a number of Karens fled to
jungle areas along the border and in 1949 rose up in rebellion,
managing to fight their way to the gates of Rangoon before being
pushed back to their sanctuaries.
   Bo Mya said recently that his insurgent group, called the Karen
National Union, fields 17,000 troops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
