<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Killed in Ethnic Violence in Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HYDERABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more people were reported killed
in this southern city Monday, and President Ghulam Ishaq Khan met
with local leaders about ethnic violence that claimed more than 200
lives over the weekend.
   People fired guns into the air during a two-hour break in the
curfew late Monday afternoon and one person was killed by a stray
bullet, police reported. They said the second was shot by an
attacker who fled.
   Ishaq Khan met with officials of the city and Sind province
about the violence. It began Friday night with an attack by Sindhi
gunmen on immigrants from India called Mohajirs, in which at least
160 people died.
   He also has visited Karachi, the country's largest city, where
more than 50 people were killed after the Hyderabad massacre.
   Some opposition politicians have suggested agents of India were
behind the violence in Sind province, but government officials have
not been so speific.
   A statement distributed by the official news agency APP quoted
Ishaq Khan as saying: ``Those who are trying to pit brother against
brother are the real enemies of Pakistan, and the government has
taken note of it. The government is fully aware of the elements who
indulged in the bloodbath and will eliminate them with an iron
hand.''
   Those ``elements'' were not identified.
   Karachi was reported quiet Monday, with several districts under
curfew and soldiers in armored vehicles patrolling the streets.
Military units also patrolled Hyderabad, 100 miles northeast of
Karachi.
   Gen. Aslam Beg, the army commander, and some other officials
claimed the violence was part of a conspiracy to disrupt national
elections set for Nov. 16. The statement by Ishaq Khan said
elections ``will be held on schedule and in an impartial, fair and
free manner.''
   Police and witnesses said the main culprits in Friday's
Hyderabad massacre were members of the Jeay Sind movement who want
an independent homeland.
   Mohajirs, almost 40 percent of the province's population, have
formed their own group to seek recognition as a nationality along
with Sindhis, Punjabis, Baluchis and Pathans.
   Karachi and Hyderabad have a history of ethnic troubles between
local tribes and immigrants from India and other parts of Pakistan.
</TEXT>
