<HEAD>Harold Robinson, Dunkirk Veterans Leader, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEEDS, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Robinson, the general secretary of
the Dunkirk Veterans Association, died from injuries suffered in a
fall, his family said Monday. He was 68.
   Robinson, died Sunday in a hospital in Leeds, northern England,
his son Nigel said. He said Robinson was paralyzed from the neck
down when he fell down a flight of stairs at his home on Wednesday.
   The former prisoner of war was made a member of the Order of the
British Empire by Queen Elizabeth II and was awarded the French
National Order of Merit for his part in founding the World War II
veterans association which has a worldwide membership of 50,000.
   Nearly 200,000 British soldiers and 140,000 French troops were
ferried across the English Channel from Dunkirk in northern France
between May 26, 1940, and June 2, 1940, to escape rapidly advancing
German troops.
   Robinson is also survived by his wife, Eileen, and another son.
