<HEAD>Enraged Tyson Goes on Rampage in His Mansion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with police confirming they
were called to house, but saying no complaint filed; picking up at
the 9th graf pvs, `I've heard...'. Adds byline. A version also
moved sports wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERNARDSVILLE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife and mother-in-law of
heavyweight boxing champion Mike Tyson called police over the
weekend when he flew into a rage but no complaints were filed and
no arrests were made, authorities confirmed today.
   ``The man has done nothing wrong,'' Chief Thomas J. Sciaretta
said at a news conference following reports that Tyson hurled
furniture through windows of his mansion Sunday morning. ``It's his
home. He's entitled to do anything he pleases, provided no one is
injured.''
   Tyson's rage was sparked by an interview his wife, actress Robin
Givens, and mother-in-law, Ruth Roper, had with Barbara Walters,
which was broadast Friday on ABC's ``20-20,'' the New York Post and
New York Daily News reported.
   In the interview, Givens and Roper portrayed Tyson, 22, as a
``scary'' and ``frightening'' person to live with.
   The Post said Tyson, who has said he is manic-depressive, hurled
a sugar bowl, a fireplace andiron and chairs through the windows of
his home. The News said Tyson brandished ``an instrument'' from the
fireplace and ran through the home smashing windows.
   The police chief said there was damage but would disclose only
that there was broken glass in the foyer.
   People suffering from manic-depression can alternate between
moods of abnormal excitability and mental depression. In last
week's television interview, Tyson said he would not take
medication for the ailment.
   Sciaretta disclosed the barest of details of the case.
   He said he believed it was Givens, a star of television's ``Head
of the Class,'' who called his department about a disturbance at
Tyson's northern New Jersey estate.
   When police arrived, they spoke with Givens and Roper, who asked
the officers to speak to Tyson and calm him down, Sciaretta said.
   The officers explained to Tyson that they just wanted to resolve
the situation but the boxer felt the police presence was
unwarranted, the chief said.
   When Givens and her mother left the estate a short time later,
Tyson was in the driveway, Sciaretta said, adding that Tyson left
shortly thereafter.
   He refused to elaborate further.
   The Post said Tyson drove to New York City. Hours later, he
phoned for a limousine to pick him up after he missed meeting a
friend, the newspaper said.
   ``I've heard things, but I cannot comment on it,'' said Bill
Cayton, Tyson's manager.
   But the 83-year-old woman who has been characterized as Tyson's
``adopted'' mother, Camille Ewald, told the Post that Tyson's
behavior comes as no surprise in light of the ``20-20'' interview.
   ``I think that if I was Mike I would have choked her right then
and there on that show,'' she said. ``She was trying to belittle
him, take everything away, his dignity, and embarrass him in
public.''
   The reported incident came one day after the three celebrated
Roper's birthday. The Post said the champion ``didn't seem to be
that upset'' Saturday as he watched the heavyweight Olympic bout on
TV with Finkel and boxer Ed Hopson.
   It was only the latest in a series of problems for Tyson. Last
month, he crashed in his car and was knocked unconscious, forcing
him to postpone a match, and news reports later said he had
threatened beforehand to kill himself.
   Meanwhile, boxer Mitch Green, who had an impromptu fight with
Tyson outside a Harlem clothing store in August, was arrested
Sunday for the third time in less than two weeks Sunday after
police found him in a car that had crashed into a parked vehicle,
authorities said.
   Green, 31, who was charged with driving while impaired, has had
his driver's license suspended 54 times, police said.
   Green pressed assault charges following his Aug. 23 street fight
with Tyson, but dropped them three days later. He lost a bout with
Tyson for the U.S. Boxing Association heavyweight title in 1986.
</TEXT>
