<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-AlaskaPipeline 1stLd-Writethru a0581 10-03 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Alaska Pipeline, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0581,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eskimos Lose Challenge to Pipeline Rates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Artic to Arctic throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected a challenge
to the rates being charged for transporting oil through the
Trans-Alaska Pipeline.
   The justices, without comment, left intact a rate agreement
between Alaska and the pipeline's eight owners.
   The rates were challenged by the Arctic Slope Regional Corp.,
established under Alaska law to protect the rights of Inupiat
Eskimos.
   Lawyers for Arctic said the pipeline rate agreement, which
extends through the year 2011, ``will have a critical effect on the
development and cost of oil from the Alaska North Slope, an energy
resource vital to our nation's economy and security.''
   After large reserves of oil were discovered on Alaska's North
Slope in 1969, eight oil companies constructed an 800-mile pipeline
to the all-weather port of Valdez on the state's Pacific coast.
   The pipeline was completed in 1977, at a cost of some $9 billion.
   The Alaska law, aimed at promoting oil production, extinguished
the land claims of native Alaskans by compensating them with money.
   Arctic is one of 13 regional corporations given ownership of
lands formerly held by natives. Arctic leases much of its 4.5
million acres for the benefit of its Inupiat Eskimo shareholders.
   Oil from Arctic's lands likely will start being shipped through
the pipeline sometime in the 1990s, and the oil's value to Arctic
will be reduced dollar-for-dollar by charges levied for
transporting it.
   After nine years of administrative proceedings, Alaska and the
pipeline's eight owners reached a rate agreement in 1986.
   Arctic attempted to challenge the agreement, contending that the
per-barrel rates it yielded are too high.
   But the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission approved the
agreement as uncontested after ruling that Arctic was not
``particularly aggrieved'' by the pipeline rates.
   A federal appeals court here upheld the commission ruling last
Oct. 27 after noting that the rate agreement is not binding on
Arctic, and that Arctic is free to challenge the rates once oil
from its lands begin to pass through the pipeline.
   ``Arctic can properly be left out in the cold for the moment,''
the appeals court ruled, adding, ``The commission acted within its
lawful authority and discretion in closing a long and wearisome
chapter in the saga of (Trans-Alaska Pipeline) rate regulation.''
   The pipeline's owners are Amerada Hess, Arco, BP, Exxon, Mobil,
Phillips, Sohio and Unocal.
   The case is Arctic Slope Regional Corp. vs. FERC, 87-1869.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ShuttleWatchers 3rdLd-Writethru a0612 10-03 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Watchers, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0612,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Cheer As Shuttle Comes Down To Smooth Landing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with reaction after launch; new
crowd estimate put at 425,000. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The
camp...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos EAB1,2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cheers erupted from
425,000 people today who gathered in tents, motor homes and trucks
and atop every NASA building here as the space shuttle completed
the first flight since Challenger exploded.
   ``I had goose bumps all over,'' said Diane Bonds, who traveled
600 miles from Roy, Utah, to watch Discovery touch down. ``I have
always wanted to see one of these and now I have.''
   ``I think we're back on top,'' said Mike Asfall, who supervises
training for Air Force and NASA personnel working on the main
shuttle engine at Rockwell International's Rocketdyne plant in
Canoga Park, Calif.
   ``Everyone has a flag up. It's so patriotic,'' said John
Tibbets, 78, who led an 11-unit brigade of Airstream trailers from
the San Bernardino Airstreams Club across shimmering desert roads
to the public viewing site Sunday.
   Air Force spokesman Lt. Col. George Neiss said 109,000 vehicles
carried an estimated 410,000 people to the public viewing site by
the time Discovery landed at 9:37 a.m. PDT. At least 15,000 more
were in the VIP section, where Vice President George Bush was on
hand to greet the astronauts as they descended from the orbiter.
   Only one larger crowd had ever gathered to watch a shuttle land:
an estimated 500,000 for the shuttle Columbia on July 4, 1982, when
President and Nancy Reagan greeted the astronauts.
   Screams broke out from the public viewing area on the hard clay
eastern shore of Rogers Dry Lake at 9:34 a.m., as two sonic booms
reverberated across the Joshua-tree dotted high desert. Then cheers
and applause broke out as Discovery appeared in the sky.
   Crowds also cheered from atop NASA buildings as the
Star-Spangled Banner began blaring when the orbiter completed a
fast turn high over the lakebed and plummeted swiftly to Earth,
then coasted to a stop.
   All day Sunday, recreational vehicles, cars and even big rigs
streamed across heat-rippled two-lane blacktop and took up
positions surrounded by rattlesnake-infested desert. Despite some
concern about the reptiles, medics reported no problems.
   The camp of silver Airstream cocoons, decorated with American
and California flags, joined thousands of other motor homes on the
44-square-mile lake bed where the shuttle was to land.
   ``This is what America's all about,'' said Vic Failla, 61, a
World War II veteran from La Verne who brought his brother, Tony,
to this air base 80 miles north of Los Angeles.
   License plates on the motor homes, trucks and cars represented
states as far away as North Dakota and Florida.
   The crowd was festive but orderly. The constant whir of portable
generators droned throughout the day and night. Campers peered
through binoculars and telescopes and set out jugs of tea to brew
in the 102-degree heat. Teen-agers buzzed around on all-terrain
vehicles.
   Vendors hawked tiny flags and other souvenirs, such as Stealth
bomber models and mugs. Alice Brakke, selling $2 flags, and
witnessing her 18th shuttle landing, broadcast from her booth a
tape of the late Kate Smith singing ``God Bless America.''
   Other speakers broadcast news from the Johnson Space Center in
Houston.
   ``It's like a kid going to Disneyland,'' said Gordon Gilmore,
56, of Fort Worth, Texas. ``All these flags are really something.''
</TEXT>
