<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MissouriExecution 2ndLd-Writethru a0550 10-03 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missouri Execution, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0550,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stay Halts What Would Have Been State's First Execution Since 1965</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with stay of execution issued,
picking up at 6th graf pvs, `The execution...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede JEFFERSON CITY, Mo.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today granted a stay of
execution for a convicted killer who had said he wanted his
execution by lethal injection to take place tonight as scheduled.
   A three-judge panel of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
granted the stay on a motion claiming that Gerald Smith, convicted
of fatally beating a woman with an 8-pound metal bar, may not be
competent to decide on filing appeals of his sentence.
   Smith's execution would have been the first in Missouri in 23
years.
   The panel said more time was needed for the full court to
determine whether Smith was competent to make decisions on his own
fate.
   Assistant Attorney General John Morris said the state would file
a motion as quickly as possible challenging the stay. He said he
did not know exactly what type of legal motion it would be.
   The stay was sought by the Missouri Public Defender Commission.
   On Sunday, about 50 death penalty opponents rallied on the
Capitol lawn, just blocks from the Missouri State Penitentiary
where Smith was scheduled to be executed by injection at 12:01 a.m.
Tuesday, three days before his 30th birthday.
   Speakers denounced capital punishment as state-sanctioned
homicide and called on Republican Gov. John Ashcroft or the courts
to block the execution.
   A spokesman for Ashcroft, a death penalty supporter, has said
the governor would not stop the execution.
   The execution would be the first to be carried out since 1965
and the first under Missouri's 11-year-old reinstated capital
punishment law.
   Smith has demanded that all appeals be dropped. In the past,
he's asked that appeals be halted, but later changed his mind.
However, in an interview Friday, Smith said he would not waver this
time because he considers all further appeals hopeless.
   Smith remains steadfast on wanting the execution to take place,
prison spokesman Dale Riley said.
   At the rally, speakers representing the American Civil Liberties
Union and other anti-death-penalty groups said that although Smith
was a murderer, it was not the state's place to execute him.
   On Sept. 8, 1980, Smith used an iron bar to beat to death Karen
Roberts, a woman he said had given him a venereal disease and
caused him to lose his fiancee. He received a second death penalty
for his part in the 1985 murder of fellow death row inmate Robert
Baker.
   If the execution is carried out, it would mark the first time
the state has executed anyone since Feb. 26, 1965, when Lloyd Leo
Anderson went to the gas chamber for murdering a 15-year-old St.
Louis delivery boy during a drugstore robbery.
</TEXT>
