<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--NukeProtest     10-03 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Nuke Protest,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists Protest Nuclear Tests On Gandhi's Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERCURY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities made 110 arrests, including
actor Martin Sheen, at the Nevada Test Site during a nuclear
weapons protest celebrating the birthday of Mahatma Gandhi.
   Some 200 protesters were on hand for Sunday's observance, said
Energy Department spokesman Chris West.
   Many of the protesters were arrested more than once when they
crossed the test site boundary, were arrested and released, then
crossed again, West said. All were cited for misdemeanor trespass.
   Sheen has been arrested numerous times in demonstrations at the
site where underground nuclear weapons tests are conducted.
   The Rev. Bill O'Donnell, a Catholic priest from Berkeley,
Calif., said Sheen brought along a film crew to shoot scenes for a
movie in which the actor plays a scientist exposed to nuclear
weapons.
   West said the demonstration was peaceful. He called the event
``just typical civil disobedience.''
   Gandhi, who died in 1948, advocated passive resistance as a
means of ending British rule of India.
</TEXT>
