<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-HenryMiller     10-03 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Henry Miller,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Publisher Of Henry Miller Novel Could Be Prosecuted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British publisher of a 1940 novel by American
writer Henry Miller faces possible prosecution after complaints
about the book's explicit sexuality, prosecutors said Monday.
   The Director of Public Prosecutions said it is considering
taking action over Miller's ``Opus Pistorum,'' which surfaced three
years after Miller died at age 88 in June 1980.
   The investigation was prompted by recent complaints from the
public, including one from Christian Action Research and Education,
an evangelical charity that promotes traditional family values, the
prosecutor's office said.
   ``The matter is under consideration,'' said a spokesman,
speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom.
   Publisher W. H. Allen said it has sold about 60,000 copies of
the novel, subtitled ``Under the Roofs of Paris,'' in the last four
years.
   Britain's leading news agents, W. H. Smith, said it had
withdrawn the book from its shelves, not because it is being
investigated but ``because it is not selling well,'' a spokesman
said.
   ``If you're a customer, you can still place an order for the
book,'' said the spokesman, speaking on condition on anonymity.
   Miller wrote ``Tropic of Cancer'' and other books which gave
frank accounts of his life and sexual exploits in New York and
Paris and were banned in the United States until 1961.
   The last successful obscenity prosecution in Britain against an
acclaimed writer was in the mid-1960s when Hubert Selby Jr.'s
account of homosexuality in ``Last Exit to Brooklyn'' was banned.
</TEXT>
