<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0685 10-03 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0685,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Bush Greets Astronauts; pick up 4th graf pvs bgng ``The
four-day...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George
Bush, taking full advantage of his incumbency, greeted the
returning Discovery astronauts today as they departed the space
shuttle with a large American flag in hand.
   The vice president said it was ``a great day for our country.''
   A campaign spokesman had said that Bush wanted to be the first
person the astronauts would see upon their return, and he was,
standing with several top NASA officials at the foot of the shuttle
ramp. The astronauts led Bush in the traditional walk-around to
review the shape of the ship. After posing for photos, Bush snapped
a salute to the astronauts.
   The Republican presidential nominee said ``Wasn't that great?''
over and over after the shuttle taxied to a stop here. Bush, with
NASA officials and veteran flyer Chuck Yeager at his side, then
greeted the five crew members once they left the shuttle.
   Bush scheduled a rally in Redding later today and also planned
to spend Tuesday in California, a critical state where polls show
the White House race dead even.
   The four-day, one-hour flight of Discovery was the first shuttle
mission since Challenger exploded in January 1986, killing its
astronaut crew and schoolteacher passenger. Bush said last week it
was ``great to be back in space'' with the shuttle and that the
return was overdue.
   The high visibility of the landing offered the GOP nominee wide
publicity in his contest with Democrat Michael Dukakis, following a
quiet weekend at home for both candidates. Dukakis praised the
landing from afar.
   Bush was asked last week if he would invite Dukakis to join him
at the shuttle landing. He replied negatively, saying such an
invitation would politicize the event.
   Bush aides said he would be there by virtue of his office, not
as a candidate for the presidency. But the shuttle stop puts Bush
in a position to continue his battle for California's 47 electoral
votes.
   Both Bush and Dukakis are devoting substantial resources and
time in the state, where polls have shown the race a virtual dead
heat.
   The California trip comes on the heels of new reports about a
matter that continues to dog Bush _ his dealings with Panamanian
leader Manuel Antonio Noriega, who has been indicted in the United
States on drug trafficking charges.
   Former CIA chief Stansfield Turner said Sunday that Bush
fostered close ties with Noriega, but he did not know whether the
vice president played a role in reinstating the Panamanian ruler to
the CIA payroll in the 1980s.
   ``It's not a coincidence that every time Bush was in the
government, we were very friendly with the Noriegas and the
Marcoses (former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos) and that
ilk,'' said Turner, who headed the agency in the Carter
administration and now supports Dukakis.
   Turner, in a telephone interview from New Orleans, said Noriega
was taken off the CIA payroll after Turner became director in March
1977. But payments to Noriega resumed during the Reagan
administration, he said.
   Turner denied published reports that he had accused Bush of
instigating a resumption of CIA payments to Noriega.
</TEXT>
