<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     10-03 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penn State football Coach Joe Paterno will
meet his match this week _ a man for whom ``nothing has been normal
since'' he won a Paterno look-alike contest.
   Edward H. Ravitch, 54, was chosen last week by Penn State's
Homecoming Committee out of 71 entrants, including three dogs, said
homecoming Chairman Marc Weinberg.
   Ravitch meets the coach Friday morning, is part of Penn State's
homecoming parade that afternoon and meets with alumni that night,
Weinberg said. On Saturday, Ravitch will sit with the homecoming
king and queen as the Nittany Lions take on the Cincinnati Bearcats
in State College.
   Ravitch says he's thrilled with the limelight.
   ``I'm a ham,'' he said.
   Ravitch, a former teacher turned inventor, said it's been hard
trying to find clothes to match Paterno's.
   ``He wears his pants short, above his socks,'' Ravitch said.
``That's archaic.''
   A 1978 graduate of Temple, Ravitch said he has no hard feelings
toward Paterno after Temple's 45-9 drubbing by Penn State on
Saturday.
   ``I have great respect for him because he cares for his kids as
sons, not only as players,'' said Ravitch.
   But he said he'll take the opportunity to kid Paterno.
   ``I'll tell him we don't look alike,'' said Ravitch. ``I'm
better looking than he is.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oprah Winfrey promises to reveal how she
lost 54.2 pounds _ as soon as she loses 10 more pounds.
   The talk show host said losing the weight was her ``single
greatest accomplishment.''
   Winfrey's brief visit here and appearance before 4,000 people
raised about $40,000 for the United Way of the Central Carolinas
and the United Way of Gaston County.
   She decided to do the benefit Sunday, she said, because the
money would help battered women ``who are trying to turn their
lives around.''
   The cheerleading talk for women was punctuated with anecdotes
about herself _ childhood with her grandmother in Mississippi and
how she became bald after a visit to a hairdresser ordered by her
bosses at a Baltimore television station.
   As the show ended, Denver sculptor Marge Crunkleton presented
her with a clay statue of Sophia, Winfrey's character in ``The
Color Purple,'' which was filmed in Anson County.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympic diver Greg Louganis, who won two gold
Olympic medals in Seoul, has been honored with four silvers from
the Republic of the Marshall Islands.
   The dives that made Louganis famous _ the jackknife, twister and
back dive _ were captured on four silver coins issued by the
Marshall Islands, located between the Philippines and Hawaii.
   Three one-ounce $25 coins are sold in a set for $300; a 5-ounce,
$75 coin is offered for $300. The coin series are legal tender in
the Marshalls.
   ``I'm flattered because the coins are beautiful and because
they're honoring me on a coin,'' Louganis said while signing
autographs Sunday at the Long Beach Philatelic and Numismatic Show
at the city's convention center.
   Some proceeds from sales of the coin, the first to honor a
living American athlete, will benefit the Amateur Athletic Union
and United States Diving Inc., officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MERRIMACK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adrienne Brown, the 38-year-old wife of
soul singer James Brown, has been convicted of possession of the
drug PCP and fined $330, a court official said Monday.
   Mrs. Brown appeared in Merrimack District Court on Friday on the
drug charge. She also was charged with arson and criminal mischief
following a May 10 fire at a Bedford hotel where she and her
husband were staying, but the HIllsborough County attorney declined
to seek indictments on those charges.
   Mrs. Brown and her husband were in New Hampshire for a concert
performance.
   Last month, in Augusta, Ga., Mrs. Brown withdrew a guilty plea
to two drug charges stemming from arrests in April and May.
   The Browns have a ranch at Beech Island, S.C., near Augusta.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Joseph Saidu Momoh of Sierra
Leone will visit South Carolina this week to explore the historic
links between his West African nation and the Gullah culture of the
state's sea islands.
   Momoh will visit the Penn Center on St. Helena Island near
Beaufort on Thursday, said Emory Campbell, the director of the
center which works to preserve the islanders' history and
traditions.
   Gullah is the mix of English and various African dialects that
was spoken by slaves, many of them from Sierra Leone, who worked
the rice plantations on the sea islands.
</TEXT>
