<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Guerrillas-Colombia     10-03 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guerrillas-Colombia,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>18 Killed In Rebel Attack On Bus And Police Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas armed with guns
attacked an army patrol aboard a civilian bus in the southern
Amazon region, killing 13 soldiers and two civilians, the Defense
Ministry said Monday.
   In another incident in northern Colombia, guerrillas of the
National Liberation Army killed three policemen in the town of
Segovia, 190 miles north of Bogota, police said without elaborating.
   The attacks, which occurred Sunday, come after Colombia's six
rebel groups last month rejected a cease-fire and peace talks
offered by President Virgilio Barco. Some of the guerrillas
suggested the government negotiate social and economic changes,
which Barco rejected.
   The army patrol attacked in the southern state of Caqueta was
disobeying military orders by traveling on a civilian bus, the
Defense Ministry said in a statement.
   The bus, carrying about 25 soldiers and 15 civilians, was
attacked on a jungle road 40 miles south of the city of Florencia,
the ministry said.
   The rebels had placed an explosive charge on the road to stop
the bus, according to Gen. Edgar Pallares, the military governor of
Caqueta.
   In addition to those killed in the attack, 12 soldiers and five
civilians were wounded, Pallares said in the interview with the
Bogota radio station Caracol. The guerrillas who staged the bus
attack belonged to the Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces, he
said.
   Pallares was named governor of Caqeuta in June 1987 after
guerrillas killed 27 soldiers in an ambush.
</TEXT>
