<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1609EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Candidates-Ethics     10-03 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates-Ethics,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Probers Seek Candidate Views On Ethics Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Watergate and Iran-Contra investigators
asked George Bush and Michael Dukakis on Monday for their views on
proposals intended to prevent lawbreaking by government officials.
   The presidential candidates were asked, for example, whether
they would agree not to appoint anyone ``who has played a leading
partisan role in the most recent presidential election campaign''
as attorney general or director of the FBI, CIA or Internal Revenue
Service.
   The group, called the Special Committee for Iran-Contra and
Watergate Reform, includes lawyers who served on various Watergate
investigative or prosecutive staffs or with the House and Senate
investigative committees on the Iran-Contra affair.
   They said their proposals were drawn from recommendations made
by the American Bar Association and by Watergate and Iran-Contra
committees and investigative staffs. The proposals are ``designed
to prevent official lawlessness and promote government
accountability.''
   The results of their questionnaire, which also will be sent to
major congressional candidates, will be published Oct. 20.
   The candidates also were asked whether they favored or opposed:
   _Extending the naming of independent counsels to investigate
members of Congress as well as high executive branch officials.
   _Presidential pardons prior to trial of individuals indicted by
an independent counsel.
   _Legislation requiring the president to sign an authorization
before any covert action is begun and requiring him to notify
appropriate members of Congress within 48 hours.
   _Legislation barring the National Security Council staff from
intelligence-gathering or covert action.
   _Public financing for congressional candidates, a limit on funds
they could accept from political action committees, and prohibiting
members of Congress from receiving honoraria if they get higher
salaries.
   The group includes Sam Dash, former chief counsel of the Senate
Watergate Committee; John W. Nields Jr., former chief counsel of
the House Iran-Contra committee, and Richard Ben-Veniste, former
chief of the Watergate prosecution task force.
</TEXT>
