<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeltaTrial     10-03 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Trial,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Liability Trial Resumes, Renewing Legal Battle With
Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal liability trial over a 1985
Delta Air Lines crash that killed 137 people resumed Monday after
being in recess since early August.
   At stake in the non-jury trial before U.S. District Judge David
O. Belew Jr. is more than $100 million in claims from survivors and
relatives of victims. Delta is trying to have the government pay
part of the claims and the cost of replacing the Lockheed L-1011
jet destroyed in the crash of Flight 191 at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport.
   If Belew rules that the government should share blame in the
tragedy, a separate trial will determine how much the government
should pay.
   Neither Delta nor the government disputes that a violent
downburst of air, or microburst, from a rapidly developing
thunderstorm at the edge of the runway slammed the aircraft into
the ground. Meteorologists say there is no known way to forecast a
microburst.
   Delta claims a lack of communication between government air
traffic controllers and meteorologists prevented the flight crew
from getting the information they needed on the weather.
   Government lawyers argue the flight crew had the best view of
the storm.
   The recess was to accommodate the judge's schedule.
   Delta attorneys have finished presenting their case.
   Likely upcoming witnesses for the government include Gene
Skipworth, the last flight controller to communicate with the
Flight 191 crew before the crash, government attorney Roy Krieger
said.
   Krieger said the government also plans to present pilot experts,
including an Eastern Airlines official who will testify about
Delta's pilot training programs.
   Attorneys said witnesses will be called to support the
government's contention that Capt. Edward M. Connors of the Delta
flight crew was heavily using prescription drugs about the time of
the crash.
   Delta lawyers have disputed that claim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
