<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1928EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HorseSlaughter     10-03 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Horse Slaughter,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Find Another 140 Wild Horses Dead In Desert, Total Nears 300</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have found 140 more wild
horses apparently fatally shot in remote central Nevada, bringing
to 268 the number found dead in the area, the Bureau of Land
Management said Monday.
   The horses were discovered about 10 miles north of a site where
authorities had found 41 horses slain and 40 miles north of an area
where 87 horses had been shot, said Bob Stewart, a spokesman for
the federal agency.
   In all three cases, Stewart said the carcasses and bones
indicate the horses died over a six-month period starting about a
year ago.
   And while BLM investigators haven't stated yet that the earlier
shootings and the latest deaths are connected, ``I'd be surprised
if there's not a connection,'' Stewart said.
   Stewart added he didn't know if there was any link between the
central Nevada horse killings and reported shootings of several
wild horses at Silverpeak in southern Nevada.
   The Bureau of Land Management has increased surveillance of the
rangeland it controls in Nevada following the discovery in August
of the 41 slain horses. The second group of horses was found after
the agency got a tip from an unidentified person being questioned
about the first killings.
   A helicopter crew made the latest find in an area about 30 miles
north of Austin, and ground crews were to go to the isolated area
to confirm the cause of death, Stewart said.
   Terri Jay, director of the Nevada Commission for the
Preservation of wild Horses, has said rewards totaling $12,000 are
being offered for information leading to the arrest and conviction
of anyone involved in the shootings.
   More than 38,000 wild horses run the open range of 10 western
states, up from about 17,000 when Congress decided in 1971 to make
it a crime to harrass or kill wild horses on public lands.
   Nevada's wild horse herds are among the largest in the West,
with estimates of up to 28,000 of the animals roaming the state.
   At the turn of the century, there were some 2 million wild
horses in the West, but they were relentlessly hunted and
slaughtered for pet food and glue.
</TEXT>
