<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Hostages 7thLd-Writethru a0735 10-03 1069</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Hostages, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0735,980</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts graf 4, He spoke, with timing of announcement.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Administration Told Of Imminent Hostage Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of nine Americans held hostage in Lebanon
will be freed later today and handed over to the U.S. ambassador to
Syria, the Syrian foreign minister said.
   The foreign minister, Farouk al-Shara, told a midday news
conference at the United Nations he had ``good news for the
American people. ...
   ``One of the American hostages will be released within one hour
from now. He can be released any minute.''
   He spoke shortly after 1 p.m. EDT. There had been no report of
any hostage freed as of two hours later.
   Kidnappers holding three American professors and one Indian
educator said today they will free one hostage at the west Beirut
headquarters of the U.N. Relief and Works Agency for Palestinian
refugees.
   The announcement from Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of
Palestine came in a 36-word handwritten statement in Arabic
delivered to a western news agency in Beirut.
   The Syrian foreign minister said the hostage, whose name he said
he did not know, ``will be released in Lebanon, where he was
kidnapped, and the Syrian security forces will bring him to
Damascus to hand him over to the American ambassador.
   NBC News and CBS News and, in Beirut, the Voice of Lebanon radio
station reported that Alann Steen, 49, of Boston, was being
released. State Department officials said they could not confirm
the report.
   Steen's wife, Virginia, told The Associated Press in a telephone
interview that she had talked with the State Department hours
earlier.
   ``We're just waiting and watching like everybody else. ...
There's nothing confirmed yet,'' she said.
   President Reagan, asked during a picture-taking session if he
thought a hostage was about to be released, replied:
   ``It's hard to tell with what little information we have. As far
as we know, no hostages has been released yet. We have no word on
that.''
   Earlier, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the United
States had been told by another government that a hostage held by
Iranian sympathizers was being released imminently.
   Fitzwater said U.S. government officials ``received reports''
this morning that a hostage would be set free, and said that the
reports came from a ``third-party government in the region.''
   At the State Department, an official who spoke on condition of
anonymity said the latest report came from the Islamic Jihad
through the Syrian government.
   He said that was the group holding four American educators and
any release was likely to come from those four hostages. A total of
nine Americans are held hostage in Lebanon.
   The four educators believed held by Islamic Jihad, all captured
Jan. 24, 1987, are:
   Steen, a journalism professor at Beirut University College;
Jesse Turner, a visiting professor at the school; Robert Pohill, an
assistant business professor, and Mithileswar Singh, an Indian
citizen holding resident alien status in the United States.
   Nearly four months after they were taken captive, Turner said in
a videotape released by Islamic Jihad that Steen was suffering from
high blood pressure, was in ``pitiful'' health and was expected to
die at any moment despite being under a doctor's care.
   At the White House, Fitzwater said, ``We have received reports
that a hostage would be released,'' the presidential spokesman
said. ``But we have not received a name, and I cannot comment any
further.'' He said he did not know if the hostage purportedly to be
released is an American.
   During his daily White House news briefing, Fitzwater said the
tip off to a hostage release was relayed to U.S. officials in
Washington by an American embassy overseas.
   Last Friday, Reagan, while on a campaign trip to Chicago, denied
that the administration was steeped in negotiations with Iranian
officials in Geneva aimed at securing the release of at least five
American hostages by Oct. 7, as a report published in Israel held.
   Earlier in the week, however, the president, during a meeting in
New York with representatives of Persian Gulf states, told
reporters he was optimistic about the hostage situation. He also
said, however, that he didn't want to talk about it.
   In Beirut on Saturday, kidnappers holding three American
educators and an Indian professor said they would release one
hostage as a goodwill gesture.
   The group, the Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine,
did not say in its statement which of the hostages it would free,
or when.
   Fitzwater said, ``Our situation is the same. Our policy is the
same. No deals. No quid pro quos.''
   ``First of all, we need to wait and see that it does happen,''
he said, noting that ``we have had some similar kinds of reports in
the past ... that fell through. ... There is a concern, in the
sense that we don't know what their motives are in any of these
actions.''
   In an interview published today, the spiritual leader of an
umbrella group for kidnappers holding foreign hostages said he
thought the problem was nearing an end.
   ``When the hostage question shifts to high-level talks between
big powers, and they start speaking of deadlines, that means the
question is nearing its end,'' Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah,
spiritual head of Hezbollah, was quoted as saying in the weekly
Monday Morning magazine.
   The Christian al-Markazia news agency carried advance excerpts
of the interview on Sunday.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, is believed to be the umbrella group
for kidnappers holding most of the 17 foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   Besides the four taken prisoner in January 1987, these Americans
are also held hostage in Lebanon:
   _Thomas Sutherland, the dean of agriculture at the American
University in Beirut. He was taken prisoner June 9, 1885; Islamic
Jihad claimed responsibility.
   _Joseph James Cicippio, acting comptroller of the university,
captured Sept. 12, 1986. The Revolutionary Justice Organization
said it took Cicippio prisoner.
   _Terry Anderson, chief Mideastern correspondent of The
Associated Press, captured March 16, 1985. Islamic Jihad claimed
responsibility.
   _Frank Herbert Reed, director of the private Lebanon
International School, taken prisoner Sept. 9, 1986. The pro-Libyan
Arab Revolutionary Cells-Omar Moukhtar Forces took responsibility.
   _Edward Austin Tracy, a children's book author. He was captured
Oct. 21, 1986. The Revolutionary Justice Organization said he was
its prisoner.
   _Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, captured Feb. 17, 1988, in
a kidnapping claimed by the Oranigzaion of the Oppressed on Earth.
</TEXT>
