<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen     10-03 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Tosses Football, Says He's Ready for Quayle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen tossed a football
and declared himself relaxed and ready Monday for his vice
presidential debate with Republican Dan Quayle.
   ``We'll talk about the issues, those that are facing America,
and get away from some of these slogans,'' the Texas senator told
reporters during a break outside the hotel where he is preparing
for the Wednesday night confrontation in Omaha, Neb.
   Formal rehearsals for the debate were being videotaped in an
empty restaurant next door to Bentsen's hotel. Campaign aides set
up two lecterns, a table for the panelists and a dark backdrop to
duplicate debate conditions, with Rep. Dennis Eckart, D-Ohio,
playing the role of Quayle.
   Bentsen scheduled no campaign events until Tuesday, when he will
attend a rally before he flies to Omaha. His only public appearance
Monday was when he emerged from his hotel for a game of catch
football with former University of Texas players who included 1969
quarterback James Street.
   ``I think we're relaxed for it. I think we're ready for it,''
Bentsen said. Was he nervous? ``I'm not nervous,'' he said.
   Bentsen, 67, joked about the differences in age and physical
appearance between himself and the telegenic Quayle, 41.
   He said that when Michael Dukakis asked him to join the
Democratic ticket, he quipped to his wife, B.A., ``I hope he
doesn't just want another pretty face.''
   ``She said, `Lloyd, dream on, dream on','' he said.
   Bentsen spent the morning in meetings with a dozen aides before
he headed to the mock-debate studio in the afternoon. His advisers
included people from his Texas entourage and Dukakis' campaign
headquarters.
   ``I think he's obviously going to be well-prepared for this
experience,'' said George Christian, former press secretary to
President Johnson and a longtime Bentsen associate.
   ``Most people have already decided that Bentsen is more
qualified than Quayle, and I don't really believe that is the issue
of this debate,'' he said.
   ``I don't think this is going to be Quayle-bashing debate,''
Christian said, adding that he expected Quayle to perform well.
Instead, he said, Bentsen needed to attack Republican distortions
of such issues as crime and gun control.
   ``The Bush campaign has used a campaign of distortion to attempt
to paint Gov. Dukakis as a wild-eyed Northeastern liberal, and here
in Texas that has hurt,'' Christian said. ``Sen. Bentsen is one of
the better Democrats available to answer that sort of thing.''
   Texas has 29 electoral votes, third highest of any state, and
despite Bentsen's presence on the ticket the Democrats are trailing
in the polls.
   Susan Estrich, the Dukakis-Bentsen campaign manager, said the
staff was trying to help Bentsen express his achievements and
experience in concise ways that fit the format of the 90-minute
debate.
   ``I think he's in very good shape,'' she said.
   Estrich said it would not be fatal to the Democrats if Bentsen
fared poorly against Quayle.
   ``There are no make-or-break occasions in this campaign. There
are no do-or-die days,'' she said. ``We think we have five weeks to
convince the American people that this is the team for our future
and we're in a tough and competitive race.''
</TEXT>
