<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1551EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Crowds     10-03 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Crowds,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Thousands Watch With Pride as Discovery Returns</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crowd of 425,000 people
_ the second-largest ever to watch a space shuttle land _ cheered
proudly Monday as Discovery dropped from a deep-blue desert sky and
gently touched down on a dusty lake bed.
   About 410,000 people had funneled cars, motor homes, trailers
and trucks down a two-lane road to a public viewing area to witness
the completion of the first shuttle mission since Challenger
exploded 32 months ago. An additional 15,000 watched from a VIP
viewing area.
   ``It sends chills up my spine,'' 26-year-old Steve Bestwick of
Port Hueneme said as two sonic booms reverberated across Rogers Dry
Lake at 9:34 a.m., three minutes before the touchdown.
   Then the gleaming white-over-black Discovery appeared from the
west and made a fast turn high overhead.
   Bestwick marveled at how quickly it plummeted to the hard-packed
floor of the Mojave Desert.
   ``That's beautiful, but geez, it's so steep,'' he said.
   ``I had goosebumps all over,'' said Diane Bonds, who traveled
600 miles from Roy, Utah. ``I have always wanted to see one of
these and now I have.''
   The vehicles, many displaying American flags, started gathering
Sunday beside the 44-square-mile lake bed in the Mojave Desert 80
miles north of Los Angeles. Some had license pates from states as
distant as Florida.
   Most of the shuttle watchers felt Discovery's safe return would
reinvigorate America's manned space program, which had been
virtually paralyzed following the Challenger disaster.
   ``I certainly hope it does,'' said Betty Davis, 66, of Goleta.
``We need to spend our money on this. It's exciting and patriotic.''
   After the landing, most viewers sprinted for their vehicles,
which threw a huge cloud of talcum powder-like dust into the air as
they crowded toward the single exit gate out of the parking area.
   The two-lane blacktop highway is the only road leading away from
the viewing site.
   Air Force spokesman Lt. Col. George Neiss said 109,000 vehicles
carried an estimated 410,000 people to the public viewing site by
Monday morning.
   Only one larger crowd had ever gathered to watch a shuttle land:
an estimated 500,000 for the shuttle Columbia on July 4, 1982, when
President and Mrs. Reagan greeted the astronauts.
   Ellery Sabin, 66, who had traveled from Ludington, Mich.,
perched atop his 33-foot motor home and surveyed the recreational
vehicles, tents, cars and trucks stretching across the desert
dotted with bizarrely twisted Joshua trees.
   ``This is crazy,'' he exclaimed. ``I've been around crowds, but
this is really something.
   ``There's such a sense of pride here,'' Sabin said. ``We need to
continue with the space program. I don't like to see them throw
taxpayer money away on a lot of things, but this is certainly worth
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
