<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BombDeath     10-03 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bomb Death,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Retrieve Bomb That Killed Boy, Injured Five Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said Monday they retrieved
most of a bomb that killed a 9-year-old boy and injured five other
children but said they haven't learned the origins of what the
children called a ``big firecracker.''
   Until laboratory tests are complete, probably later this week,
no further information about the Sunday night explosion will be
disclosed, said Lou Iliano, resident agent of the federal Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
   The explosion killed Max Herrera and injured his brother and
sister and three other children, all ages 4 to 11, in a south Fort
Worth neighborhood.
   The children were playing with the ``large and volatile'' pipe
bomb when it detonated, said David Carr, fire department district
chief.
   ``We've heard the kids were passing it around, trying to light
it with matches,'' he said. ``They had it in their hands. Whether
they lit it or not, we don't know. ... They were playing with it,
but we can't be sure at this time where it came from.''
   However, the dead boy's older sister, Rosie Arredonda, 24, told
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram, ``some kid gave Max the bomb. Max lit
it and it went up.''
   Ms. Arredonda said the Herrera children had accompanied their
mother to a grocery store a block away, but left the store to play
with their friends.
   The children were playing with some type of pipe and some
matches, and at one point, a woman took the device away from the
children, witnesses said.
   The blast spewed fragments of the bomb as far as 150 feet,
although nerly 75 percent of it remained intact, Carr said.
   ``We've got the whole (bomb),'' Iliano said. ``I was surprised
at how much there was left.''
</TEXT>
