<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     10-03 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudanese Prime Minister To Begin Peace Talks With Rebel Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi and rebel
leader John Garang will begin peace talks aimed at ending a
5-year-old civil war that has displaced thousands of people in
Sudan, a newspaper reported Monday.
   The English-language daily Sudan Times said the meeting probably
would be held late this month in Kampala, capital of neighboring
Uganda.
   El-Mahdi received a message last week from Garang expressing the
rebel leader's willingness to start negotiations, the newspaper
said. The message was delivered through Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni, it said.
   If held, the meeting would be the second between el-Mahdi and
the former army officer who in 1983 launched a rebellion in
southern Sudan against the Moslem-dominated government. A June 1986
meeting in Ethiopia's capital, Addis Ababa, failed to end the
fighting.
   Garang's Sudan People's Liberation Army claims control over most
of the southern countryside, while government forces dominate large
towns and cities.
   The rebels, mostly animists and Christians, demand the
government grant them more autonomy and initiate economic reforms.
   But some refugees have accused the guerrillas of taking their
crops and cattle and recruiting their young people.
   About 600 people fleeing the civil war in the countryside took
refuge in a town where thousands are fighting malnutrition and
diseases, the Sudan News Agency reported today. The new refugees
recently arrived in the town of el-Muglad, about 460 miles south of
Khartoum, which already is home to 5,000 people who escaped the
fierce battles between the rebels and government, the agency
reported. It did not give the exact date of the refugees' arrival.
   Half a dozen people were dying every day in el-Muglad from
spreading diseases caused by malnutrition, the agency said.
   Since 1983, about 820,000 people have left their homes in
southern Sudan as a result of the civil war. Some settled in
government-controlled towns and cities, while others wandered north
to Khartoum, and eastwards into Ethiopia. This summer, at least
8,000 people died of starvation while fleeing the war.
   El-Meiram, another town 500 miles south of Khartoum, houses
about 20,000 refugees under conditions of malnutrition and disease,
the agency said. About 2,550 people had died in el-Meiram between
June and August, the agency said.
   Tensions were mounting in the town because thousands of Arab
tribesmen and their cattle were expected to arrive there soon,
swelling the size of the town to about 70,000 people, the agency
said.
   The United States and other donor governments have recently
succeeded in moving large quantities of food and other supplies
into the Sudan, after months of difficulties that had frustrated
relief agencies, according to Jay F. Morris, deputy administrator
of the U.S. Agency for International Development. Arrangenments are
being made for the agency to provide $l.5 million to the Sudan
government's Relief and Rehabilitation Commission, according to
Deputy Spokesman Phyllis Oakley.
   Morris said that on Sept. 25 the guerrillas tried and failed to
shoot down a transport plane carrying U.S. supplies from Khartoum
to the city of Juba. He said the rebels also have threatened to
shoot down flights headed for Aweil, where 100 deaths a day from
starvation have been reported.
   ``We deplore these outrageous actions which target trucks and
planes that are undertaking humanitarian missions,'' Mrs. Oakley
said.
   Last month Mauris Lawya, the governor of Equatoria province,
said a convoy of 912 trucks bound for Juba under army escort had to
return to Yie because of rebel attacks. He added that in another
convoy only 96 out of 1,080 trucks were able to to reach Juba, 750
miles south of the capital.
   The rebels fear the government will use relief convoys to bring
reinforcements to areas the rebels control, which they claim
include 90 percent of the countryside in the south.
</TEXT>
