<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Eisele     10-03 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Eisele,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral Thursday for `Father Earthquake'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Louis J. Eisele, a Jesuit priest
and seismologist who was the first person to record an Alaskan
earthquake that killed 114 people in 1964, died Monday after a
brief illness. He was 76.
   Eisele, also a physicist, taught at the Roman Catholic Spring
Hill College in Mobile and operated its seismographic station for
more than 40 years.
   Eisele, nicknamed ``Father Earthquake,'' reported data on major
quakes to the National Earthquake Information Service and was the
first to record the March 2, 1964, quake. It registered 8.5 on the
Richter scale of ground motion.
   Eisele invented the Eisele AC Transducer pen and ink seismic
station. This year, he had installed a new seismographic electronic
recording unit at Spring Hill, the first such system in the country.
   Survivors include three sisters and a brother.
   His funeral will be Thursday at St. Joseph's Chapel on campus.
</TEXT>
