<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WaterTankCollapse     10-03 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Water Tank Collapse,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighborhood Rebuilds After Water Tank Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This financially strapped city is
keeping its promise to replace houses destroyed in July when a
790,000-gallon water tank collapsed and released a wall of water
downhill into a poor neighborhood.
   The July 22 flash flood killed three people, injured more than
20 and destroyed at least 13 adobe and wood homes. Cars, furniture
and parts of houses were washed to the bottom of the slope.
   The next day, Mayor Jaime Bermudez visited the neighborhood and
promised the city would provide medical care and replace everything
that could be replaced.
   Two months later, the city is erecting cinderblock replacement
houses.
   ``The flood forced the city to build me a new home, which is
better than what I had,'' Elida Molina said last week. ``Our new
home is going to have an indoor bathroom, a separate kitchen and a
bedroom. We had only one room before. Things are looking bright
now.''
   But her enthusiasm is tempered.
   ``Three boys that I knew were killed,'' she said. ``They can
never be replaced.''
   The water was released when a 75-foot-long wall of the concrete
water tank gave way. Officials believe heavy rain might have
weakened the tank's foundation.
   There was no immediate word Monday how much the disaster is
costing the city. City spokesman Mario Trejo was in a cabinet
meeting with the mayor in preparation for his state-of-the-city
speech. The money will come out of the public works and maintenance
department.
   Juarez, a city of 1.5 million people, has an operating budget of
less than $12 million and has been operating in the red since 1986,
so the rebuilding just adds to the deficit.
   In addition to the new houses, the city has provided a doctor
who set up a tent office in the neighborhood to provide free
medical attention and prescriptions.
   ``I'm going to be here for as long as people need medical
attention,'' said Dr. Leonardo Ruiz, who sees about 10 patients
daily. ``There aren't any more residents with serious injuries.
They have all gotten better.''
   ``We never expected this kind of help,'' said resident Maria
Santos Garcia. ``They tell us that in two weeks all the homes will
be rebuilt.''
   In the meantime, families are staying with relatives.
   What hasn't gotten better is some children's fear, Ms. Santos
said.
   ``When it starts raining, you see a lot of children crying and
running to their moms,'' she said. ``Some of the children are
afraid to go to sleep because they are afraid of waking up in
water.''
   The children get help from social workers who visit
periodically, she said.
</TEXT>
