<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Lawyer     10-03 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Lawyer,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Rule on Representation of Poor in Civil Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to decide
whether federal courts have the authority to force lawyers to
represent in non-criminal cases people too poor to pay for legal
help.
   The justices said they will hear the appeal of John E. Mallard
of Fairfield, Iowa, who was ordered to represent prison inmates in
a suit charging prison officials with mistreatment and other
misconduct.
   Two current inmates and one former inmate at the Iowa state
penitentiary in Fort Madison said prison guards and officials filed
false disciplinary reports against them, physically mistreated them
and endangered their lives by revealing they were informants.
   A federal judge picked Mallard from a list of lawyers to
represent the three because they are too poor to hire attorneys.
   Mallard sought to be excused on grounds he lacked experience in
trial cases and that the federal courts lacked the power to require
an unwilling attorney to represent someone who requests a lawyer in
a civil case.
   Courts routinely assign lawyers to represent indigent defendants
in criminal cases and the lawyers are paid, at taxpayer expense,
generally a fraction of what they would receive normally.
   In civil rights cases like the one in the case acted on Monday,
lawyers are paid expenses and may be paid a part of any damages won
by their clients.
   U.S. District Judge Harold D. Vietor denied Mallard's motion to
be excused from the inmates' suit.
   ``Mallard can hardly claim incompetence when he has filed an
18-page brief in support of this motion that demonstrates thorough
research, careful reasoning and effective writing,'' Vietor said.
``Despite his renunciation of any claim to being a litigator,
Mallard does have litigation experience. Mallard is not
incompetent.''
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld Vietor's decision
last December.
   The Iowa attorney general's office urged the Supreme Court to
reject Mallard's appeal. The office acknowledged that it is a
hardship for lawyers to be forced to take cases without being paid
a fee.
   But, the attorney general's office said, ``The attorney
appointment process ... spreads the risk of that hardship, makes
more efficient and effective the utilization of practicing
attorneys and is soundly rooted in the ethical obligation of each.''
   The case is Mallard vs. U.S. District Court, 87-1490.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1646EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DroughtAid     10-03 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Aid,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Begin Signing Up for Federal Drought Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers began signing up for payments Monday
under a $3.9 billion benefits package to aid victims of the drought
that hammered the nation's croplands over the summer.
   ``The telephones have been real busy all morning with calls from
people asking for appointments,'' said James Anderson, director of
the Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service (ASCS)
office in Brown County, S.D.
   The Agriculture Department agency is in charge of parceling out
aid under the program President Reagan signed into law on Aug. 11
to offset losses among farmers from a drought that reduced the U.S.
harvest an estimated 31 percent.
   Brisk business was reported at ASCS offices in the nothern Grain
Belt, where blistering sun and scarce rainfall wrecked the spring
wheat crop. In most places, though, there was no stampede on the
first day of a lengthy sign-up period that ends in March.
   Across the midcontinent, many farmers were still in their fields
harvesting what was left of their crops after the drought. Only
after they are finished will they know the full extent of their
losses _ prerequisite for receiving benefits under the program.
   ``It's a production-loss program,'' said Dale Hertlein,
executive director of the Fayette County, Ohio, ASCS office. ``So
to know exactly what the guy has lost, he will have to finish
harvesting first.''
   In Texas, ASCS state executive director Terence G. Harman said
quiet prevailed at most of the agency's 239 county offices.
   ``We're in harvest in a lot of the crops down here ... and so
we're involved in a lot of other things rather than standing in
line,'' he said. ``I think there will be a gradual trickle'' of
farmers coming in to apply for the benefits in the months ahead.
   ``I'm sure there must be somebody in the state of Iowa who is
done with the harvest,'' said Bob Furleigh, state ASCS director.
But he said there was no flood of farmers at the agency's offices.
   ASCS has county offices nationwide and in some cases farmers who
have wrapped up the harvest can do much of the ``paperwork'' of
applying for benefits on computer terminals in those offices.
   Sometimes, farmers can obtain a check on the day that they apply
for the aid. In other cases, the length of the wait varies.
   The cost of the assistance remains uncertain, although officials
say it could exceed the $3.9 billion price tag estimated when the
measure won congressional approval.
   Among highlights for eligible producers:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>LIVESTOCK AID</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Livestock producers with annual gross revenues of less than $2.5
million can get either half of their feed costs from the government
or surplus grain owned by the department's Commodity Credit Corp.
at discounted prices.
   Those eligible are producers of cattle, sheep, goats, swine,
poultry, horses, mules and donkeys used for food or in the
production of food, and fish used for commercial food production.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CROP AID</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop producers with gross annual revenues of less than $2
million can receive payments for losses greater than 35 percent of
normal production.
   They are eligible for aid equal to 90 percent of losses in
excess of 75 percent of normal production.
   Producers also are eligible for assistance equal to 65 percent
of losses between 35 percent of normal production and 75 percent.
   These losses are calculated on the basis of ``payment rates''
set by the Agriculture Department and which vary from one crop to
another.
   On that basis, some of the payment rates will involve:
   _For crops participating in farm programs, such as wheat, feed
grains, cotton and rice, the payment rate will be the target price,
a figure set by Congress, adjusted by the secretary of agriculture
and normally used to calculated ``deficiency,'' or income support,
payments for farmers.
   _For non-participating program crops, the payment rate will be
the county rate for price-support loans.
   _For tobacco, the payment rate will be the national average
price-support loan rate for the type of tobacco involved.
   _For sugar beets and sugar cane, the payment rate will be ``a
level determined by the secretary to be fair and reasonable'' in
relation to 1988-crop price supports for beets and cane.
   _For soybeans and non-program crops, the payment rate will be
the average commodity price received in the state for the previous
five years, not counting the high and low years.
   Among other provisions, farmers who received advance deficiency,
or income-support, payments ``may not have to refund (those)
otherwise unearned payments on crop losses up to 35 percent of
normal production.''
   An owner of 1,000 or fewer acres of trees planted for commercial
purposes will be eligible for 65 percent federal assistance if
losses of the 1987 or 1988 tree seedlings is greater than 35
percent, adjusted for normal mortality.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
