<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WrongBones     10-03 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wrong Bones,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wife of Misidentified Airman Says it was Like Death Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of an Air Force officer whose
plane crashed during the Vietnam War testified Monday that the
misidentification of some bone fragments as his was like giving him
a death sentence should he still be alive in Southeast Asia.
   ``The message went out to those countries: `Don't you ever
return that guy because this would be a real humiliation''' to the
U.S. government, Anne Hart told a federal judge hearing a
multimillion-dollar lawsuit brought by Mrs. Hart, her daugher
Gillian and her mother-in-law Vera Hart.
   The 45-year-old Pensacola woman was was the first witness in the
non-jury, civil trial over the military's misidentification of
seven bone fragments found at a plane crash site in Laos as being
the remains of Lt. Col. Thomas Hart III.
   The military withdrew the identification after an outside expert
hired by Mrs. Hart said it was impossible to tell if the fragments
belonged to her husband or anyone else.
   The lawsuit claims the three suffered emotional distress as a
result of the misidentification, which they contend was
intentional, and they are seeking an unspecified amount put only in
the multimillion-dollar range. Five other children originally
listed as plaintiffs have been dropped from the suit.
   Senior U.S. District Judge Winston Arnow ruled Jan. 12 that Mrs.
Hart suffered from severe emotional distress, leaving only the
matter of damages to be decided in her portion of the case.
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs will try to show Hart's mother also
was emotionally distressed and that his daughter suffered from
bulemia, an eating disorder that caused her to lose 30 pounds.
   ``It's very similar to living without any skin,'' Anne Hart said
of her life since the dispute over the bones' identification began
in 1985.
   She described the initial news of her husband's plane crash Dec.
21, 1972, and then the identification of the remains more than 13
years later as like being ``hit with a two-by-four.''
   She said she recovered enough to lead a relatively normal life
after the crash, but she has been unable to do so following the
misidentification of the remains and the military's insistance on
burying them as her husband.
   A self-proclaimed ``Army brat'' whose father was a military
physician, she accused Army and Air Force officials of lying to her
and causing her to become so disillusioned with the government she
once revered that she had to seek professional counseling for
emotional distress.
   She said she has has trouble sleeping and gave up activities
with the National League of Families, a support group for families
of servicemen who are missing in action or had been prisoners. She
testified she spends most of her waking hours as a volunteer worker
at the Pensacola Veterans' Center, where she can be with people who
feel the same way.
   She also testified she has left her children to fend for
themselves, failed to pay bills although she had the money to do so
and can see no reason for living, although she lacks the courage to
commit suicide.
   Hart was one of 16 crew members aboard the AC-130 Spectre
gunship when it was shot down near Pakse, Laos.
   Two crewmen were rescued and one was immediately identified as
killed, but the other 13 has been listed as missing until the crash
site was excavated by U.S. Army and Laotian authorities in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
