<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Sudan,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Says Sudanese Rebels Attack Aid Convoys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudanese rebels have attacked aid shipments,
reversing their previous practice of letting them proceed safely,
the State Department said Monday.
   Jay F. Morris, deputy administrator of the United States' Agency
for International Development, said that nine drivers and
assistants from Kenya are dead or missing and an unknown number of
relief trucks were abandoned Sept. 8, when forces of the Sudanese
Peoples Liberation Army attacked a convoy driving from Yei to Juba.
   Morris said that on Sept. 25 the rebels tried unsuccessfully to
shoot down a transport plane carrying U.S. supplies from Khartoum
to Juba. He said the rebels have threatened any flights heading for
Aweil, where 100 deaths a day from starvation have been reported.
   ``We deplore these outrageous actions which target trucks and
planes that are undertaking humanitarian missions,'' said
department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   She said arrangements are being made for AID to provide $1.5
million to the Sudanese government. A U.S. team has been sent to
help the Khartoum government and other donors to work out a plan to
meet the area's needs.
   Christian and other guerrillas in The Sudan, which is directly
south of Egypt, have been fighting since 1983 against the country's
Moslem-led government.
   According to Morris, thousands of refugees have been driven from
the countryside into towns, especially in the southern part of
Kordofan province, which is near the area that has seen the most
fighting. The United States and other governments have recently
moved large amounts of food and other supplies into the area, after
months of difficulties.
   The rebels fear the government will use relief convoys to bring
reinforcements to areas the rebels control, which they claim
include 90 percent of the countryside in the south.
</TEXT>
