<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1716EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hostages-Singh     10-03 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages-Singh,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Professor Thought He Was Safe in Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends say Mithileshwar Singh, the Indian professor taken
hostage in Lebanon with three Americans last January, thought he
was safe in that strife-torn land.
   J.B. Curtis, president of now-defunct Western Colorado
University, where the 60-year-old Singh taught, called him a
``dedicated educator.''
   ``He had a contract and would honor his agreement. He enjoyed
his students and believed he was safe,'' Curtis said of Singh, who
is a resident alien of the United States.
   A family friend, Mary Pillais, said Singh told her during a
visit in September 1986 ``there was nothing to be afraid of. He
said there were guards at the university to protect them.''
   Another friend, Ruth Dale, said Singh's wife Lalmoney did not
want to return to his post at Beirut University College ``because
of all the bombing and fighting. But Mr. Singh said there was
nothing to worry about. The fighting was miles away.''
   Singh was born in Varanasi, India, Dec. 13, 1927. He taught
eight years at the University of Agra and eight years as an
assistant professor at the University of Gorakhpur before coming to
the United States in 1965 to do graduate work at the University of
Oregon in Eugene.
   He graduated from the University of Oregon in 1968 with a
master's degree in business administration, and received his
doctorate from Western Colorado, an independent-study institution
that operated in 1970-83, according to Beirut University College.
   Singh taught at the University of Wisconsin-Platteville in
1970-72 as an assistant professor of business management. He also
taught business at Milton College, Wis., before moving to Grand
Junction, Colo., in 1976.
   In Grand Junction, he taught at Western Colorado University and
the Western Colorado School of Business, which later merged with
Technical Trades Institute, a vocational and business school still
in operation.
   Singh was offered a one-year visiting professorship in Beirut in
the fall of 1983. He ``liked the students and the school and when
they asked him to stay on, he did,'' said Curtis.
   Curtis said Singh later was named chairman of the business
department on the Beirut campus.
   He was kidnapped Jan. 24, 1987 and his abduction was claimed by
the Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine.
   The Singhs have no children, Curtis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
