<HEAD>Vandals Prompt Closing of High School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school was closed Monday because
vandals broke in over the weekend and spilled hazardous chemicals,
released laboratory animals, toppled filing cabinets and drove off
in two drivers' education cars, authorities said.
   Fifteen people were treated at hospitals and released for
complaints associated with the chemicals.
   The vandals broke a bottle containing a mixture of several
chemicals, including the pesticide malathion, sending noxious fumes
through cooling ducts in the three-story, windowless Hialeah-Miami
Lakes High School, said Fire Chief Harry Killingsworth.
   A python was among the animals released. The intruders also
emptied refrigerators and scattered papers.
   The cars were not found and no arrests had been made.
   County Superintendent Joseph Fernandez said classes would resume
Tuesday.
