<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2028EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PesticideAnalysis     10-03 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pesticide Analysis,400</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Many Pesticides Undetected in Food Supply, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analyses used by federal agencies to check on
pesticides in the nation's food supply can't detect about half the
pesticides permitted to be used, a research arm of Congress
reported Monday.
   Food is checked by the Food Safety Inspection Service of the
Agriculture Department, which analyzes meat and poultry; the
department's Agricultural Marketing Service, which analyzes eggs;
and the Food and Drug Administration, part of the Health and Human
Services Department, which analyzes all other foods.
   As a routine matter, the agencies can use only ``multi-residue''
analyses _ methods that reveal the concentration of a number of
compounds. Except in special cases, methods useful for detecting
only one compound are too expensive to use, the congressional
Office of Technology Assessment reported.
   There are 316 pesticide active ingredients for which the
Environmental Protection Agency has established maximum permissible
concentration of residues in food, or tolerances.
   The OTA report said the five multi-residue methods used by the
Food and Drug Administration can detect only 163 compounds.
   Similarly, these methods can detect only 10 of 74 compounds with
pending or temporary tolerances, 25 of 56 with no established
tolerance and 92 of 297 breakdown products, impurities or other
``pesticide-associated chemicals.''
   The report presented less detail on the Food Safety Inspection
Service, but did say the four methods used there can detect about
40 chemicals.
   ``FSIS has identified 10 highly ranked pesticides it would like
to monitor routinely but cannot using its multiresidue methods,''
the report said.
   FDA spokesman Emil Corwin said the agency had not had a chance
to study the report and therefore could not comment. A chemist to
whom he referred detailed questions did not answer.
   USDA spokeswoman Karen Stuck said she was seeking comment from
agency officials.
   Diane Baxter, staff scientist for the National Coalition Against
the Misuse of Pesticides, said the lack of coverage in routine
monitoring ``worries us very much.''
   She said fungicides of a class called ``EBDC'' whose breakdown
products cause cancer and the herbicide glyphosate are chemicals
that need routine monitoring.
   Results from what analyses could be performed showed a low
failure rate. The report said 2.5 percent of about 12,700 samples
last year showed excessive residues, but the sampling was not
random.
   Samples contained a higher percentage of fruits and vegetables
than the general food supply, and were biased toward food-pesticide
combinations known to yield residue problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Deaver     10-03 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaver,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deaver Files Appeal of Conviction for Lying to Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential aide Michael K. Deaver
filed a formal appeal Monday of his conviction that he lied under
oath when questioned by a grand jury and a House subcommittee about
his lobbying activities.
   The former deputy White House chief of staff was given a
suspended three-year sentence and a $100,000 fine last month by
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
   The judge also ordered Deaver to perform 1,500 hours of
community service and barred him from lobbying the federal
government for pay during a three-year period the former White
House aide was placed on probation.
   A longtime friend of President Reagan and his wife, Nancy,
Deaver became a Washington lobbyist after resigning from his White
House job in May 1985.
   He was convicted last year of lying in 1986 to a grand jury and
the House Energy and Commerce oversight subcommittee that
investigated whether his lobbying of former Reagan administration
colleagues violated conflict-of-interest laws.
   The formal notice of appeal, signed by Deaver and his lawyer,
Herbert J. Miller Jr., was filed in U.S. District Court.
</TEXT>
