<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Soviet-Peace     10-03 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Soviet-Peace,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Propose World's Armies Set Aside Units For U.N.
Peacekeeping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union says it is ready to set
aside troops for a reserve of U.N. peacekeepers to be sent to
global flashpoints, if other nations do the same.
   It also suggests posting U.N. peacekeepers in ``explosive areas
of the world.''
   Carolyn Dulin, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Mission, said of
Moscow's latest proposals, ``These are interesting ideas; I would
not say they are good or bad.''
   She said, however, that the suggestions are the latest in an
overall Soviet package of proposals for international security
which Washington opposes on the grounds it would replace the
existing U.N. charter.
   Last Thursday, the U.N. peacekeeping operations were awarded the
Nobel Peace Prize for 1988.
   The latest Soviet proposal, first introduced as a document to
the General Assembly on Sept. 22 and now bound for assembly
consideration, calls for ``the establishment of a reserve of
military observers and armed forces of the United Nations.''
   ``The U.S.S.R. is prepared to participate in the formation on a
mutual basis with other countries of a system of personnel training
for service in the United Nations troops,'' it added.
   The Soviets said they would be willing to provide their own
military units in appropriate peacekeeping situations.
   The five permanent members of the Security Council _ the United
States, Britain, France, China and the Soviet Union _ usually do
not send troops to join peacekeeping units to avoid accusations
that the superpowers or former colonial powers are trying to
involve their armed forces in local conflicts.
   There have been exceptions, such as the British peacekeepers in
Cyprus and Americans in Lebanon, when the countries requesting
peacekeepers do not object.
   The Soviet proposal also suggested an expanded use of U.N.
peacekeepers ``in situations where accusations are made of outside
interference for the purpose of destabilizing governments,'' and
putting U.N. observers along the borders of a nation fearing
foreign interference ``at the request of that country alone.''
   Last week, the Soviets assailed the U.N. peacekeepers in
Pakistan and Afghanistan for allegedly not investigating Soviet and
Afghan claims that Pakistan was repeatedly violating the April 14
Geneva accord on Afghanistan. The Soviets and Afghans accused
Pakistan of trying to undermine Afghanistan.
   The accord calls for Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan and for
non-interference in the internal affairs of Afghanistan and
Pakistan.
   The Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman, Gennady Gerasimov, said
last week the fate of future peacekeeping forces is in question
because of this issue.
   The Soviets could use their seat on the Security Council to
block establishment of peacekeeping units.
   The newest Soviet U.N. peacekeeping proposals are part of the
``Comprehensive System of International Peace and Security'' that
Moscow has introduced for three General Assembly sessions, so far
without success.
   ``It's no secret that we're against the `comprehensive
system,''' said U.S. spokeswoman Dulin on Monday. ``We feel that's
sort of a reforming of the U.N. Charter, which we feel is not
necessary.''
   Other Western U.N. ambassadors on the Security Council have said
they think some Soviet proposals have merit; their objection is
only to the overall package, which they say would replace the
Charter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Iran     10-03 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says Mild U.N. Action on Chemical Weapons Encouraged Iraqi
Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Monday the Security Council's
meek criticism of the Iraqis' use of poison gas encouraged Iraq
``to continue ... its horrifying use of chemical weapons'' against
the Kurdish minority.
   The allegation was made by Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velyati in his address to the 43rd session of the General Assembly.
   Iraq has acknowledged using chemical weapons against Iran in the
8-year-old war between the Persian Gulf nations, but has denied
using such weapons against its own Kurdish rebels battling for
autonomy in northwestern Iraq.
   Iraq also has accused Iran of using chemical weapons in the war
_ a charge Iran has denied.
   The U.S. State Department has said it has evidence Iraq used
poison gas against the Kuridsh insurgents.
   Velyati told the General Assembly, ``While the Security Council
dealt in two different resolutions, 612 and 620, with the Iraqi use
of chemical weapons, the mild nature of the resolutions in fact
encouraged Iraq to continue on a massive scale its horrifying use
of chemical weapons.''
   Resolution 612 condemned the use of chemical weapons and 620
criticized the use of such weapons ``against Iranians'' without
mentioning Iraq.
   Western diplomats have said the Security Council did not
specifically denounce Iraq because it hoped to avoid complicating
the Iran-Iraq peace talks.
   Velayati said that after the Security Council resolutions Iraq
``used on a large scale chemical weapons against its own Kurds in
the northern part of the country.''
   The foreign minister again blamed Iraq for starting the war and
claimed the Iraqis had seized more than 700 prisoners of war since
a U.N.-mediated cease-fire began Aug. 20.
   Velyati gave no indication of any change in Iran's positon on
the disputed Shatt-al-Arab estuary, which is the southern boundary
between the two nations and is Iraq's only waterway outlet to the
Persian Gulf.
   A boundary treaty was established in 1975, but Iraq has
repudiated it and claims Iran abrogated the accord in 1979. Iraq
wants control over both banks of the Shatt-al-Arab to ensure a
secure passage to the gulf.
   That is a main issue stalling peace negotiations that remained
deadlocked after a session at the United Nations on Saturday. It
was the first meeting between Iran and Iraq since talks in Geneva
on Sept. 13.
   Velayati, without naming Israel, also said the conflicts in the
Middle East cannot be resolved until ``this racist regime is
eradicated and the rights of Palestinians to self-determination and
the establishment of an independent government within their own
territory are restored.
</TEXT>
