<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NASD-MarketHalts     10-03 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NASD-Market Halts,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OTC Dealers Accept Market-Wide Trading Halts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers
announced Monday that despite its opposition in principle to
market-wide trading halts, it would go along with one at the
request of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Although the NASD, which governs the over-the-counter stock
market, repeated its objections in detail, the new position by its
board of governors is seen as removing an obstacle to SEC approval
of a proposed one-year experiment with a trading halt rule.
   In July, the New York Stock Exchange, the nation's largest stock
market, and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the largest market for
stock index futures, submitted a so-called ``circuit breaker'' plan
that would halt trading across markets for one hour if the Dow
Jones industrial average fell 250 points or more or if the futures
market dropped by a parallel amount. The plan calls for a two-hour
halt if the Dow fell an additional 150 points.
   If the NASD had refused to budge, it would have made
implementation of the pilot program difficult because the SEC does
not have authority to impose an across-the-board market halt
without a presidential order.
   Ever since the stock market crash last Oct. 19, when the Dow
fell 508 points, securities industry and government officials have
been trying to agree on measures to calm volatility and restore
investor confidence.
   One of the few concrete proposals to emerge has been the circuit
breaker concept first advanced by the White House task force headed
by investment banker and now Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady.
An administration working group that included the heads of the
regulatory agencies affected, including the SEC, later endorsed it.
   SEC spokeswoman Mary McCue said of the NASD position, ``We
believe it's a constructive action and it's generally consistent
with the recommendations of the working group.''
   She said the agency has not yet acted on the submission from the
NYSE and Merc, but said action on such proposals is generally taken
within 90 days.
   Those who favor circuit breakers say the stock and futures
markets in effect behave as one market because high-speed computer
linkages. Proponents argue that it is better to artificially stop
trading at a predetermined point before one market breaks down,
sending sell orders cascading into markets that remain open.
   However, NASD Joseph R. Hardiman said in a statement that
circuit breakers ``are likely to increase market volatility rather
than curb it.''
   ``The closer a market gets to a circuit breaker level, the more
likely it is of reaching as sellers rush to execute orders under
the wire. Academic studies also indicate that markets are the most
volatile at the opening or reopening of a security following a
trading halt,'' he said.
   But the NASD statement said its board ``acknowledged that there
may be unacceptable risks imposed on any market which remains open
when all its counterparts have closed.''
   ``We're recognizing we're living in the real world here and if
all other markets close, we can't just stand here and be the market
of last liquidity,'' said NASD spokesman Bob Ferri.
   The new NASD stance is effective through the end of 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
