<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland     10-03 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post in New Polish Cabinet Reported Offered to Moderate Foe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate opposition figure who founded a
group to promote private enterprise said he was offered a position
Monday in the government being formed by new Prime Minister
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski.
   Unconfirmed reports said other members of the opposition also
were approached about serving in the government.
   Aleksander Paszynski, who edits a magazine for private home
builders and who founded the pro-business Economic Society, said in
a telephone interview that he was offered a position at a meeting
with Rakowski on Monday.
   The Economic Society for a year has been stymied in its bid for
official registration.
   Paszynski said Rakowski's offer concerned the Ministry of
Construction and Local Planning and the job would deal with
apartment construction. He declined to be more specific and said he
had not made up his mind whether to accept.
   ``I can say only one thing, that he (Rakowski) is really
intensively searching for new faces,'' said Paszynski. ``I can't
tell you what the results of this search are.''
   Rakowski, a member of the ruling Communist Party Politburo, was
appointed prime minister on Sept. 27 and is scheduled to present
his Cabinet for approval by the Sejm, or parliament, on Oct. 13.
   Rakowski told parliament he would need two weeks to enlist
ministers with ``reformatory attitudes'' and expressed the hope his
would be a ``coalition government with a broader representation
than has been the case.''
   Rakowski succeeded Zbigniew Messner, who resigned Sept. 19 with
his entire Cabinet after the government came under heavy attack for
its handling of the economy.
   Bronislaw Geremek, a senior adviser to Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa, said he heard of several attempts to enlist independent
figures for high posts in the Rakowski government, but knew of no
one who accepted.
   Geremek called the recruitment a ``strange attempt ... certain
to fail'' to circumvent planned round-table talks this month
between authorities and the opposition.
   Paszynski has been a leading advocate for the right to form
private associations. The official publication Lad quotes him in
its current issue as urging that Solidarity be made legal again and
that other groups, including his own Economic Society, be legalized.
   Solidarity, outlawed in 1982, reported that opposition activist
Jozef Pinior and three associates received suspended sentences by a
Wroclaw court on Monday for an alleged assault on a factory guard
there during a wave in strikes in May.
   Czeslaw Borowczyk was sentenced to 1{ years in prison, Pinior
and Aleksandra Sarata to one year each and Yolanta Skiba to eight
months, but all sentences were suspended for a three-year
probationary period, Pinior reported.
   They were found guilty in connection with an incident during a
May 5 factory rally at the Dolmel electric machinery plant in which
the guard was said to have suffered a broken arm.
   Pinior, a Solidarity leader in Wroclaw and a founder of the
illegal Polish Socialist Party, or PPS, denied assaulting the
guard, as did the other defendants.
   ``We treat it as pure harassment for our PPS activities,''
Pinior said of the verdict. He said the four planned to appeal.
</TEXT>
