<HEAD>Man Accused of Trying To Bomb Wife In Scotland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man in the midst of a divorce has been
charged with trying to hire someone to take a bomb concealed in a
tape recorder to his wife in Scotland, police said Monday.
   The bomb was set to explode when the play button was pressed.
   Charles Hili, 54, a former U.S. Marine munitions expert from
Long Island, was arrested after a man answered an advertisement
Hili placed in the Irish Voice newspaper Oct. 1, seeking a ``tough
Irishman ... to handle a confidential assignment,'' police said.
   The respondent then called police, said Detective Sgt. Daniel
Severin.
   The man who answered the advertisement met with Hili under
police surveillance on Sunday.
   Hili allegedly spelled out his instructions and handed the man a
tape recorder with a bomb inside, police said.
   Hili, a self-employed lumber buyer, also made arrangements to
pay the man $2,000, he said.
   Hili is charged of criminal solicitation, criminal possession of
a weapon and conspiracy.
   The man who answered the ad was an out-of-work Irish-American
who needed money, police said.
