<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congressman-Indictment     10-03 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congressman-Indictment,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia Congressman Demands Own Indictment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Georgia congressman, dogged by news accounts
of a grand jury investigation into drug money laundering, demanded
Monday on the House floor that he be indicted immediately ``on all
charges that may be under consideration.''
   Rep. Pat Swindall, R-Ga., who is locked in a tight re-election
battle, said he told Attorney General Dick Thornburgh in a letter
Monday that he is ``ready, able and willing to go to trial on the
day following the indictment which I now request.''
   ``Simple justice and fairness demand that I be allowed to prove
my innocence in a court of law rather than in the media,'' Swindall
said. ``Simple justice and fairness also demand that I be allowed
to prove my innocence before rather than after the Nov. 8
elections.''
   Justice Department spokesman John Russell said Thornburgh would
have no response to Swindall's request.
   On Friday, Swindall criticized the grand jury investigation and
suggested it might be politically motivated. U.S. Attorney Robert
Barr in Atlanta responded that the decision by his office and grand
juries in his district ``have never been, are not, and will never
be influenced or made on the basis of statements by or pressures
from third parties, including persons who may be subjects of
investigations.''
   Earlier this year, it was disclosed that a videotape had been
made of an Aug. 28, 1987, meeting Swindall had with an undercover
federal agent posing as a money launderer for underworld figures.
   Swindall was subpoenaed and testified before the grand jury in
February, but has never been charged with any crime.
   In June, Atlanta newspapers obtained tape recordings from the
investigation and published excerpts that showed Swindall continued
to pursue negotiations for a $850,000 home construction loan long
after being told it might be financed with drug money he would be
helping to launder.
   Swindall apologized for his role in the negotiations, saying he
was wrong and ashamed but would continue to seek re-election. He
also asked the House ethics committee to determine if he had
violated any law or House rule. The panel agreed to investigate,
but has not issued a ruling.
   Swindall said Monday that news that the grand jury had been
reconvened just 36 days prior to the election made him take the
``unprecedented'' request for his indictment. He is opposed by
Democrat Ben Jones.
   Swindall said newspaper stories about the investigation based on
unnamed federal sources have made it impossible for him to defend
himself.
   ``The only way I know to stop it is to throw myself at the mercy
at the court and say I waive my rights, I want an immediate
trial,'' he said. ``I will try the case myself. I will walk into
the courtroom with a simple yellow pad and I will prove my
innocence in a forum where I can prove it.''
</TEXT>
