<TEXT>
   Moscow went to Washington, D.C., Monday, apparently intending to
return to the Soviet Union.
   Theodore and Cheryle Branch of Erie moved to the Soviet Union in
October after suffering financial setbacks. They were granted
political asylum in January, and said the Soviets gave them a
furnished apartment in Moscow, medical benefits and jobs with Radio
Moscow.
   Branch has said they did not plan to return to the United States
until a U.S. embassy official in Moscow offered to match the
Soviets' benefits plus reimburse their travel expenses if the
couple came home.
   The State Department denied Branch's claims, and Soviet embassy
spokesman Boris Malakhov declined comment.
   The Branches were accompanied Monday by a crew from KDKA-TV of
Pittsburgh, whose Evening Magazine paid for their trip, said
Carolyn McClair, spokeswoman for the feature news program.
   The Branches said last week they would be broke by Monday.
   Meanwhile, Erie businessman David Olsen, upset the Branches
would forsake their country for the Soviet Union, said Branch
bruskly rejected an offer from him and New Jersey businessman Tom
Hogan for assistance returning to Moscow.
   ``Mr. Hogan is fully prepared to pay for the flight to the USSR.
I'm fully prepared to pay any expenses to any international airport
... and whatever's necessary,'' Olsen said. ``I said I'll literally
help them pack their bags. If it was necessary, I'll physically
carry them up the ramp and put them in a seat as long as it's an
international flight.''
