<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Kids     10-03 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Kids,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ad-Libs, Advice and Giggles Mark Dukakis Talk with Elementary
Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis had a ready comeback
Monday when an elementary school student called out the name
``Bush'' to the Democratic presidential candidate's query to the
class to name some drugs.
   ``Puts you to sleep, right?'' Dukakis ad-libbed as he bantered
with fourth and sixth graders at the Allen E. Barr school.
   Aides said they were pleased with Dukakis' freewheeling
discussion with the students, and hoped to schedule similar
appearances in the future.
   Dukakis asked the combined fourth- and sixth-grade classes if
they had learned about the dangers of drugs, and then asked them to
list a few ``bad drugs.''
   The answers: Cocaine, marijuana, ``Angel Dust,'' heroin, crack,
cigarettes, and then, yes, ``Bush.''
   After giggles had subsided, Dukakis said: ``Bush is a drug, eh?
Interesting. I hadn't thought of that. Puts you to sleep, right?.''
   When it came to listing ``good drugs,'' Dukakis took exception
to one student's mention of ``aspirin.''
   The son of physician told the youths: ``It'll put a hole in your
stomach, I think, if you take too much of it. You've got to watch
it.''
   Dukakis told the youngsters he was glad they were receiving drug
education because, ``If you're going to make a contribution to the
kind of country we want to build together, it's very, very
important. I think the earlier you can begin to discuss those kinds
of things, the better.''
   He threw the floor open to questions, saying, ``I mean, here I
am, I might be the next president of the United States, right?''
   Dukakis was asked what the best and worst parts of running for
president were.
   ``You have an opportunity to meet wonderful people all across
this country ... And if you win, it gives you a chance to make a
real difference in the lives of people,'' he said.
   ``The toughest part is it's long, it takes a lot of work, a lot
of effort. But, you know, whatever you do in this life, if you want
to do it well, you have to work at. Got to get that homework done
and pay attention ...''
   He told the class: ``I want every single one of you to have a
chance to go on to college, and to do the best that you can do. I
want you to grow up, and marry and have children and buy a little
house.''
   ``I like this class,'' Dukakis said. ``I'm going to take you
wherever I go.''
   He promised to invite them to the White House if elected.
</TEXT>
