<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NavajoSlayings     10-03 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navajo Slayings,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Navajos Sentenced To Life For Slayings Of Tribal Officers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Navajo tribal members to life in
prison Monday for the shooting and burning deaths of two tribal
police officers who had tried to break up a party.
   Thomas Cly, 22, and Vinton Bedoni, 31, were found guilty Aug. 2
of two counts of first-degree murder, aiding and abetting and use
of a firearm in a crime.
   ``There's no question this is a crime of first-degree murder in
its most brutal form,'' U.S. District Judge J. Thomas Greene said
in sentencing Cly.
   Greene also sentenced both men to a pair of five-year terms for
aiding and abetting and use of a firearm. Those terms are to be
served consecutively after the concurrent life terms, Greene said.
   A third defendant, Ben Atene Jr., 24, is scheduled for a new
trial Oct. 11. The same jury that convicted Cly and Bedoni
deadlocked on Atene, and U.S. District Judge J. Thomas Greene
declared a mistrial.
   Charges against a fourth defendant, Marques Atene, 22, were
dismissed when prosecutors acknowledged they lacked enough evidence
to convict him.
   The four were charged in the slayings of tribal policemen Roy
Lee Stanley and Andy Begay, whose bodies were found Dec. 5, 1987,
in a burned-out police truck in a remote southern Utah canyon.
   Prosecutors said the officers were killed at the site of a
bonfire drinking party near Gouldings the night of Dec. 4. Alcohol
is prohibited on the Navajo Indian Reservation.
   The officers were trying to break up the party and became
involved in altercations with the defendants.
   In the August trial, prosecution witnesses repeatedly changed
their accounts of the crimes, and defense witnesses who placed the
accused at other locations at the time of the slayings.
</TEXT>
