<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-03 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Air Across Northern Plains Put Chill on Growing Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The coldest air so far this fall spread across the north-central
states Monday, bringing an end to the growing season across much of
Minnesota and the Dakotas.
   Gusty northerly winds Monday afternoon accompanied temperatures
in the 40s and low 50s north of a Plains cold front.
   A hard freeze was forecast overnight for all of North Dakota,
with temperatures expected to drop into the low 20s. Freeze
advisories were posted for the Dakotas, western Minnesota and much
of northern Nebraska, and a frost advisory was in effect for much
of southern Nebraska.
   By early Wednesday, the cold air will slide into the South, with
readings of about 40 degrees expected around Memphis, Tenn.
   While most of the nation was dry Monday, showers and
thunderstorms _ some severe _ wet southern Georgia and much of
Florida. Lighter rain fell from South Carolina to the mid-Atlantic
states, including showers in western New York.
   A tornado touched down near Cross City, Fla., damaging trees and
downing power lines.
   Rainfall for the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included almost
2 inches at Tallahassee, Fla., and more than 1{ inches at Brunswick
and Macon, Ga., and Apalachicola, Fla.
   At Jacksonville, Fla., nearly 2 inches of rain fell in two hours
ending at 3 p.m, with almost three-quarters of an inch in 20
minutes.
   Warm and dry conditions prevailed across the nation west of the
Rockies, with afternoon temperatures mostly in the 60s and 70s but
in the 90s to about 105 degrees in the desert Southwest. From the
northern Rockies to the Great Lakes, the mercury dropped into the
40s and 50s. Readings in the 60s and 70s reached from the East
Coast across the middle and lower Mississippi Valley to the central
and southern parts of the Plains and Rockies.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 40
degrees at Ely and Duluth, Minn., to 106 degrees at Palm Springs,
Calif.
   The low in the nation early Monday was 18 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo.
   For Tuesday, rainshowers were forecast from the Great Lakes
across New York to New England, with snowshowers over upper
Michigan and northern Wisconsin. Scattered showers also were
expected along the Atlantic coast, with thunderstorms over Florida.
   Tuesday's highs were forecast in the 40s and 50s from New
England across the Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes region and the
upper half of the Mississippi Valley to the northern and central
Plains. Readings in the 80s were predicted for Florida and from the
southern half of Texas across the Southwest, but in the 90s or low
100s in the desert.
</TEXT>
