<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BodyParts     10-03 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Body Parts,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Parts Removed From Home In Boxes, Bags And Buckets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The previous owners of the McClures'
new house used to take their work home with them. Unfortunately,
they were coroners.
   When the McClures' cat, Puffy, started growling in the backyard
Sunday night _ their first night in the new home _ the couple went
to investigate and found 25 boxes, bags and buckets full of human
body parts.
   The labeled body parts were left behind by the former
homeowners, a pair of Riverside deputy coroners, who apparently
were doing some work for an independent laboratory, authorities
said.
   The bags and boxes were labeled with people's names, a series of
numbers and dates, and a description, such as ``stomach and
contents.''
   McClure said he picked up a plastic bag, noted the squishy feel
and carried it into the light for a better look. The label on the
bag said: ``Heart.''
   ``It was all purple. When I found out it was a heart I dropped
it,'' said McClure, a 24-year-old auto technician.
   More parcels were discovered in the garage and the back yard was
dotted with clumps of hair.
   The Coroner's Office said the previous owners, Brad and Alendra
Birdsall, were cutting up human remains for an independent
laboratory where they both work part-time.
   Brad Birdsall, who visited the McClure home Sunday afternoon to
remove some items, said he had been instructed by his supervisors
not to discuss what the tissue samples were doing at the house.
   ``Suffice it to say it's for legitimate reasons,'' he said.
   The Birdsalls had left the McClures a note, written on a paper
towel and dated Oct. 1, that advised the new homeowners that some
property belonging to the Birdsalls remained at the home.
   ``We still occupy half the garage, the covered patio, part of
the brick patio (under the olive tree) and still have our tools in
the shed,'' the note stated. ``Call us if there are any problems.''
   Supervising Deputy Coroner Dan Cupido said his office had no
policy forbidding employees from working on human remains at their
homes, but an investigation could lead to a change in policy.
   The discoveries don't place any previous autopsies in doubt,
Cupido said.
   The McClures paid $85,000 for the house.
   ``The wife, she's so upset she's saying she wishes we hadn't
bought the house,'' McClure said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
