<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Hostages-Steen     10-03 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages-Steen,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage's Wife Still Awaiting Word on Husband's Fate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of U.S. hostage Alann Steen said
she was still awaiting word on the fate of her husband, who was
rumored to be released Monday by Moslem captors who released
another man instead.
   ``We have not received confirmation of anything yet,'' Virginia
Steen said from her parents' home in Clark Lake in Jackson Couny.
The U.S. State Department is ``waiting like we are for any
confirmation coming out of Beirut or Damascus.''
   The release of Mithileshwar Singh, 60, a visiting finance
professor, followed press reports that Steen, 49, a journalism
professor, was about to be released.
   Steen, Singh and two other American teachers were kidnapped Jan.
24, 1987, by gunmen posing as riot police at the campus of Beirut
University College, where they taught.
   Mrs. Steen said she talked to State Department representatives,
but she did not say what was discussed.
   Nine Americans are missing in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
