<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     10-03 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel's Surrogate Militia Supports Christian Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former Lebanese general who runs
Israel's ``security zone'' in south Lebanon declared support Monday
of the Christian slate in Lebanon's paralyzed, two-Cabinet
government.
   ``The Cabinet formed by President (Amin) Gemayel under army
commander Gen. Michel Aoun is the legitimate government,'' former
Maj. Gen. Antoine Lahd said in his first public comment on the
situation.
   Lahd spoke at a news conference broadcast by the Voice of Hope,
the radio station of his South Lebanon Army militia.
   When Gemayal's term ended Sept. 23 without a successor having
been chosen by Parliament, Gemayel appointed Aoun, a fellow
Maronite Christian, prime minister of a six-man military government.
   Three Moslem officers named to the Aoun Cabinet refused.
Lebanon's Moslem majority rejected the Christian Cabinet and
declared the incumbent government of acting Prime Minister Salim
Hoss, a Syrian-backed Sunni Moslem, the legitimate authority.
   That caused one of Lebanon's biggest political crises since
independence from France in 1943. By unwritten agreement, Lebanon's
president always has been a Christian, the prime minister a Sunni
Moslem and the speaker of Parliament a Shiite Moslem.
   Lahd held his news conference at Jizzine, the largest Christian
town in south Lebanon, which has a population of 30,000. It is 25
miles south of Beirut in the northern tip of Israel's
self-proclaimed security zone, which the South Lebanon Army patrols
with the aid of Israeli soldiers.
   ``We shall not be handcuffed in dealing with any danger that
threatens Lebanon's existence and unity. We shall take active
measures to restore unity and legitimacy to the nation,'' Lahd
said, without elaborating.
   Nabih Berri, leader of the Shiite Moslem militia Amal and
Justice minister in the Hoss government, was quoted as saying
afterward: ``If some in the security zone began threatening
military measures, we affirm that we were and still are against any
military actions.''
   Asked whether Parliament will convene to elect a new president
soon, Berri was quoted by Voice of Lebanon radio as saying: ``There
will be no elections. We do not need them (the Christians).
   ``We need one government, at least in the current stage, that
will unite the country and form a new (political) system. It is not
required to have a president who will rule without
responsibilities.''
   Israel controls a six- to 10-mile-deep strip of land in south
Lebanon as a buffer zone against guerrillas trying to infiltrate
Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
