<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO-Soviet     10-03 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Soviet,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Official Says Soviet Changes Offer `Mixed' Picture</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Shake-Up, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of NATO said Monday that the
leadership upheaval and other sweeping changes under way in the
Soviet Union offer the West a mixed picture, but ``there is still
more continuity than change.''
   ``The aim of Soviet reform efforts is, of course, not to please
the West. Nor do the Soviets intend to abandon their own system,''
Secretary-General Manfred Woerner told the Royal Institute of
International Relations in Brussels.
   ``On the contrary, the basic objective is to make the present
system work more efficiently and thus to enhance the credibility
and authority of the Communist Party.''
   Woerner, former West German defense minister, said the West
should welcome Soviet reform programs that promise greater freedom
for citizens.
   ``It is not in our interest to see the present reform programs
fail ...,'' he said. ``Stable and improved relations will require
predictability in the behavior of all countries involved.''
   Woerner said in prepared remarks that Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev ``faces considerable problems in his efforts to modernize
the Soviet society. But he pursues his objective with energy and
determination, as last week's events in Moscow demonstrate.''
   Gorbachev late last week led the most dramatic political changes
in Soviet leadership of his 3{ years in power, including his
election as the country's president to replace Andrei Gromyko.
   In addition, Gorbachev has pushed policies of glasnost, or
openness, and perestroika, or reform. He also has pressed for
improved relations with the United States and other members of the
16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization defense alliance.
   President Reagan and Gorbachev last December signed the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty that provides for
elimination over three years of medium-range nuclear weapons.
   East and West negotiators also are pursuing discussions on
reducing conventional arms in Europe.
   ``There can be no doubt that there has been a shift in Soviet
attitudes and positions,'' Woerner said. ``Nevertheless, the
present picture is a mixed one.''
   ``There is still more continuity than change. The Soviets are
more actively pursuing arms control. But at the same time the
modernization of nuclear as well as conventional forces facing
Europe continues unabated.''
   ``There is a strong push for economic reform,'' he said. ``But
military expenditures remain at a level far beyond defensive
requirements.''
   He defended NATO against criticism it has been slow to respond
to Gorbachev's push and lacks a comprehensive strategy for pursuing
East-West relations.
   ``I strongly disagree with this perception. The achievements of
the last few years have come in response to our proposals and
determination,'' he said.
   Woerner said the West should encourage East bloc leaders in
their policy changes and be ready for greater cooperation.
   ``But in the end,'' he said, ``future developments will depend
on these leaders themselves, and in particular on the Soviets.''
   ``They must demonstrate,'' he said, ``that they are not merely
seeking a breathing space, but a permanently improved relationship
between East and West at a lower and more balanced level of
forces.''
   He cautioned that despite reform programs, ``Soviet military
capabilities and posture remain the same. We cannot base our
security on declared intentions which may rapidly change.
   ``A prudent insurance policy requires a defense based on a sober
evaluation of Warsaw Pact capabilities. And if we are to further
reduce the level of arms on both sides, we must have the political
determination required to keep the remaining forces _ nuclear as
well as conventional _ strong and up-to-date.''
</TEXT>
