<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AbortionWars     10-03 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Wars,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice, Anti-Abortion Groups Rally in Advance Of
Demonstrations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped following evening rallies</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Monday arrested the leader of the
militant anti-abortion group Operation Rescue on the eve of the
organization's ``siege of Atlanta'' _ intensive picketing to
blockade the city's abortion clinics.
   As those seeking to outlaw abortion prepared to renew
demonstrations that began during the Democratic National
Convention, activists who say the decision to end a pregnancy
should be a woman's, not the state's, readied their own
countermeasures.
   Like armies girding for battle, both sides planned rallies
Monday evening to arouse supporters.
   Randall Terry of Operation Rescue was arrested shortly after he
addressed a group of his supporters, who plan to block entrances to
clinics for four days beginning Tuesday morning.
   He was charged with conspiracy to commit a crime and jailed
under a $75,000 bond pending a hearing Tuesday afternoon, said
police Sgt. Dorothy Smith.
   Atlanta officials have vowed tough law enforcement to keep
demonstrations or any confrontations between the two sides from
getting out of hand.
   Abortion foes scheduled its rally at St. Jude's Catholic Church
in suburban Sandy Springs. Its goal, said spokeswoman Judi Loesch,
was to ``rev people up (and) give people the information they
need'' for the demonstrations.
   Pro-choice forces, meanwhile, planned a service at Central
Presbyterian Church across from the state Capitol in memory of a
woman who died from a back-street abortion.
   The program was to include speeches by Bill Baird, a longtime
advocate of a woman's right to choose and the owner of clinics in
New York; National Organization of Women President Molly Yard, and
Kate Michelman, executive director of the National Abortion Rights
Action League.
   Organizers of Operation Rescue's so-called ``siege of Atlanta''
predict hundreds of their supporters will take part in blockading
the seven clinics in Atlanta where abortions are performed.
   Abortion rights groups, led by the Georgia Abortion Rights
League, have trained about 300 people to help escort women through
picket lines outside the clinics, said executive director Sally
Tyler.
   Also, a hearing is set Tuesday on the city's request for a court
injunction declaring anti-abortion pickets ``public nuisances'' and
forbidding them from blocking clinics or coming within 15 feet of
anyone seeking to enter a clinic.
   Ms. Tyler said pro-choice groups will not stage any
counterdemonstration outside the clinics because it ``makes it
harder on the individual woman; it becomes more confusion. ... it's
just more of a mob scene.''
   Operation Rescue, a New York-based organization, led 17
demonstrations in Atlanta beginning during the Democratic National
Convention in July. More than 700 people were arrested during those
demonstrations, many of them remaining in jail for up to 70 days
because they refused to give their names and identified themselves
instead as Baby John Doe or Baby Jane Doe. Three remain in jailed.
   Pro-choice groups scheduled Monday's rally ``because it is on
the eve of the return of Operation Rescue to Atlanta,'' Ms. Tyler
said.
   In addition, Monday was the 11th anniversary of the death of
Rosie Jimenez, who Ms. Tyler said was the first woman to die from a
cut-rate abortion after Congress cut off Medicaid funds for
abortions in 1977.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
