<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Botha     10-03 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Botha,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Will Not Attend Meeting with Other African Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha will not
go to Zambia this week to confer with leaders of other African
nations, Foreign Ministry spokesman Roland Darroll said Monday.
   His statement came in response to reports that Botha planned to
go to Lusaka, Zambia, to meet with President Kenneth Kaunda and
several other black African leaders.
   Botha has visited Mozambique, Malawi and Zaire over the past
three weeks for meetings that were seen as a breakthrough for
white-dominated South Africa.
   Botha told a public meeting Monday night in the town of George
in Cape province signs emerged of ``greater understanding and
cooperation but leaders of southern Africa still have to take the
great step in getting together.''
   ``Over many years the perception has developed that South Africa
is a belligerent country in an antagonist region,'' he said.
``Events in recent months have questioned the validity of this
perception.''
   Botha noted labor-market, scientific and technological links
between his country and its neighbors and said, ``A strong basis
for cooperation already exists between South Africa and the other
states in the region.''
   Malawi is the only African country that has formal diplomatic
ties with South Africa but some other countries have trade missions.
   South Africa has been politically isolated because of its policy
of apartheid.
   By South African laws and customs, apartheid establishes a
racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
