<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     10-03 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Fell in September Fighting in El Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Combat between government
forces and leftist guerrillas resulted in hundreds of casualties
last month, according to military and rebel reports issued Monday.
   The armed forces press office listed 88 rebels killed and 117
wounded in September and said 65 soldiers died and 141 were wounded.
   Guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front
claimed to have inflicted 1,062 casualties on forces of the
U.S.-backed government last month, which saw the beginning of a
rebel drive called ``Death to Reagan's (Salvador) Policy, Yankee
out of El Salvador.''
   Radio Venceremos, the rebels' clandestine radio, said the deaths
of 78 troops was confirmed.
   The rebels do not usually provide figures on their own
casualties.
   Guerrillas early Monday attacked a branch of the state-run Banco
Capitalizador in Atiquizaya, 42 miles west of San Salvador, the
armed forces said.
   A communique said the branch was sacked and burned in the
pre-dawn raid, and that two national policemen were wounded
fighting the rebels.
   Bank manager Francisco Rodriguez told journalists the guerrillas
took about $48,000.
   The communique also reported that government forces kIlled five
rebels and wounded two in fighting Sunday in northeastern Morazan
province.
   No way exists to independently verify casualty figures reported
by either side in the 9-year-old war. Evidence indicates both sides
inflate the number of casualties inflicted on the enemy, while
underreporting their own casualties. Radio Venceremos said 450
soldiers were killed or wounded in what it described as the
``annihilation'' of the 4th Army Brigade headquarters in
Chalatenango province on Sept. 13.
   Reporters who visited the brigade that day saw damage from rebel
mortar fire but no evidence the base had been overrun. The
government said 15 soldiers and six guerrillas were killed in that
attack.
   The guerrilla claim for September was nearly double that of
August, when the rebels said they caused 544 government casualties.
   Rebel reports do not separate dead and wounded.
   About 65,000 people have died in the war, most of them civilians.
</TEXT>
