<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Issigonis     10-03 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Issigonis,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Designer of Mini Car Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUDREY WOODS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Alec Issigonis, designer of the box-like Mini
car that brought economical motoring to millions of Britons, has
died at age 81, the London Times reported.
   Issigonis, who also designed the immensely popular and
long-lived Morris Minor, died at his home in Edgbaston, Birmingham,
on Sunday, a death notice in Tuesday's editions of the Times said.
   No cause of death was announced but for years Issingonis
suffered from Parkinson's disease. He retired in 1971 but continued
working as a consultant to the Rover Group until a year ago.
   More than 5 million Minis, planned as ``a box on wheels,'' have
been built since they were introduced in 1959, setting a new
standard for small-car design.
   A 10-foot-long box, it weighed about 1,300 pounds and sold for
less than $1,500.
   It was just the car for the swinging sixties, a favorite with
aristocrats, film stars and the bell-bottomed and mini-skirted
young people who could, at last, afford a car.
   Despite embellishments and refinements, its outward appearance
has never greatly changed. The price has multiplied almost tenfold,
but sales are still buoyant.
   Said Issingonis in 1986: ``Oddly enough, I don't think I'm
proudest of the Mini. I think it was the Morris Minor, the first
all-British car to pass the 1 million mark.''
   That doughty little car, produced between 1948 and 1971, still
bowls along highways all over Britain, cherished and coddled by
owners who shun any thought of driving anything else.
   Its snub-nosed plainness, little changed throughout its
production years, retains an aura of tradition and sober
reliability. The wood-paneled station wagons and sprightly
convertibles are much sought after in the 1980s.
   About 100,000 are still on British roads. Thousands survive in
India and Pakistan, and Sri Lankans drive an estimated 45,000 of
them in various stages of decay.
   Issigonis was born on Nov. 18, 1906, in Smyrna, then part of
Turkey, and came to Britain with his widowed mother following the
1922 war between Turkey and Greece.
   After studying engineering in London, he joined Morris Motors in
1936 and built a lightweight hill-climb car to demonstrate the
potential of all-independent suspension.
   His first complete production car was the Morris Minor.
   After working at Alvis in the early 1950s, Issigonis returned to
what had become BMC to design and produce a small, economical car _
the Mini.
   The result was radical for the time _ a transverse engine
powering the front wheels.
   In 1967, Issigonis was named a fellow of the Royal Society,
Britain's most prestigious scientific establishment. He was
knighted in 1969.
   Issigonis was not married
</TEXT>
</DOC>
