<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hostages 3dLd-Writethru a0837 10-03 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages, 3d Ld-Writethru, a0837,0849</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE BEIRUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Moslem Kidnappers Free Indian Hostage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 UPDATE with Singh in Damascus given medical
exam. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, In Beirut ... with minor editing</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem kidnappers in Lebanon freed Indian
educator Mithileshwar Singh, a resident alien of the United States,
after holding him hostage for more than 20 months and Singh was
taken to Syria early Tuesday.
   The kidnappers, who still hold three American colleagues of
Singh, released the Indian professor in southern Beirut on Monday
night and Syrian intelligence officers drove him to Damascus.
   He was taken to a government guest house where two doctors
examined him, according to a government official who spoke on
condition he not be identified. The official said the examination
was ``a normal routine'' and gave no details.
   He said Singh talked by telephone with the U.S. ambassador in
Damascus, Edward Djerjian, and would be turned over to the
ambassador later Tuesday at the Foreign Ministry.
   In Beirut, Singh's wife choked back tears as she told reporters:
``This is a happy day for me, but I still did not see him. I want
to see him.''
   Singh, 60, was released at 10:05 p.m. across the street from the
Beirut headquarters of the U.N. Relief and Works Agency that aids
Palestinian refugees, a Lebanese police spokesman said.
   He was freed five minutes after a deadline set by Islamic Jihad
for the Liberation of Palestine, which still holds three American
college teachers kidnapped with Singh at Beirut University College
in Moslem west Beirut on Jan. 24, 1987. The kidnappers posed as
police officers.
   Nine Americans are among the 17 foreigners missing in Lebanon.
Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent
of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   In Washington, the State Department said ``we are anxious to
talk to him (Singh) and learn if he has any information to share
with us'' about the other captives.
   Spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said: ``We join with Mr. Singh's
relatives in rejoicing in his release and call for the urgent,
unconditional release of all hostages in Lebanon.''
   Syrian intelligence officers and plainclothes secret service
agents took Singh into their custody in front of the former Kuwaiti
Embassy building facing the UNRWA headquarters in Bir Hassan on
Beirut's southern outskirts, police reported. About 7,500 Syrian
soldiers are stationed in west Beirut.
   Nasser Qaddor, Syrian minister of state for foreign affairs, had
said in Damascus Monday night that an American hostage was freed
and in Syrian hands.
   Singh holds an Indian passport and an American green card that
makes him a legal resident alien of the United States.
   Earlier reports by the CBS and NBC television networks and a
Christian radio station in Beirut said American teacher Alann
Steen, 49, a native of Boston and one of those kidnapped with
Singh, was the man to be released.
   A 36-word handwritten statement in Arabic delivered to a Western
news agency Monday said the hostage would be freed by 10 p.m.
   Accompanying the statement was a photograph showing U.S. hostage
Jesse Turner, 41, a native of Boise, Idaho, shaking hands with
Singh while Steen and Robert Polhill, 54, of New York City, the
fourth captive, smiled as if bidding the Indian farewell.
   Their wives waited for news at Mrs. Turner's apartment on the
Beirut University College campus.
   ``We are listening to the radios. Insha'allah, insha'allah (God
willing) these rumors come true. It's a good sign whoever is
released,'' Badr Turner, a Lebanese, said in a telephone interview.
   The kidnappers said in a statement released Saturday they would
free one hostage as a goodwill gesture and to stimulate U.S.
support for the 10-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   They urged the families of the hostages to be in Beirut for the
release. The comment apparently was directed at Steen's wife,
Virginia-Rose, who is vacationing with her parents in the United
States. She is expected back in Beirut on Wednesday.
   Gunmen kidnapped the educators from Beirut University College
campus, where Singh taught finance.
   Steen taught journalism at the school and his wife, 31, of
Jackson, Mich., is a fine arts instructor there.
   Turner taught mathematics and computer science and Polhill was a
business teacher and lecturer in accounting.
   Singh was born in Varanasi, India, Dec. 13, 1927. He taught
eight years at the University of Agra and eight years at the
University of Gorakhpur before moving to the United States in 1965
for graduate work at the University of Oregon in Eugene.
   He obtained a master's degree in business adminstration from the
University in Oregon in 1968 and a doctorate from Western Colorado,
an independent-study institution that operated from 1970 to 1983 in
Grand Junction, Colo., according to Beirut University College.
   After teaching at the University of Wisconsin-Platteville;
Milton College, Wis., and Western Colorado, he joined the Beirut
University College faculty in 1983.
</TEXT>
