<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadetsStricken     10-03 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Troopers Leave Academy Where 16 Cadets Were Sickened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AGAWAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two state troopers in charge of a police
academy training program that put 16 cadets in the hospital said
their farewells Monday as they prepared to turn their jobs over to
new instructors.
   Also Monday, the state Department of Public Safety ordered its
police academies to stop using pushups and other exercise as
punishment in training cadets. The Agawam police academy was closed
Sept. 21 for an investigation.
   One cadet remained in a coma after collapsing on his first day
at the Agawam academy, which trains police for cities in western
Massachusetts. Others suffered dehydration and kidney failure,
doctors said.
   Troopers Charles Blake Gilmore and John M. Richardson ended
official duties at the academy Monday. On Tuesday, they will
transfer the academy's physical training program to state police
Lt. William J. Shea and Trooper James Ryan.
   The two men asked to be reassigned Friday because of the
attention the academy has received since members of their class
began collapsing two weeks ago.
   ``They will not have further contact with the class,'' said Jeff
Grossman of the Department of Public Safety.
   One cadet, Timothy Shepard, 25, remained in a coma Monday at a
Pittsburgh hospital where he underwent a liver transplant. Fifteen
other cadets were hospitalized when they reported to doctors on
their own or on the orders of the troopers.
   Several trainees showed signs of dehydration, exhaustion and
kidney failure, doctors said.
   A team of 15 doctors, professors and police chiefs was preparing
for an examination of the training practices that may have caused
the ailments.
   One member of the team named by the Massachusetts Criminal
Justice Training Council, the group of 22 law enforcement officials
that runs the Agawam academy, said Monday she doubted that anything
but overexercise could have caused the illnesses.
   ``There are data on military recruits who suffered acute renal
failure from overexertion,'' said Priscilla Clarkson, a University
of Massachusetts researcher on muscle damage.
   ``In fairness to the instructors,'' Ms. Clarkson said, ``they
may not have known how strenuous the exercise was. It's a matter of
knowing what kind of damage the type of exercise you're doing can
cause. Some are particularly effective at inducing muscle damage
without giving an immediate sign.''
   Some cadets reported undergoing 10{ hours of exercise the first
day of class with relatively little water. Police chiefs who sent
trainees to the academy have said water was available, but the
cadets may have hesitated to break ranks to ask for it.
   Another investigation, by the state attorney general's office,
entered its second week Monday. Spokeswoman Mary Breslauer said
nine investigators were still talking to witnesses.
</TEXT>
