<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Philippines     10-03 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Philippines,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippines Foreign Minister Calls For Debt Rescheduling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign minister of the Philippines
called Monday for creditor nations to reschedule or even forgive
the debts owed by Third World countries.
   Raul S. Manglapus also called the United States a ``hegemonic
power'' that he said could ease the debt crisis but had not done so.
   Manglapus devoted his entire speech to the General Assembly to
the economic policies of the industrialized countries and accused
them of perpetuating and increasing the debt of Third World nations.
   ``It is valuable to reschedule debt, but it is even more
precious and human to forgive debt,'' he said.
   Manglapus proposed the creation of an International Debt and
Development Commission to evaluate alternative plans for global
debt management and said the commission staff could be drawn from
other international financial agencies.
   He said the commission should develop standards for debt relief
or debt forgiveness and propose them to the United nations for
``approval, proclamation and execution.''
   ``There is one hegemonic power today that could crack the whip,
the United States of America,'' he said. ``But the crisis is
enormous and there are rising economic powers with which the
enforcer must coordinate if order and resolution are to be reached.
This is not happening.''
   Referring to the industrialized North and developing South,
Manglapus said the North should not blame imports from the South
for unemployment and other economic problems and should instead
stop competing with the South.
   He said the North should get out of manufacturing and exporting
textiles, garments and shoes because they are ``economic activities
in which the North has no economic advantage.''
   The debt crisis is not only a problem for the debtor but also
for ``the creditor, a problem for the world,'' he said.
``Therefore, the solution cannot be sectoral. It must be total. It
cannot be regional, it must be global.''
   Manglapus praised U.N. achievements in peacekeeping and called
on the world body to play a larger role in resolving Third World
debt.
   ``What is this debt crisis but a monstrous threat to peace?'' he
said. ``Today the debt of nation to nation is not developing man.
It is killing man.''
</TEXT>
