<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FrancisExecution     10-03 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Francis Execution,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Issues Stay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who opted for shooting a drug informant in
the head and heart instead of injecting him with drain cleaner won
a stay of execution Monday night, the second time since the killer
was sentenced to death in 1976.
   Bobby Marion Francis, 44, had been scheduled to die at 7 a.m.
Tuesday in the electric chair at Florida State Prison near Starke.
But U.S. District Judge Lenore Nesbitt granted a stay, ruling
inadequate time to consider the appeal.
   A Monroe County jury found Francis guilty of murder in the death
of Titus R. Walters. Walters was bound and gagged for nearly two
hours while Francis planned how to kill him, according to court
records. Francis apparently debated injecting Walters with the
household caustic used to clear clogged pipes.
   Nesbitt said the appeal was filed shortly after noon Monday,
fewer than 19 hours before Francis was set to die. She said there
was not enough time for her to study all the testimony in the
voluminous file.
   The stay remains in effect until further orders by the judge.
Francis' death warrant expires Oct. 10.
   Francis, who was sentenced to death in June 1976, survived his
first death warrant when the Florida Supreme Court granted him a
stay in November 1987.
   Nine death row inmates are now under active warrants. Gov. Bob
Martinez has signed 55 death warrants since taking office 21 months
ago. Since then, Willie Jasper Darden and Beauford White have been
electrocuted.
