<2ND_LINE>AM-Baldwin Baby,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Mother Gives Up Infant For Adoption, May Be Sterilized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who pleaded guilty to neglect
charges in the death of a 4-year-old son gave up her day-old baby
for adoption Monday and also would undergo sterilization under the
plea bargain, her attorney said.
   Melody S. Baldwin, 29, was close to agreeing to be sterilized
Tuesday morning, the latest she can undergo the procedure without
waiting another six weeks, attorney Michael J. Donahoe said.
   A judge has said the operation could reduce her sentence.
   ``We're going to get that ironed out tomorrow,'' Donahoe said
after the adoption papers were signed. ``I think everyone wants to
make sure they're doing the right thing and not leaving themselves
open to criticism.''
   For medical reasons, a woman can only be sterilized within 48
hours of giving birth before waiting six weeks for conditions to be
proper again, Donahoe said.
   Baldwin, who is awaiting sentencing for administering lethal
doses of mind-altering drugs to her son Joshua two years ago, gave
birth to an 8-pound, 5-ounce boy Sunday at Wishard Hospital, where
she is being detained.
   Both were reported in good condition Monday.
   Donahoe said rights to privacy prevented him from saying where
the child would go or who was present for the signing.
   Marion Superior Court Judge Roy F. Jones has offered to give Ms.
Baldwin a reduced sentence if she agrees to be sterilized.
   She could face up to 20 years imprisonment on the neglect
charge. The former waitress had been charged with murder for
administering lethal doses of a drug and interfering with the
child's medical treatments.
   Ms. Baldwin was placed under a court order when she attempted to
leave another Indianapolis hospital, where she was being treated
for possible self-induced weight loss while she was pregnant.
   Jones later approved an order transferring Ms. Baldwin to
Wishard from St. Francis Hospital, where the sterilization process
cannot be performed because of the hospital's affiliation with the
Catholic Church.
   Donahoe filed a motion Friday to release his client on bond,
pending sentencing. Jones was awaiting a psychiatric evaluation on
Ms. Baldwin before ruling on the motion.
</TEXT>
