<2ND_LINE>AM-Producer Murder, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0873,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges Filed In 5-Year-Old Murder Of New York Producer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0873 to restore 1st Ld-Writethru designator.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four people have been charged with murder in
the 5-year-old slaying of New York producer Roy Radin, who
authorities say was embroiled in a soured deal to finance the movie
``The Cotton Club.''
   Radin disappeared May 13, 1983, on his way to a meeting
concerning the film, and his body was found a month later with a
bullet wound in the head. His death, authorities said Monday, was a
contract killing.
   A key figure in negotiations over the film was Hollywood
producer Robert Evans, said Deputy District Attorney David Conn,
and ``I'm sure his testimony is going to become important at some
point.''
   ``We're not making any allegations against him at this time,''
Conn said. Asked if Evans, producer of such movies as ``Chinatown''
and ``Marathon Man,'' remains under investigation, Conn answered,
``Yes.''
   Charged with Radin's murder were Karen De Layne Greenberger,
formerly known as Elaine Jacobs; William Molony Mentzer; Alex
Lamota Marti; and Robert Ulmer Lowe. The complaint alleged that
they killed Radin ``for financial gain.''
   In addition, the complaint charged Mentzer, Lowe and a fifth
defendant, Robert Leroy Deremer with murdering June Mincher, a
prostitute. Conn said the two killings were unrelated except that
two of the defendants were involved.
   Conn said the Radin slaying resulted from a dispute between
Radin and Greenberger about a plan to raise $35 million from
investors in the Puerto Rican government for Evans' production of
``The Cotton Club.''
   The prosecutor said Radin was introduced to Evans by
Greenberger, and Radin became a middleman in the Puerto Rican
negotiations.
   But a dispute developed between Radin and Greenberger over a
finder's fee she was demanding, Conn said.
   ``We think the individuals felt the deal could go forward
without Radin being involved,'' Conn said, ``and it did go forward,
but without the Puerto Rican investors.''
   On May 13, 1983, he said Radin stepped into a limousine rented
by Greenberger ``with the intention of going to a restaurant and
discussing the business arrangement further.
   ``He never arrived at the restaurant and his body was found June
10, 1983, in the northwest corner of (Los Angeles) County in
Gorman,'' Conn said. ``He'd been shot in the back of the head.''
   Asked why it had taken so long to bring charges, Conn said: ``We
have new evidence that's been uncovered in the course of the
investigation by the sheriff's department.''
   Conn said the complaint was issued Sept. 22 but kept sealed
because of fear for the safety of an informant who has since been
relocated.
   Search warrants executed Sunday and turned up weapons and
explosives at the homes of Mentzer and Marti and at a storage
locker, he said..
   Conn said Mentzer was a private investigator involved in
security work with Marti, Deremer and Lowe.
   The complaint alleged special circumstances which could result
in the death penalty if the defendants are convicted.
   Greenberger was arrested in Florida, Conn said. Lowe was
arrested in Maryland, where Deremer was due to be arrested, he
said. Mentzer and Marti were arrested in Los Angeles.
   In 1980, actress-model Melonie Haller claimed Radin drugged and
raped her at gunpoint during one of the frequent parties at his
mansion on Long Island, east of Manhattan.
   The actress, who appeared in ``Welcome Back, Kotter,'' was found
dazed and bleeding on a Long Island Rail Road train. Radin who
pleaded innocent to the rape charges but guilty to possessing a
handgun, was fined $1,000 and placed on probation.
</TEXT>
