<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-CentralAmerica     10-03 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Central America,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Costa Rica Assails Nicaragua For `Repression' of Democratic Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Costa Rican foreign minister said
Monday that no Central American nation fulfilled its duties under a
regional peace plan, but singled out Nicaragua in particular for
stepping up ``its repression.''
   ``The progress in this peaceful effort has stopped,'' said
Foreign Minister Rodrigo Madrigal Nieto. President Oscar Arias
Sanchez of Costa Rica won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for drafting
the plan.
   The minister, speaking in Spanish, told the 43rd General
Assembly that ``to a greater or lesser degree, none of the states
that signed the procedure (peace plan) has complied fully with the
letter of the agreement.''
   Costa Rica has not yet ratified the treaty establishing the
Central American Parliament envisaged in the plan, Madrigal Nieto
noted.
   The presidents of Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Honduras, Guatemala and
El Salvador signed a peace plan Aug. 7, 1987, which has as its main
goals: cease-fires in insurgencies taking place in Nicaragua,
Guatamala and El Salvador; amnesty decrees; democratization
measures; lifting of emergency or martial laws; an end to outside
military adventurism in the region, and an end to using any
country's territory by groups or individuals seeking the overthrow
of a neighboring government.
   ``Unfortunately, we have to say that, over the months, we have
seen the Nicaraguan government step up its repression, move away
from fulfilling its commitments and attempt to reduce the crisis to
a problem of security, showing obvious contempt for democratic
values,'' Madrigal Nieto said.
   ``The most alarming thing, however, is that this situation has
serious repercussions for Nicaragua's neighbors, who have to take
in the thousands of people who flee in search of freedom, food and
shelter.''
   Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government has been fighting
U.S.-backed rebels known as Contras since 1981.
   Madrigal Nieto told reporters later, speaking in English, ``The
firm commitment to democracy has not been made by some countries,
and that is the main problem.
   ``I mentioned Nicaragua clearly in my speech because I do not
think they have the political will to carry it (the peace process)
on. I think they could introduce a lot of changes, and they should
assume some other attitudes, more positive ones, to see real
progress.
   ``We think they should not send 40 political leaders to jail, as
they have had 40 people for more than 80 days without due process.
That does not contribute to our efforts to find this (diplomatic)
solution above any decision of the United States'' to fund a
military solution through the Contra rebels, he said.
   Madrigal Nieto said such democratic reforms would save Nicaragua
from later counter-revolution by rightists radicalized by
repression by the Sandinistas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
