<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MedflyInfestation     10-03 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medfly Infestation,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>30 More Mediterranean Fruit Flies Found, Major Infestation Feared</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL MONTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty Mediterranean fruit flies were
found in Los Angeles County traps, triggering a major effort to
kill the pests before they destroy crops, authorities said.
   The Medfly, a severe threat to California's multibillion-dollar
agricultural industry, is considered one of the most destructive
crop-damaging pests because it preys on more than 250 varieties of
produce, reproduces rapidly and survives in different climates,
officials said.
   The state's most serious infestation cost $97.6 million in
eradication efforts that continued from 1980 to 1982.
   The flies, both male and female, were discovered over the
weekend, said William Edwards, chief deputy to the county
agriculture commissioner.
   More than 1,300 detection traps were set after a male fruit fly
was discovered in a trap last week.
   ``This one has the potential to be really bad,'' Edwards said.
``Thirty-one flies is a significant number to start out with.''
   Edwards said aerial applications of the pesticide malathion are
tentatively scheduled for Wednesday.
   Also planned is the release of up to 40 million sterile
Mediterranean fruit flies per week over a couple months in an
effort to eradicate the crop-destroying pests, he said.
</TEXT>
