<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mideast-Carter     10-03 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mideast-Carter,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former President Urges U.N. Peace Conference On Middle East</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter asked
Monday that an international peace conference be held on the Middle
East and cautioned that the superpowers' ``uncontrollable'' allies
there could spark nuclear conflict.
   ``Without peace in the Middle East there cannot be peace in the
world,'' Carter told 900 people in a speech at the Oxford Union,
Oxford University's student-run debating society.
   Carter, 64, called for peace talks supervised by the U.N.
Security Council to resolve disputes in the Middle East and said
wealthy nations should donate $15 billion to fund any agreements
stemming from the proposed forum.
   ``The Palestinians must publicly accept Israel as a nation with
a permanent existence and must renounce violence,'' said Carter,
who also urged Israel to respect ``basic human rights'' and
self-determination for the Plestinians.
   During his presidency, the Georgia Democrat was architect of the
1978 Camp David accords between Israel and Egypt.
   Carter said the Middle East remained the most likely flashpoint
for a nuclear war between the United States and the Soviet Union.
   ``The Soviet Union and the United States have allies and friends
in that region who are unpredictable and uncontrollable,'' he said.
``There is no way to have an easy ... solution to the problems of
the Middle East, but the overwhelming majority of people there want
peace and justice.''
   He condemned Israel for using plastic bullets in the 10-month
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
Israeli authories say the bullets, which reportedly killed several
protesters, are designed to cause injuries.
   The former president's appearance at Oxford followed his recent
tour of the Middle East.
</TEXT>
