<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BallotQuestion     10-03 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ballot Question,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Blocks Anti-Abortion Measure From Ballot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court on Monday
dismissed an appeal by an anti-abortion group seeking to put a
question on the state's November ballot about whether human life
begins at conception.
   The justices of the state's highest court issued the dismissal
without explanation, saying they wanted to make the decision known
by the ballot's printing deadline but needed more time to write
their ``opinion or opinions.''
   ``Until we find out (the court's reasons), I don't know what to
say except that I am greatly disappointed,'' said John Rankin, head
of the New England Christian Action Council, which sponsored the
ballot question.
   Susan Newsom, spokeswoman of the Planned Parenthood League of
Massachusetts, said the court had made a good ruling.
   ``I am not surpised at all at that decision. (The referendum)
did not fit the criteria at all for a public policy question.''
   The question would have asked voters to define, in biological
terms, when life begins. It gave three possible answers _
``conception, viability or birth'' and a write-in option where
voters could ``specify a different biological term.''
   State Attorney General James Shannon had ruled the non-biding
referendum improper, saying it failed to give a clear directive to
lawmakers and was ambiguous.
   Rankin said the question's objective was to develop a consensus
on when human life begins to redress what he considers a failing to
answer the question in the landmark Roe vs. Wade U.S. Supreme Court
decision allowing abortions.
   Although Rankin's group was unable to get the question on the
1988 Massachusetts ballot, Rankin found success in being able to
collect nearly 26,000 signatures for his ballot petition.
   ``I think what we have done so far is redefined the debate'' on
the issue from one typically limited to government funding for
abortions to a broader question, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
