<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-SmithExecution     10-03 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Smith Execution,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Refuses To Reverse Stay Of Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday night refused to
let Missouri officials execute a convicted killer who was scheduled
to be the state's first death row inmate put to death in 23 years.
   The Justices, without dissent, rejected an emergency request
aimed at setting aside a lower court's postponement of Gerald
Smith's execution, which had been scheduled for early Tuesday.
   Smith, who had asked that there be no appeals made to delay his
execution, was convicted of the 1980 bludgeoning death of Karen
Roberts, a woman he said had given him a venereal disease and
caused him to lose his fiancee. He was given a second death penalty
for his part in the 1985 stabbing murder of fellow death row inmate
Robert Baker.
   He was to have been killed by lethal injection. The high court's
action means Smith will not be executed pending further review of
his case.
   No convicted murder has been executed in Missouri since 1965,
when Lloyd Leo Anderson was sent to the gas chamber for murdering a
teen-age delivery boy during a drugstore robbery.
</TEXT>
