<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-PersianGulf-POWs Adv10   10-03 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Persian Gulf-POWs, Adv 10,0818</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Oct. 10 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Thousands of POWs Stranded by Stalled Iran-Iraq Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stalled Iran-Iraq peace talks have
left tens of thousands of prisoners of the Iran-Iraq war
languishing in camps, waiting for freedom that may be months, even
years, away.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran, who heads his
country's delegation at the talks, said in a recent Tehran radio
interview monitored in Nicosia: ``We're trying to get an exchange
of POWs arranged as quickly as possible.''
   But United Nations officials said the issue has still had not
been discussed at the month-old peace talks when they went into
their stall.
   When a prisoner exchange does come off, however, it will be the
biggest organized by the International Committee of the Red Cross
since the Geneva Convention of 1949.
   The Red Cross has registered 50,182 prisoners held by Iran and
19,284 by Iraq. But U.N. officials and diplomats in Baghdad and
Tehran believe Iran holds 60,000 to 70,000 prisoners and Iraq
30,000 to 50,000.
   The POWs include hundreds of Iranian boy soldiers, many of whom
have been held since the early days of the 8-year-old war and have
grown up in captivity.
   The Soviet Union held thousands of Germans after World War II.
The last 9,000 were only released in 1955 after the Soviets and
West Germans agreed to establishing diplomatic relations.
   Iran has freed a handful of disabled Iraqis since a cease-fire
took effect Aug. 20.
   But Iraq has freed none and has even added to its tally by
seizing more than 700 Iranians in September in what Tehran claims
was a major cease-fire violation.
   U.N. observers have confirmed the Iranians were captured, but so
far have not been able to secure their release.
   Iraq's information minister, Latif Nayef Jassim, said his
countrymen ``are opening their arms wide to welcome home'' the POWs
held by Iran.
   But some diplomats fear that both sides will try to use the
prisoners as bargaining chips in the peace talks that bogged down,
almost as soon as they began, over sovereignty of the Shatt Al-Arab
waterway and troop withdrawals.
   The POWs appear to have become pawns in the propaganda war
between Iran and Iraq that has swelled since the peace talks began
Aug. 25 in Geneva.
   Iraq, stung by international condemnation for its alleged use of
outlawed chemical weapons against Kurdish rebels, has intensified
accusations that the Iranians have tortured, killed and brainwashed
Iraqi POWs. Iran has made similar charges.
   Jassim recently accused the Iranians of ``inhuman practices .. .
starting with mass executions and ending with psychological
torture.''
   The official Iraqi News Agency quoted him as saying in a
statement: ``The savagery of Iran's rulers and their mad practices
against Iraqi POWs has caused the death of a large number of them.''
   Thirty disabled Iraqi POWs released by Iran in early September
recently told a Baghdad news conference that their Iranian guards
systematically torture prisoners and pressure them to switch
allegiances. Like most Iranians, many Iraqis are Shiite Moslems.
   Christians among the Iraqi POWs were singled out and subjected
to extreme maltreatment and pressure to convert to Islam by their
Shiite guards, the ex-POWs said.
   ``When I told them I was a Christian, they asked me to convert
to Islam before they would give me any medical help,'' said Wa'd
Aziz Na'mou, who told reporters he was captured in January 1987,
after he was wounded in the eyes during an Iranian offensive.
   ``I refused and they left me without treatment. I lost both
eyes. Many of the Christian soldiers were forced to convert to
Islam under psychological pressure and torture.''
   The prisoner's account could not be independently confirmed with
other sources or raised with Iranian officials because of limited
access Western news organizations have with Tehran.
   A prisoner exchange could also be hampered by thousands of POWs
held by both sides who do not want to return to their homelands or
who fear persecution once back home.
   A U.N. report in August said officials who visited some of the
15 known POW camps in Iran reported that they appeared to be run
internally by Iraqi Shiites who had switched allegiance to
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The report said that as many as 20 percent of the Iraqi POWs
seen by the officials appeared to be defectors. Tehran newspapers
have said up to 20,000 Iraqi prisoners have opted to stay in Iran.
   The U.N. report added that many POWs on both sides fear
persecution if they go home and said Iraqi prisoners might riot if
repatriation is attempted.
   Many Iranians were also hesitant about being exchanged, the
report said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs Oct. 10</NOTE>
