<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0903EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Lisbon-ChiadoFire Adv11   10-03 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lisbon-Chiado Fire, Adv 11,0694</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs Oct. 11 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Talk of Lisbon: Bringing Back a Burned-Out Chiado</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The talk of Lisbon these days is about
the Chiado, the 10-block area of 19th-century department stores and
shops swept by fire Aug. 25.
   Most of the talk centers on the Chiado's future in the heart of
the city.
   Will it be restored to what it was? Will modern high-rises win
out?
   ``I think they will have to preserve the facades of the district
_ it will have to look like it did before,'' said Joao Bento, a
26-year-old bank employee.
   Experts say facades of 18 of the 20 buildings damaged by the
fire are restorable.
   Even while the embers were still glowing on rua do Carmo and rua
Garrett, many Lisbonites began to worry that municipal authorities
would commission an up-market, high-rise development on the ashes.
   ``No one can have the illusion the Chiado will be what it was,''
said Alvaro Siza Vieira, an architect recently appointed by Mayor
Nuno Kruz Abecasis to plan the restoration. ``Even the dirt
engrained on the tiled facades was part of the atmosphere.''
   But Siza Vieira is not seen as likely to suggest a sprawling
hi-tech plan and has made his proposals subject to vetting by the
Portuguese Architects Association.
   But whatever form it takes, the ``new'' Chiado is expected to
point the way for the rest of this historic city, whose buildings
exhibit a ravishing collage of architectural styles but are in dire
need of restoration.
   Pedro Brandao, secretary general of the Architects Association,
said the organization wants a competition among local architects to
form a development team for the whole historic area of the Baixa,
Lisbon's lower city that was destroyed in the 1755 earthquake and
of which the Chiado is just one part.
   But Chiado watchers have concerns other than architecture,
provided the proposed plan does not involve complexes of apartments
of glass and aluminum.
   Author Jose Victor Adragao, for example, maintains that the
Chiado is cherished as much as anything else for its ``air, sounds,
smell of violets and roasting chestnuts, strolls and sandwiches
before the opera _ and because it is Lisbon.''
   Goncalo Ribeiro Teles, City Council member for the
ecology-conscious Monarchist Party, cautions: ``In other parts of
the city big businesses and banks have sprung up where cafes and
restaurants once were and have killed the city. The offices close
early, people leave and the area dies.''
   Insurers say the inferno caused $300 million in material damage,
but the Lisbon Shopkeepers Association estimates losses at double
that figure.
   Many small shopkeepers were under-insured at the time of the
fire and might not be able to afford to move into a new Chiado
commercial center, despite cheap loans from a $32.5-million
government credit line offered to traders to help them get back in
business.
   The lack of cash could also cast a pall on Ribeiro Teles' hopes
of handing back new Chiado apartments to the area's pre-blaze
residents who benefited from long-standing rent control.
   New apartments on expensive city center ground mean new leases
and higher rents, forcing former low-income residents out of a new
residential Chiado. The fire rendered 300 people homeless and left
1,200 shopworkers unemployed. Two people were killed in the fire
and 43 were injured.
   Alternative plans to keep the Chiado alive would be hotels or
student accommodations.
   One banker said he had already received hundreds of phone calls
from investors, mainly Japanese and Germans, asking to secure
pockets of land in the neighborhood.
   But the problem, Ribeiro Teles said, ``involves the whole of
Lisbon's historic zone and is vaster and much more serious than
that of the Chiado.''
   Brandao agrees.
   ``For the Chiago to recuperate, great amounts of money are not
needed ... but to restore all the historic part of Lisbon, we need
a lot _ and we don't have enough for that in all of Portugal.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Oct. 11 or Thereafter</NOTE>
