<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, Oct. 15, the 289th day of 1988. There are 77
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Oct. 15, 1860, 11-year-old Grace Bedell of Westfield, N.Y.,
wrote a letter to presidential candidate Abraham Lincoln suggesting
he would look better if he were to grow a beard.
   On this date:
   In 1914, the Clayton Antitrust Act was passed.
   In 1917, Mata Hari, a Dutch dancer who had spied for the
Germans, was executed by firing squad outside Paris.
   In 1928, the German dirigible ``Graf Zeppelin'' landed in
Lakehurst, N.J., on its first commercial flight across the Atlantic.
   In 1937, the Ernest Hemingway novel ``To Have and Have Not'' was
first published.
   In 1945, the former premier of Vichy France, Pierre Laval, was
executed.
   In 1946, Nazi war criminal Hermann Goering poisoned himself one
day before he was to be executed.
   In 1951, the television series ``I Love Lucy,'' starring Lucille
Ball and Desi Arnaz, premiered on CBS.
   In 1964, it was announced that Soviet leader Nikita S.
Khrushchev had been removed from office. He was succeeded as
premier by Alexei N. Kosygin and as Communist Party secretary by
Leonid I. Brezhnev.
   In 1966, President Lyndon B. Johnson signed a bill creating the
Department of Transportation.
   In 1969, peace demonstrators staged activities across the
country, including a candlelight march around the White House, as
part of a moratorium against the Vietnam War.
   In 1976, in the first debate of its kind, the major-ticket
vice-presidential nominees, Democrat Walter Mondale and Republican
Bob Dole, faced off in Houston.
   Ten years ago: The 95th Congress adjourned after an all-night
session during which lawmakers took final action on about two dozen
bills, including energy legislation, tax reduction, airline
deregulation and the Humphrey-Hawkins full-employment measure.
   Five years ago: U.S. Marine sharpshooters reported killing five
snipers who had pinned them down at Beirut International Airport _
the first time since the Marines were deployed in Lebanon that they
reported killing combatants.
   One year ago: Frantic rescue efforts continued in Midland,
Texas, to save 18-month-old Jessica McClure, who had fallen 22 feet
down an abandoned well the day before. (Jessica was freed the
following evening.)
   Today's birthdays: Economist John Kenneth Galbraith is 80.
Author and historian Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr. is 71. Author Mario
Puzo is 68. Chrysler chairman Lee Iacocca is 64. Actress Linda
Lavin is 51. Actress-director Penny Marshall is 43. Musician
Richard Carpenter is 42. Tennis player Roscoe Tanner is 37. Singer
Tito Jackson is 35. Britain's Duchess of York (formerly Sarah
Ferguson) is 29.
   Thought for today: ``The young do not know enough to be prudent,
and therefore they attempt the impossible _ and achieve it,
generation after generation.'' _ Pearl S. Buck, American Pulitzer
and Nobel Prize-winning author (1892-1973).
</TEXT>
