<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--TheNewGuard-Honduras ADV16   10-03 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--The New Guard-Honduras, ADV 16,0798</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--The New Guard-I</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMP POWDERHORN, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The civilian visitors troop
into the green Army squad tent one by one, pausing at the entrance
to slake thirsts born of a tropic sun with paper cupfuls of
Kool-Aid.
   They have come by helicopter to this dusty camp in a remote,
northern Honduran valley to see for themselves the work of Task
Force III of the U.S. Army National Guard.
   Using charts and maps on easel boards, the task force commander,
Col. Eldridge Casto Jr. and his aides explain their mission, to
build the final seven miles of a 34-mile road into the Yoro Valley.
   Casto, a spare man with a West Virginia drawl, speaks with pride
of the men and women under his command who have moved thousands
upon thousands of cubic yards of earth, crushed ton upon ton of
rock into gravel and forced a formidable path across towering
mountains.
   He speaks, too, of the hundreds of doctors and nurses of the
National Guard who have gone into dozens of remote villages to
vaccinate and treat men, women, children, cows, horses, goats,
sheep, dogs and cats for an array of exotic ailments seldom seen in
the United States.
   ``It is invaluable experience,'' the colonel tells his visitors.
``It is something we simply can't get at home.''
   So for three years running, thousands of National Guard members
have come to Honduras in the November-to-June dry season to work
for two weeks alongside regular U.S. Army and Honduran soldiers on
a project once known as ``Blazing Trails-86'' and now called
``Fuertes Caminos-88.'' The Spanish name means Strong Roads.
   When work is completed in a few days, Casto says, the Yoro
Valley will for the first time be open to the outside world,
permitting access to new markets by its peasant farmers and
creating the possibility of development in one of the poorest parts
of one of the poorest nations in the Western Hemisphere.
   ``The humanitarian aspects of this project are immeasurable,''
the colonel tells his listeners, who include a bank president from
Sardis, Miss., a state representative from Washington and a
professor from the Georgia Institute of Technology.
   His guests this day number 28. Many are community leaders back
home and they have been flown to Honduras in a military version of
a Boeing 727 with an escort that includes Lt. Gen. Herbert R.
Temple Jr., chief of the National Guard Bureau in Washington, D.C.
   In three days of briefings and tours, they will be told of
National Guard training exercises that cannot be duplicated in the
United States, of the good that comes from accompanying civic
action programs that range from drilling wells and constructing
latrines to building orphanages and schools.
   They will see with their own eyes the shy, grateful smiles of
Hondurans in one of 80 tiny, northern villages as they receive
periodic medical and dental care from a team of regular Army,
National Guard and local doctors, dentists and nurses.
   When the visitors return home, it is hoped they will carry what
they have seen and heard to political associates, civic clubs,
church groups and the like, for the National Guard is increasingly
under fire for conducting training missions abroad and needs all
the friends it can get.
   The road being built by the National Guard is not simply a
farm-to-market route designed to bring progress to an isolated
valley. It is a military road, built to the specifications of
Honduran army engineers, and designed to carry the heavy weapons of
war _ trucks, artillery, even tanks.
   And the Hondurans wanted this road in this particular place
because the Yoro Valley has for years been the inaccessible hiding
place of a small but persistent band of leftist insurgents.
   It is the National Guard's involvement, however tangential, in
the internal and even foreign affairs of other countries that has
troubled some Americans. Several governors, including
Massachusetts' Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential
candidate, have objected to foreign training of their state
militias, arguing that they are being used for a purpose they were
never designed to fulfill _ the projection of U.S. policy abroad.
   American political influence and the presence of U.S. military
personnel in Honduras, including the 1,200 members of Task Force
Bravo permanently stationed at Palmerola Air Base also bothers many
Hondurans. It goes hand in glove with their dislike of the
U.S.-backed Contra rebels who have been operating out of base camps
in Honduras for more than six years in an attempt to overthrow the
communist government of neighboring Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
