<DOCNO> AP881003-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--TheNewGuard-Image ADV16   10-03 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--The New Guard-Image, ADV 16,0700</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN-The New Guard-I</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite vastly improved equipment and more
intense training during the military buildup of the Reagan years,
America's National Guard still has an image problem.
   The regular Army still isn't quite ready to accept the new Guard
as its equal in the Total Force battle plan.
   ``They're not exactly an orphan any more,'' says a top Pentagon
official who did not want to be identified. ``But they're still a
poor relation.
   ``Realistically, how do you integrate, train and equip a
part-time Guard on a par with a full-time force? I think you can
count on them to fight. But for the most part, you can't count on
them in the very first wave of the war.''
   Says one Army officer: ``They're better, but they're not ready
to saddle up and fight as soon as the rest of my division gets the
call.''
   Adds another: ``They're still part-time soldiers. That's what
they're supposed to be, and that's what they are.''
   On the other hand, Gen. John R. Galvin, commander of the U.S.
and NATO forces in Europe, observed a National Guard unit training
in West Germany in late September and commented later: ``I'm really
high on them after what I have seen out here.''
   Military officers on both sides of the fence agree the National
Guard is a much more credible fighting force today than perhaps at
any point in peacetime history.
   They cite a real push to modernize Guard units: better-quality
recruits; worldwide training year-round instead of ``summer camp''
at home, and a serious effort to require Guard units to meet the
same type of readiness standards as active units.
   Lt. Col. John Chapla, a spokesman for the active-duty Army at
the Pentagon, says the parent service is convinced that attitudes
are changing as the Guard's war-fighting ability improves.
   ``Generally speaking, the ability of the Guard and Reserve to
work with the active-duty units has been significantly improved,''
Chapla says. ``We are now better prepared to go to war as a total
Army.
   ``And with those improvements, the attitudes about the Guard
being just `weekend warriors' are dying out. The attitudes are
changing. We are not going to be able to go to war and fight
effectively without significant participation by Guard and Reserve
components.''
   ``That's the official line, and things have improved, but old
attitudes die hard,'' counters a National Guard officer, who like a
half-dozen other officers and officials agreed to comment if not
identified.
   ``You can see it when they watch us train. There's still a kind
of snobbery.''
   ``I'm sure the questions still linger in the minds of the
decision-makers: `How reliable are they?' `How well-led are they?'
'' says another Guard officer.
   What about the Air Guard, the other half of the National Guard?
Officers in the field and in Washington express no doubts about its
fighting readiness.
   ``The relationship between the Guard and Air Force has always
been different,'' one official says. ``You've got fly-boys who flew
for the active force, are still flying today for airlines and
keeping their hands in, flying fighters on the weekends.''
   ``The Air Guard almost always has to be with the active force
for training, while the Army National Guard can train in their back
yard,'' observes an Army guard officer. ``That's an important
difference.
   ``And they tend to be flying every day, in their civilian jobs,
too. The guys in that Army Guard unit aren't smelling ordnance
every day. You can't be a recreational artilleryman. But those Air
Guard guys never stop flying and the active crews recognize that.''
   The Army National Guard in the old days was widely regarded as
something of a political organization.
   ``It used to be solely a question of who you knew to climb to
the top,'' says one Pentgon civilian.
   ``That's changed a lot. There are standards for a state adjutant
general, for example. But the perception hasn't caught up.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
