<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek ADV16   10-03 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, ADV 16,0876</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To get to the offices of ``The Van Dyke
Show'' at Culver Studios you have to go to the rear of the building
and climb two flights of iron stairs.
   ``Maybe if the show does well we'll get new offices without
stairs,'' says Dick Van Dyke.
   In a new half-hour comedy on CBS, Van Dyke and his son, Barry,
play a father and son who team up to run a struggling regional
theater in a rural town in Pennsylvania. Barry gives up a career in
advertising to pursue his dream of running the theater. Dick is a
famous stage and screen star who stops off to see his son and is
dragooned into an effort to salvage the risky venture.
   ``The Van Dyke Show'' has its own hard climb ahead.
   The show is paired with Mary Tyler Moore's new sitcom on CBS on
Wednesday nights. Both shows premiere Oct. 26, although Miss
Moore's show is as yet untitled. It's a comeback effort for both of
them, once among the most beloved entertainers on television. It's
been a long time since either has had a hit show.
   ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' in the 1960s, which also starred Miss
Moore, is a classic that makes just about everyone's list of
favorite shows. His next situation comedy was only moderately
successful, and his attempt at a variety show, ``Van Dyke and
Company,'' was a quick failure. His last regular appearance was on
``The Carol Burnett Show'' in 1977. He hasn't had his own show in
12 years.
   ``There's no talk that I know of to have Mary and I visit each
other's shows,'' Van Dyke says. ``But if I don't deliver her some
ratings she may drop in on me.''
   Barry Van Dyke has been in four series, ``The Harvey Korman
Show,'' ``Battlestar Galactica,'' ``Gun Shy'' and ``The Redd Foxx
Show,'' but none was a success.
   ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' in the 1970s was another gem. But
two attempts at a variety show didn't work, nor did Miss Moore's
next comedy series in 1985-86.
   Both Van Dyke and Miss Moore face formidable competition on
Wednesday nights from ABC's ``Growing Pains'' and ``Head of the
Class'' and NBC's ``Unsolved Mysteries.''
   ``The Van Dyke Show'' also stars Kari Lizer as Barry's wife,
Barry O'Sullivan as their son, Whitman Mayo as the stage manager
and Maura Tierny as the woman who runs the ticket office.
   The show has also run into creative problems.
   ``We discarded the pilot because it wasn't right,'' says the
senior Van Dyke. ``We've made some changes in the concept and in
the cast. I think in the pilot we tried to get in so much
background exposition that we forgot to be entertaining. Our
relationship is no longer so adversarial.''
   Barry says, ``We had too much conflict and not enough comedy. It
was real but it wasn't funny. We've gotten rid of all the
background where he had been an absentee father and I was
resentful. We deal more with the present and the future: how a play
will be done, whether I'm going to let him help me out
financially.''
   ``We'll probably get into generational differences, such as how
to raise a child,'' adds Dick.
   All three of Van Dyke's comedies have centered on shows within
the show. In the first he was a writer on ``The Alan Brady Show,''
with Carl Reiner playing Brady. In the second show he was the host
of a local television talk show. And in the present show the focus
is the theater.
   The elder Van Dyke is well-tanned and his jaw juts out like a
snowplow beneath thick white hair. He wears a blue pullover sweater
with rimless glasses hanging from his neck, white sailing pants and
sneakers without socks. Barry looks like a younger version, but is
more conservatively dressed in darker clothes.
   This is their first real collaboration, although Barry made his
television debut on Dick's ``Morning Show'' on CBS in 1955. ``I'd
come out and say, `Daddy,''' he recalls.
   His acting debut was on ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' at the age of
9 in 1962. He later worked as an associate producer on ``The New
Dick Van Dyke Show'' and made occasional appearances in small parts.
   ``Alan Brady had a talent show and I came in and played a
violin,'' Barry says of his debut performance. ``I was actually
taking violin lessons at the time. But that got me hooked on
acting. To a 9-year-old it looked like a great way to make a
living. Dad held me back until I was older.''
   Dick says he may use some of his own stage appearances for the
series. He won a Tony as best supporting actor for ``Bye Bye
Birdie.'' His last appearance on Broadway came when he took ``The
Music Man'' on the road and finished the tour at the City Center in
New York.
</TEXT>
