<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV16-2Takes   10-03 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 16-2 Takes,0695</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In this city that boasts an extraordinary
symphony orchestra and a first-rate art museum, Josephine Abady
hopes to provide something it never has had before _ a world-class
theater.
   Her formidable task is to wake up the slumbering Cleveland Play
House, a regional theater long on history and short on artistic
excitement. For more than 70 years the theater has been part of
Cleveland's cultural life, alive but rarely making waves or
attracting attention.
   That changed after Abady arrived in January as the theater's
artistic director and began planning 13 productions on three stages
for her 1988-89 season. One of the first things she did was fire
the company's resident acting troupe, including some members who
had been employed for 25 years or more. There were protests from
some longtime subscribers, unhappy Play House board members and
angry letters to the Cleveland Plain Dealer.
   ``I'm not the most popular girl in Cleveland,'' Abady says now.
``It was a very, very difficult decision to make, but this theater
had become very insular. It had used the same actors over and over.
So the quality and level of performance and production here had
become very small.''
   Abady will now cast each show separately, bringing in what she
says will be the best actors and directors she can find. And she
has a budget of $4.8 million, up $1 million from the previous
season, to bring her plans to fruition.
   She also brought in her own production staff, including a
literary manager and a company director, to strengthen the artistic
side of the operation. And she began putting together a season she
hoped would attract audiences and stop the downward spiral of
subscribers. They now number about 12,000, about half of the
capacity of the Play House's three theaters.
   What she devised was a fascinating mixture of the old and the
new.
   Her first production, although not part of the first season's
subscription series, was ``Born Yesterday,'' by Garson Kanin and
starring Ed Asner and Madeline Kahn. They were two big names who
might lure back audiences who stopped going to the Play House.
Abady directed the revival herself and after the September opening
in Cleveland, the play is on a long national tour before arriving
on Broadway next January. When it does, the Play House will gain
further visibility as one of its producers.
   Currently on her agenda is ``On the Waterfront,'' the world
premiere of the stage version of Budd Schulberg's novel of the same
name, adapted by Schulberg and Stan Silverman. Grant Show, of
television's ``Ryan's Hope,'' plays Terry Malloy, the role made
famous by Marlon Brando in the film, and Abady will direct again.
It will run through Nov. 20.
   ``I wanted to start off the subscription season here with
something that is new and dynamic but also familiar enough that
people who hadn't been coming to the Play House might be
attracted,'' Abady says. ``Something that was related to this
community without being a local play. And then I remembered that
Cleveland is redeveloping its waterfront.''
   For the rest of the season that ends next May, she has several
new plays including ``Italian-American Reconciliation'' by John
Patrick Shanley, who won an Oscar for his ``Moonstruck''
screenplay, and ``Real Dreams,'' a play set in Cleveland but
written by an Englishman. More traditional offerings include the
musical ``Carnival,'' directed by Jack Hofsiss; the London and
Broadway hit ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses,'' and an all-black cast in
``The Glass Menagerie,'' starring Ruby Dee.
   ``Most of the stuff is new because I think if a theater is going
to make its mark on the community and, ultimately, the theatrical
world at large, you have to generate work as well as reproduce
work,'' Abady says. ```Born Yesterday' is a loving revival, but you
also have to do things like `Waterfront' and `Italian-American
Reconciliation'' and `Real Dreams.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881003-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV16-1stAdd   10-03 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 16-1st Add,0664</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>CLEVELAND: `Real Dreams.'''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   It's that community awareness and national profile that the
Cleveland Play House wants.
   The company certainly has the facilities: Its three-theater
complex looks like a red-brick medieval village rising out of the
ruins of the city's run-down East Side, an area still recovering
from the riots of the late 1960s.
   Behind the three theaters stands an old Sears, Roebuck
department store purchased by the Play House in 1980. The building,
now renovated, holds production facilities, some 200,000 square
feet of space where sets, costumes and props can be stored and
where rehearsals are held. What was once the ladies lingerie
department is now a private club and restaurant for theater
subscribers.
   Two of its theaters were built, side by side, in 1927 and a
third, larger theater, designed by Philip Johnson, was opened in
1983. Johnson linked all three theaters together with a huge
rotunda and added connecting passageways.
   ``This theater has always been a family affair. When they built
this building, it stopped being a family affair,'' Abady says,
referring to the Johnson project. ``It costs $1 million a year to
run it before there is the first bit of art on stage. Like a lot of
institutions, they had the edifice complex for a while.''
   Despite its long history, the Play House has had only a half
dozen or so artistic directors. The theater was founded in 1915 but
didn't really start developing until 1921 when Frederic McConnell
and K. Elmo Lowe came from Pittsburgh to run it. By the time Lowe
retired in 1969, their reign had lasted nearly 50 years. The
company had become a family. It also had its share of famous
graduates _ performers such as Joel Grey, Paul Newman, Margaret
Hamilton, Alan Alda and Dom DeLuise played the theater.
   In the 1970s, the theater was directed by Richard Oberlin who
had been trained by McConnell and Lowe. By the end of the decade,
critics were starting to grumble about the quality of the
productions. Some called the Play House dull, one step up from
community theater.
   The malaise continued into the '80s, and when Oberlin resigned
in 1985 William Rhys was named acting director. Rhys took over the
theater, while the board began its search for a permanent artistic
director who would be a strong leader. They found her in the
Berkshires.
   The 39-year-old Abady has made a lot of difficult decisions in
her career. For nine years, she ran the Berkshire Theater Festival
in Stockbridge, Mass. She eliminated the festival's deficit, set up
an endowment fund, reconditioned the theater and made it a center
for American drama. The festival even started to develop a national
profile, coming out from under the shadow of the Williamstown
Theater Festival, a star-studded summer troupe that also operates
in the Berkshires.
   ``I probably could have done that job for the rest of my life,''
Abady says. ``But I felt I wanted a new challenge, and I was afraid
of getting stale.''
   Abady will be a visible artistic director in Cleveland.
Brochures for the new season proclaim, ``Josephine Abady is coming
to town.'' Her name is stamped on the product, whether it succeeds
or not.
   ``My theory of management has always been the same, although
managers probably will have a fit,'' she says. ``You hire really
good people to do their jobs, tell them what the parameters are and
then you leave them alone. I've always had good people working for
me.
   ``If you make the environment for actors, directors and staff a
really productive one, where people feel they have a stake in the
outcome, it's easy to get good people,'' Abady says. ``The beauty
and thrill of the theater is that it's a collaborative process, if
it happens correctly. That's what I want to institute here.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
