<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo ADV00   10-03 0943</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, ADV 00,0983</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``White of the Eye'' (Paramount Home Video; VHS, $89.95; Beta,
$29.95; Rated R)
   
   Joan is on her way to Malibu with her hippie-like friend, Mike.
They stop in the desert near Tucson, Ariz., where she meets and
falls in love with Paul.
   Bad move, Joanie. The desert seems to have its way with women.
   And in ``White of the Eye,'' women drop like so many grains of
sand, hacked to death by a deranged killer who stores their body
parts in plastic bags.
   Joan's biggest problem, besides her self-indulgence, is that the
killer is husband Paul, who appears to be a normal father and a
passionate lover. But he occasionally has the need to paint his
face, don a samurai hairdo, lay out Indian objects in some sort of
bizarre ritual and kill a woman.
   David Keith plays Paul with a quiet rage. Though police suspect
him from the start, we are led to believe his innocence. But the
script never quite explains what has led the successful audio
technician to be a homicidal maniac.
   Cathy Moriarty gives her sexy all to Joan, and does her best
working with the silly and sometimes farfetched dialogue and
situations written by China and Donald Cammell, who also directed.
   When Joan finds her husband's stash of spare body parts, she
calmly calls up a girlfriend and asks her to take care of their
daughter for the night. The reason? ``Marital problems.'' Be real.
   Despite a weak script and lapses of reality, ``White of the
Eye'' offers glorious camera work by Larry McConkey and nice
performances by Keith and Moriarty.
   The R rating is well deserved for violence. There also is sexual
content.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Last Emperor'' (Nelson Entertainment; VHS-Beta, $89.98;
Rated PG-13)
   
   Probably no recent film better exemplifies what a blessing home
video is than ``The Last Emperor.'' This epic, which won nine
Academy Awards including best picture, must surely rank with the
best films ever made, and yet hasn't enjoyed the box-office success
it richly deserves.
   Now with video, you can catch what many of you so foolishly
missed.
   Director Bernardo Bertolucci makes brilliant and seamless use of
flashbacks to tell the saga of Pu Yi who became emperor of China in
1908, the last before that nation was sundered by 20th-century wars
and social forces.
   Pu Yi is a fascinating, paradoxical historical figure because,
as the movie shows so movingly, this man born to seemingly
unlimited power is nothing more than a prisoner in a gilded cage, a
museum piece who takes a painful lifetime to realize how time has
passed him and his royal kind by. He is a pawn who thinks himself a
king.
   His whole life is spent as a captive _ first of the Forbidden
City in Beijing, later of the Japanese when they set him up as
puppet ruler in their captive state of Manchukuo in the 1930s.
Finally, he spends a decade in a prison getting ``re-educated'' by
the Chinese Communists who revile him as a Japanese collaborator.
   Bertolucci's feat is in no small measure thanks to the Chinese
who allowed him to film on location at the Forbidden City. It makes
for an eyeful.
   ``The Last Emperor'' runs 2 hours and 44 minutes, but is never
less than gripping. The film is rated PG-13, with a few very brief
snatches of nudity and a word or two of profanity.
   _ By Lee Mitgang, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``School Daze'' (RCA-Columbia Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95;
Rated R)
   
   At the end of Spike Lee's latest and eagerly awaited film, the
hero storms the campus of a black college yelling ``Wake up!''
Unfortunately, that call may be needed by many who sit all the way
through an occasionally bright film which seems to have lost its
way.
   Not quite a drama, never exactly a comedy, ``School Daze'' even
takes a stab at being a musical. Nothing works well enough to meet
the expectations created by Lee's first big success, ``She's Gotta
Have It.''
   The movie explores conflict between light-skinned ``wannabees''
(want to be whites) and the earthier ``jigaboos'' at Mission
College. The hero, Dap (Larry Fishburne) is leading protests
against the school's investments in South Africa and generally
trying to raise the social consciousness of his fellow students.
   However, his cousin, Half Pint (Spike Lee), aspires to join the
leading fraternity, presided over by the smug, sadistic Julian
(Giancarlo Esposito).
   Half Pint becomes a frat man, in effect, by bedding Julian's
girlfriend _ at Julian's insistence. Unlike Mars Blackmon, the
talkative, street-smart character Lee played in ``She's Gotta Have
It,'' Half Pint is simply a worm. Not many laughs there.
   Among the bright moments in the film is Ossie Davis' cameo as an
overwrought football coach begging his team to end a losing string.
Lee follows with an impressive game scene which never once looks at
the field, but charts the defeat in the sagging spirit of the crowd.
   _ By Robert Barr, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
