<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   10-03 0918</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,0958</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Western Standard Time'' (Epic) _ Asleep At The Wheel
   
   With Asleep At The Wheel, it's always ``Western Standard Time''
_ time for American standards, Western swing style.
   This time out, singer-guitarist-frontman Ray Benson and his six
cohorts swing their way through 10 more songs they like to play,
from Glenn Miller (``Chattanooga Choo Choo'') to Commander Cody and
His Lost Planet Airmen (``Hot Rod Lincoln'').
   For the most part, these are reverential renditions of
certifiably great American music.
   ``San Antonio Rose,'' the signature song of the king of Western
swing, Bob Wills, is served up almost too neatly, with Benson
resonant but overly controlled in the footsteps of Tommy Duncan,
Wills' longtime lead singer.
   Another standard, ``Walking the Floor Over You,'' works better,
going for the spirit of that great country classic, down to a
pretty good job of sounding like Ernest Tubb _ which can't be an
easy thing to do.
   ``Chattanooga Choo Choo'' finds Benson and Willie Nelson
swapping vocals over a heavy horn arrangement, making a song that's
become a cliche interesting again. Nelson shows he could have been
a fine orchestra crooner _ a country Crosby, if you will.
   Weakest are two Side 2 throwaways: an overly serious ``Roly
Poly,'' a silly ode to obesity; and the instrumental ``Sugarfoot
Rag,'' for aficionados only.
   Western swing seems to be making sort of a comeback these days;
George Strait's Ace In The Hole Band is a prime example. And that
must bring some feeling of vindication to Asleep At The Wheel, a
proudly anachronistic band pledged for 18 years now to the
perpetuation of an underappreciated art form.
   Despite this album's limitations, when it was over, I found
myself reaching for an old Bob Wills record. And that, I would
think, is the idea.
   _ By Robert Byrd, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Instinct'' (A&M) _ Iggy Pop
   
   This album is a shocker. Who would've thought that Iggy Pop
would still be alive to make a record in his 40s?
   ``Instinct'' can't be compared with the ground-breaking music a
young and crazed Iggy made as leader of Stooges more than 15 years
ago. But there's still a link evident between the Godfather of Punk
and such acts as the Sex Pistols, Ramones and Billy Idol _ all
metal minimalists with a theatrical shtick.
   On ``Instinct,'' the metal tramples the theatrics. Ex-Pistol
Steve Jones cranks out one thundering rhythm guitar riff after
another while Pop alternately snarls and croons like a cross
between James Dean and Dean Martin.
   The lyrics are dumb, but matched with such simple arrangements,
that's OK. Pop is heartbroken on ``Lowdown,'' mad at the system on
``Power & Freedom'' and on the run on the title cut. But most of
all, he's defiant. ``I ain't gonna be no squarehead,'' Pop sings on
``Squarehead.'' Then he barks.
   It's fortunate for his fans that Iggy still doesn't act his age.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Orlando Gibbons, Second Service and Anthems (CRD) _ Choir of New
College, Oxford, Edward Higginbottom conducting.
   Thomas Weelkes, Ninth Service and Anthems (Nimbus) _ Choir of
Christ Church Cathedral, Oxford, Stephen Darlington conducting.
   
   Gibbons and Weelkes were late figures in England's musical
renaissance, the last great composers of an era dominated by Thomas
Tallis and William Byrd.
   Gibbons, born in 1583, was appointed organist of the Chapel
Royal at age 21, and was named organist of Westminster Abbey two
years before his death in 1625.
   Weelkes, born around 1570, was appointed organist at Chichester
Cathedral in 1601 and died in London in 1623. Weelkes seems to have
been a bad egg, frequently at Chichester for drunkenness and foul
language.
   Both men are well known for their madrigals, including Weelkes'
``O Care Thou Will Despatch Me'' and Gibbons' ``The Silver Swan.''
   The highlights of the Gibbons recording come at the end,
especially a spirited rendition of ``O Clap Your Hands.''
Higginbottom's reading of the verse anthem ``See, See the Word Is
Incarnate'' is more languid but equally assured.
   Higginbottom chose to perform with organ accompaniment instead
of with a consort of viols, a choice which some listeners will
regret. The disc also excludes one of Gibbons' greatest verse
anthems, ``This Is the Record of John.''
   Those reservations aside, this is the most satisfying collection
of Gibbons' sacred music now available _ livelier than the
recording by the King's College Choir made in 1982 and technically
far superior to that by the Clerkes of Oxenford in the mid-1970s.
Both of those earlier recordings have recently been released on CD.
   Weelkes' exile in Chichester adds a touch of poignancy to some
of his greater compositions, which seem to have been intended for
the Chapel Royal in London rather than his provincial cathedral
choir.
   The disc from the choir of Christ Church Cathedral in Oxford
leaves no doubt about Weelkes' talent. ``Alleluia, I heard a
voice'' is a brilliantly effective song of praise despite its minor
key. ``Hosanna to the Son of David'' has become a Palm Sunday
favorite in many churches, and there are few songs of the period as
touching as Weelkes' setting of ``When David heard that Absalom was
slain.''
   The Christ Church choir gives a solid performance, if
occasionally marred by some raggedy trebles on the highest notes.
   _ By Robert Barr, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
