<HEAD>New Research Reveals Side Effect of Potential High Blood Pressure
Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hormone that researchers hope may one day
help victims of high blood pressure may also contribute to abnormal
blood clotting, increasing the risk of stroke or heart attack,
scientists say.
   People with high blood pressure have higher levels of the
hormone, called atrial natriuretic factor, or ANF. They also
experience abnormally fast clotting, apparently because ANF also
appears to help blood clot faster, said Marc Taylor, a clinical
fellow in cardiology at the University of Virginia School of
Medicine in Charlottesville.
   Taylor reported his results at the 42nd Annual Conference and
Scientific Sessions of the American Heart Association's Council on
High Blood Presure Research. Nearly 60 million Americans suffer
from high blood pressure, the heart association said.
   Taylor, who stressed the preliminary nature of the research,
said it is ``too soon to speculate about what this is going to mean
in the long term.''
   ``Every agent that comes along with a beneficial effect always
has its downside,'' said Taylor.
   ANF has a ``lot of possibilities'' for treating congestive heart
failure and high blood pressure, said Taylor, who still expects the
compound eventually to be marketed. Increased blood clotting, if
further research supports the preliminary finding, could be listed
as a side effect, he said.
   Abnormal clotting may contribute to heart attacks, said Taylor,
whose research revealed ANF levels twice as high in people with
high blood pressure as those with normal blood pressure.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mexican-American Diabetics Run Extra Blindness Risk, Study</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Suggests
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican-Americans with diabetes run a higher
risk of developing a potentially blinding eye disease than do
non-Hispanic whites with diabetes, a new study suggests.
   Mexican-American diabetics showed more than twice the risk of
severe retinopathy, a complication of diabetes, in a study by Texas
researchers.
   Previous work has shown that Mexican Americans also have a
three-fold greater prevalence of non-insulin-dependent diabetes
than non-Hispanic whites do, according to the American Diabetes
Association.
   The new work compared 257 diabetic Mexican Americans living in
the San Antonio area with 56 diabetic non-Hispanic whites from
Wisconsin. Generally, the Mexican Americans had their diabetes
diagnosed at earlier ages than the other group, and they had higher
blood-sugar levels.
   Although they also tended to have lower socio-econonomic levels
than the Wisconsin group, detailed analysis showed that made no
differences in the risk of the eye disease.
   The work appears in the July issue of Diabetes, a journal of the
diabetes association.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Great Lakes Climate under Scrutiny at US-Canadian Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The global warming trend due to the
so-called ``greenhouse effect'' could make droughts in the U.S.
Great Lakes region more frequent, dropping lake levels and reviving
nagging questions about whether to divert lake water to parched
lands, a government spokesman said Thursday.
   For that reason, 125 U.S. and Canadian scientists meeting at the
first United States-Canada Symposium on Impacts of Climate Change
on the Great Lakes Basin recommended that the two countries start
attacking the problem of global warming now with joint scientific
study.
   ``We would like to set a tone of mutual cooperation and
understanding,'' said Alan Hecht, an organizer of the conference
and director of the National Climate Program Office in Washington,
D.C. ``We have a very good opportunity to build a constructive
relationship.''
   Pollution and gases that trap the sun's heat are blamed for the
greenhouse effect, and a finding was announced in Toronto last June
that the Earth's temperature rose one degree in the last century
because of it.
   Scientists are concerned that temperatures could rise as much as
9 more degrees Fahrenheit in the next 50 years if the trend
continues, altering weather patterns around the world as well as
lake levels and growing seasons. There is considerable
disagreement, however, over how quickly the Earth's temperature
might rise.
   Dr. F. Kenneth Hare, of Ontario's Commission of Nuclear Safety,
said if the Great Lakes region does get hotter and drier, it would
affect shipping, shoreline recreation and communities, fisheries,
agriculture, hydroelectric power, water quality and sewage
treatment operations.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Obese Rats May Provide Insight Into Blood Pressure-Obesity Link</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strain of obese rats with high blood pressure
may help researchers understand why about half of obese people have
high blood pressure.
   Obesity and high blood pressure have long been known to be
frequent partners, but researchers haven't understood why.
   ``Until now, the only way to study the connection between
obesity and hypertension in the laboratory has been to stuff
animals with food, which is not an ideal approach,'' said Dr.
Theodore Kurtz of the University of California, San Francisco.
   Kurtz and his colleagues are using the rats to investigate
whether obese people develop high blood pressure because of a
reduced sensitivity to insulin, which helps control blood sugar
levels.
   Kurtz and one of his colleagues, Dr. Harrihar Pershadsingh,
suggested earlier this year that in obese people the changes in
insulin response may affect the ability of cells to regulate levels
of calcium. Calcium levels have been shown, in turn, to be high in
blood cells of people with high blood pressure, the researchers
said.
   The rats are important in testing this hypothesis because doing
such tests in humans is difficult, the researchers said _ live
cells must be taken from blood vessel walls. In the rats, the
researchers can easily examine the blood vessel walls to see
whether they, too, have increased levels of calcium.
   Kurtz and Pershadsingh outlined their investigations in San
Francisco at the annual high blood pressure meeting of the American
Heart Association.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 6</NOTE>
