reached a tentative three-year contract agreement over the weekend,
opening the way for a resumption of talks between the union and
Caterpillar Inc.
   The tentative settlement between Deere and the UAW was announced
early CDT Saturday, averting a threatened widespread strike.
   The spotlight now shifts back to the St. Louis suburb of
Bridgeton, Mo., where negotiators for Caterpillar and the UAW
agreed Friday to extend their contract indefinitely and recess
talks pending the outcome of Deere bargaining.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers who grow corn and most other feed
grains in 1989 will have to idle only 10 percent of their base
acreage to qualify for price supports and other benefits.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng announced the plan Friday.
   This year farmers had to set aside 20 percent under the acreage
reduction program to qualify for benefits. But the drought cut
yields sharply and siphoned off much of the nation's grain
stockpile. Thus, restrictions were eased on next year's plantings.
</TEXT>
