<TEXT>
   The confidence of international bankers in the
creditworthiness of the world's nations has sunk to a 10-year low,
Institutional Investor magazine says.
   Its September survey, released Friday, found Japan again
garnered the most confidence, with a rating of 94.8. Switzerland
was second at 93.9, West Germany third at 93.1 and the United
States fourth at 89.7.
   North Korea was at the bottom at 4.5, just below Nicaragua at
5.2.
</TEXT>
