<HEAD>Chrysler Price Increases Average 2.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. says its 1989 cars
will cost about 2.3 percent more than this year's models.
   The announcement Friday followed similiar moves by General
Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Corp.
   GM said it was raising its auto prices 2.9 percent on average
and Ford announced a 2.6 percent increase.
   In a sampling of its 1989 prices, Chrysler said its Plymouth
Sundance four-door would sell for $8,595, compared with $8,522 in
the previous model year, while the Dodge Omni America would sell
for $6,595, up from $5,995 in 1988.
   The 1989 Chrysler New Yorker lists for $17,416, down from
$17,578 in 1988, the automaker said.
