<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Scherer     10-03 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scherer,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scherer to Explore Sale, Other Alternatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.P. Scherer Corp.'s board said today it is
exploring the sale of the gelatin capsule company, marking victory
for a group of dissident shareholders led by the founder's daughter.
   In a brief statement, Scherer said it has hired the investment
firm Goldman Sachs & Co. to ``analyze alternatives which might
include a recapitalization, business combination, management-led
buyout or approaching third parties on the potential sale of all or
part of the company.''
   Karla Scherer Fink, Scherer's largest shareholder and daughter
of the company's late founder, sparked the battle months ago by
pressing her contention that the company be sold.
   Heading the opposition was Peter Fink, the company's president
and chief executive officer and Fink's estranged husband.
   Suits and countersuits have been filed during the past few
months as the two factions struggled to gain control of the
company. Mrs. Fink and her brother, John Scherer, waged a
successful proxy fight at the company's annual meeting in August
that resulted in the ouster of at least one director who opposed
their plan to sell the company.
   The dissident group also was successful in blocking several
management stock-option proposals. Mrs. Fink controls about 33
percent of the company.
   According to today's editions of The Wall Street Journal, Fink
changed his position on the sale after losing the support of other
directors who were swayed by the proxy victories and other factors.
   In a statement, Fink said the hiring of Goldman Sachs doesn't
guarantee that the company will be sold, but Scherer directors will
consider information the firm develops at their next meeting, set
for Oct. 25.
</TEXT>
