<HEAD>Soybeans Sag, Grains Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices dipped while grains
advanced slightly today in early trading at the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Wheat and corn prices received a boost from the U.S. Department
of Agriculture's report on grain stocks released after the close of
trading on Friday. The report showed slightly lower-than-expected
quantities for both grains.
   Buying also was sparked by speculation that China may make a
major purchase of U.S. wheat and the Soviet Union might sign a
long-term grain agreement with the United States, said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Soybean prices were pressured by the USDA report showing
slightly higher-than-expected quantities, and by anticipation of
good harvesting weather this week, Lespinasse said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 2\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.17 a bushel; corn was }
cent lower to 1} cents higher, with December at $2.87{ a bushel;
oats were 1} cent to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.44 a
bushel; and soybeans were 1{ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with
November at $8.12{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork complex prices opened
sharply lower at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, live cattle were .05 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with October at 71.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25
cent lower to .33 cent higher with October at 82.70 cents a pound;
live hogs were .50 cent to 1.50 cents lower with October at 39.10
cents a pound; and pork bellies were 2 cents lower across the
board, with February at 50.32 cents a pound.
   Cattle and pork futures prices were mostly higher in trading
Friday.
