<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-HongKongBanks Adv08-09   10-03 0873</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hong Kong Banks, Adv 08-09,0893</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 8-9 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Two Striking New Bank Buildings Speak To Hong Kong's Future</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Hongkong (not Hong Kong) is the spelling used by the Hongkong
and Shanghai Banking Corp.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One building juts up like an abstractly
whittled chopstick. The other looks like a stack of bridges.
   Two new bank buildings in Hong Kong are striking architectural
testimonies to the future beyond the return of the British colony
to Chinese rule in 1997.
   The taller building, recently topped out at 70 stories, will be
completed next spring to house the Hong Kong office of the Bank of
China, the international banking arm of Communist China.
   The fifth tallest building in the world and the tallest in Asia,
it towers above its neighbors as a symbol, some say, of Beijing's
impending dominance of this free-wheeling world trade center.
   Two blocks east is the ultra-modern glass and aluminum main
office of the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corp., commonly called
the Hongkong Bank, a publicly held corporation that is the colony's
leading commercial bank. It also has some central-bank functions
and owns subsidiary banks and stock-dealing firms around the world.
   A radical-looking, 52-level structure, the Hongkong Bank
building was completed in 1985 with a whopping 5.227 billion Hong
Kong dollars ($670 million) spent on its construction and
furnishings, the bank says.
   If the powerful corporation, which has offices in over 50
countries, had put its money elsewhere, it probably would have
shaken confidence in Hong Kong's future as a capitalist haven.
   In 1997 China retakes sovereignty over Hong Kong and its 5.5
million people. Under an agreement between Britain and China the
territory is to enjoy a high degree of autonomy and retain its
capitalist system for 50 years, but doubts about whether the
agreement will hold up have led to an increase in emigration and a
general nervousness about the future of capitalism.
   Michael Broadbent, spokesman and external relations manager of
the Hongkong Bank, said the building was put up ``because we needed
a new building, not because of Hong Kong's future.''
   ``But people did say that if the Hongkong Bank is prepared to
spend so much, it must be confident in the future of Hong Kong,''
Broadbent said.
   ``That is perfectly true. We do have confidence in Hong Kong's
future.''
   The Bank of China building, though taller than the Hongkong Bank
headquarters, may end up costing less. The land for the Bank of
China building cost 1 billion Hong Kong dollars ($128 million) and
the construction cost is set at 1.1 billion Hong Kong dollars.
   Though the two banks compete in some areas, people associated
with the two buildings aren't throwing stones at each other's costs
or architecture. Broadbent, of the Hongkong Bank, said he greatly
admired the Bank of China's new building. Kellogg Wong, associate
partner in the New York-based I.M. Pei architectural firm that
designed the Bank of China building, has been equally gracious in
his praise of the Hongkong Bank building.
   The Hongkong Bank was designed by the British architect Norman
Foster. The building, more than 585 feet high, has such unusual
features as a sun-scoop across the south side to reflect light into
a 170-foot-high interior atrium; bridge-like trusses at five levels
across the width of the building on which the weight is suspended;
a completely open floor plan; 62 escalators, a claimed world record
for one building; and prefabricated modules on the ends of each
floor containing toilet and service facilities.
   The building was planned to be flexible, and staffers say such
costly features as movable floor panels made from the same material
as aircraft flooring have already paid off by making it possible to
move a whole department in a weekend at low cost.
   The Bank of China building, by contrast, surges up from a base
tier 170 feet square and 170 feet tall, making the first tier a
cube. At that level three-quarters of the cube continues to rise,
and at higher tiers the building becomes abruptly narrower up to
the prism-shaped top, 1,220 feet high. Triangular trusses and
upward-pointing angles are the main visible features.
   ``It's not surprising that the building makes a very strong
structural statement,'' said Wong.
   Leslie Robertson, head of a New York structural engineering firm
that now counts the Bank of China as well as the two World Trade
Center towers in New York among its super-tall clients, said the
building was destined to become ``a new symbol for Hong Kong.''
   But for the Japan-based Kumagai Gumi construction company, which
is doing much of the building work, the Bank of China is likely to
be a money loser.
   By contract the company will receive 1.1 billion Hong Kong
dollars for its work, said Martin Hadaway, project director for
Kumagai Gumi, but costs have escalated above that with the rise in
the Japanese yen and other factors.
   Asked how much Kumagai Gumi would lose, Hadaway replied, ``I
don't know ... But if you take the long-term view, your reputation
in Hong Kong and China will more than cover the loss eventually.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 8-9</NOTE>
</DOC>
