<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Britain-Eurotunnel     10-03 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Eurotunnel,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consortium Raises Cost Estimate for Channel Tunnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eurotunnel, the Anglo-French consortium set up to
build a 31-mile rail tunnel linking Britain and France, said Monday
the project would cost about $500 million more than previously
forecast but that its May 1993 completion date remained unchanged.
   The consortium said it revised its total cost estimate upward by
6 percent to 5.2 billion pounds, the equivalent of $8.8 billion,
from an originally projected 4.9 billion pounds, or $8.3 billion.
   Eurotunnel had said in August that drilling on the tunnel was
well behind schedule. The consortium said Monday it was confident
it could make up for lost time.
   Some 229 million pounds have been spent on the project in the
six months ending June 30, officials said.
   Of the total forecasted costs, Eurotunnel said 3.7 billion
pounds would go to construction, project management and corporate
costs, 1 billion pounds toward financing costs, and 530 million
pounds toward a provision for inflation.
</TEXT>
