<1ST_LINE>r f BC-UPSExpansion     10-03 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-UPS Expansion,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UPS Expands International Delivery Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Parcel Service announced that it has
expanded its international air delivery network to 19 new countries
in Europe and the Far East.
   UPS said Monday that it now is able to provide scheduled
delivery of packages and documents to and from every address in 40
countries and 57 cities in China. Delivery usually takes two to
four days to most points, but the company is aiming for overnight
service, said Senior Vice President John W. Alden.
   UPS, a privately owned company based in Greenwich, Conn., calls
itself the world's largest package delivery company. It currently
ships 10.5 million packages a day worldwide, the bulk of them in
the United States.
   UPS also announced that, as part of the expansion, it has
acquired for an undisclosed sum Asian Courier System, which
operates in Hong Kong, Malaysia, Singapore, Taiwan and Thailand.
   Rates for the international service include customs fees, Alden
told a news conference in New York. He said UPS' computers can hook
up directly with those of customs services in different countries.
   It costs $22 to send a letter overseas with the service, while
the cost of a package ranges from $32 to $246, depending on weight.
</TEXT>
