<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Scotus-Manville 2ndLd-Writethru   10-03 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus-Manville, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Challenge to Johns-Manville Bankruptcy
Reorganization</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lede to CLARIFY that Manville used to manufacture
asbestos products.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected a challenge
to the bankruptcy reorganization of Manville Corp., a building
materials manufacturer that once produced asbestos products.
   The court, without comment, denied an appeal by a company that
distributed asbestos made by Manville, which changed its name in
1981 from Johns-Manville Corp.
   The distributor, MacArthur Co., said the bankruptcy proceedings
unfairly denied it adequate financial protection.
   Manville filed a bankruptcy petition in 1982 designed to protect
it against potential liability of more than $2 billion in suits by
people suffering asbestos-related injuries.
   Between 1984 and 1986, Manville reached a settlement with its
insurance companies. The insurers agreed to pay the company $770
million in return for assurances they would not face additional
claims.
   The insurance settlement, a cornerstone of Manville's bankruptcy
reorganization, was approved by a federal bankruptcy judge.
   The MacArthur company said the judge's order is valid only if it
extends protection to MacArthur against suits by asbestos victims.
   MacArthur said it has been forced to accept the burden of suits
by asbestos victims without the protection of insurance coverage to
which it is entitled.
   But the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in January ruled
against MacArthur.
   The appeals court said if the company has any valid claim
against the insurers, its remedy is to seek money from the $770
million settlement fund created by the insurance firms.
   ``It may well be that MacArthur would prefer to assert its
interest in Manville's property in a proceeding other than in the
bankruptcy court, but such a result is not required by the
bankruptcy law,'' the appeals court said.
   The case is MacArthur Co. vs. Johns-Manville, 87-2082.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
