<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     10-03 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Drifts Lower; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar drifted lower in thin European
trading Monday under the spectre of central bank intervention
raised by West Germany's top central banker.
   Gold prices rose.
   Karl Otto Poehl, president of the Deutsche Bundesbank, was
quoted in a newspaper interview over the weekend as saying that
further weakening of the West German mark ``can't be desirable.''
   The statement implied that the central bank would intervene on
foreign exchange markets to take the steam out of any steep rise in
the U.S. currency, dealers said.
   Frustration over failed attempts to take the dollar higher led
to lackluster selling Monday, one London dealer said.
   ``People are so fed up with the possibility of central bank
intervention on the upside that it's easier to give the dollar a
push lower,'' said Roger Allen, corporate dealer at EBC Amro Bank
in London.
   Dealers in London and Frankfurt predicted the dollar will wander
lower throughout the week until it picks up support at about 1.85
marks. They expect little market-affecting news until the release
Friday of U.S. employment figures for September.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 133.90 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 133.80 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6990 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.6905 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
rates included: 1.8608 West German marks, down from 1.8725; 1.5785
Swiss francs, down from 1.5830; 6.3350 French francs, down from
6.3700; 2.1010 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1185; 1,397.95 Italian
lire, up from 1,396.50; and 1.2104 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2171.
   Gold prices rebounded in Europe based on short-covering, the
buying of gold to fulfill agreements to sell it, Zurich dealers
said. But they predicted lower oil prices will continue to dim
fears of inflation and depress the value of bullion.
   Gold climbed more than $3 per troy ounce in London to a late bid
price of $397.75, compared with late Friday's $394.45.
   In Zurich, gold rose marginally higher, closing at a bid $397
compared with $396 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.31 to close at a bid $397.91
per ounce.
   Silver bullion prices edged higher on the London market where
the metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.22 a troy ounce,
compared with Friday's $6.14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
