<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   10-03 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Off 23.9 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange fell
sharply Monday to close at the day's lowest point, as a negative
start to Wall Street and concerns over slumping oil prices
depressed a thin market.
   Dealers said declines in prices and volume reflected renewed
skittish sentiment in contrast to last week's enthusiasm over a
better-than-expected British trade report for August and takeover
speculation.
   ``Cold water has been poured on the market and any advance has
been stopped dead in its tracks,'' one dealer said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 23.9
points, or 1.3 percent, lower at 1,802.6, its worst level for the
day.
   The index moved in negative territory all session, and at its
best level, at midmorning, it showed a loss of 9.1 points.
   Volume was modest, as just 336.6 million shares changed hands,
compared with 550.1 million shares traded Friday.
   The Dow Jones industrial average was off 25.43 points at
2,087.48 as London trading subsided.
   Several dealers said Wall Street's slide came on the heels of
talk in New York that a major U.S. brokerage issued a strongly
worded recommendation for clients to switch out of equities.
   The sagging price of crude oil took its toll on market
sentiment, some said.
   ``It might have absolutely horrendous implications'' for
Britain's trade balance, one market maker said. The country is the
world's fifth-largest oil producer.
</TEXT>
