<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Fairchild-Carlyle     10-03 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fairchild-Carlyle,0243</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A unit of The Carlyle Group, L.P. has
purchased almost 10 percent of Fairchild Industries Inc.'s common
stock for about $16.8 million, according to documents filed with
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The Carlyle Group, a Washington-based private merchant banking
and investment firm, stated in its SEC filing that it was exploring
the possibility of acquiring all of the outstanding common stock of
Fairchild in a friendly transaction.
   The filing stated that the deal ``is not opposed by a majority
of the members of the company's board of directors.''
   Fairchild board chairman Emanuel Fthenakis said Monday the
company is evaluating the Schedule 13D filing and the investors.
   Fthenakis noted that the company historically has attracted
investors who are interested in Fairchild's long-term value, rather
than short-term profit-taking.
   Carlyle stated it believed any transactions could be financed
under current market conditions. No agreement, however, has been
reached with the banks, the investors said.
   According to the filing, the partnership holds more than 1.4
million shares of stock in the Chantilly, Va.-based defense
electronics and industrial parts company.
   All of the stock was purchased since July 25 at prices ranging
from $9.96 to $11 per share, Carlyle said.
   Several telephone conversations between Carlyle and Fthenakis
have been held, but no meeting has been scheduled.
   Fairchild reported second quarter profits of $10.2 million on
revenues of $132 million.
</TEXT>
