<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1502EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-03 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0260</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grains futures prices were mostly higher while
soybean prices were mixed Monday as traders at the Chicago Board of
Trade took their cues from U.S. Department of Agriculture reports.
   ``Wheat and corn benefited from Friday's (USDA) quarterly stocks
report, which showed a little less corn and wheat ... than
expected,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   Speculation that China may be on the verge of making a
substantial purchase of U.S. wheat, and that the Soviet Union may
be preparing to sign a long-term grain agreement with the United
States also fueled buying, he said.
   Corn traders received another bullish signal from the USDA's
quarterly report released after the close of trading Friday showing
larger-than-expected numbers of pigs expected to be born in coming
months, Lespinasse said. Corn is a major food source for pigs.
   The soy complex, especially soybean meal _ another important
feed for pigs _ also gained some support from the pig report, as
well as from the strength in the wheat and bean pits, Lespinasse
said.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 5} cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.20\ a bushel; corn was 1
cent lower to 4{ cents higher with December at $2.90\ a bushel;
oats were 3\ cents to 6\ cents higher, with December at $2.47} a
bushel; and soybeans were 8{ cents lower to 7 cents higher, with
November at $8.20 a bushel.
</TEXT>
