<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1752EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklySteel     10-03 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Fell 2.6 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production fell to 1.906 million tons in
the week ended Oct. 1, a decrease of 2.6 percent from the previous
week's 1.957 million tons, the American Iron and Steel Institute
reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 88.9 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 91.8 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
75.456 million net tons, an increase of 17.4 percent from the
64.290 million net tons in the previous year.
   Production so far this year used 89.7 percent of capacity,
compared with 76.5 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended Oct. 1: Northeast
Coast, 284,000; Pittsburgh, 196,000; Youngstown, 99,000; Lake Erie,
148,000; Detroit, 160,000; Chicago, 479,000; Midwest, 207,000;
Southern, 238,000; and Western, 95,000.
</TEXT>
