<DOCNO> AP881003-0335 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Scotus-Business Bjt   10-03 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Business, Bjt,0795</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WPPSS Bond Buyers Lose Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court closed a chapter Monday in
the largest municipal bond default in U.S. history, dismissing
claims by investors who lost money from the Washington Public Power
Supply System's doomed nuclear power project.
   The court let stand a ruling that dismissed some key investor
claims triggered by the $2.25 billion bond default. It also
rejected an appeal by the bond counsel in the case seeking
additional legal protection.
   Meanwhile, Manville Corp. was given the go-ahead to emerge from
six years of federal bankruptcy court protection after the justices
rejected a challenge to the reorganization of the Denver-based
building materials company.
   Manville filed a bankruptcy petition in 1982 to protect itself
against potential liability of more than $2 billion in suits by
people suffering asbestos-related injuries.The challenge to its
reorganization plan came from MacArthur Co., which distributed
asbestos made by Manville.
   The justices also set the stage for an important antitrust case
by agreeing to decide whether states may sue on behalf of those
indirectly affected by illegal price-fixing.
   The court decided to hear an appeal by California, Minnesota,
Alabama and Arizona seeking to participate in a multimillion-dollar
settlement of a nationwide conspiracy to fix cement prices. Lower
courts had dismissed their efforts to sue for county and municipal
governments that had purchased cement products.
   In the case involving WPPSS, investors, ranging from individuals
to major corporations, had sued WPPSS and numerous others in 1984.
   The Washington State Supreme Court last year upheld a state law
that retroactively expanded protection for cities and utilities
against some bondholder claims.
   That ruling made it more difficult for investors to recover
their losses by suing public agencies. But at the same time the
state court permitted other investor claims to proceed to trial.
   A trial began last month in Tucson, Ariz., in which more than
24,000 bond buyers are charging fraud by 19 defendants _ 16
utilities, two engineering firms and a financial adviser. The
defendants allegedly withheld crucial information from investors
who bought bonds to finance construction of two nuclear power
plants.
   The appeal acted on Monday challenged portions of the 1987
Washington Supreme Court decision upholding state law protections
for cities and utilities.
   In other cases Monday, the justices:
   _Announced they will expand the court's study of drug testing in
the workplace by agreeing to decide whether a railroad may require
workers to take the tests routinely.
   _Rejected arguments aimed at making it easier to sue those
accused of taking part in antitrust conspiracies uncovered years
after they occurred.
   _Agreed to study the power of federal courts to decide some
disputes in which the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp.
takes charge of a failing state-chartered financial institution.
   _Agreed to decide whether states generally may prosecute
employers for withholding accrued vacation pay owed fired workers.
   _Decided to consider, for the second time in two years, the
authority of states to deny unemployment benefits to people who
refuse to work on their Sabbath.
   _Said it would judge the validity of a 1986 federal law imposing
``user fees'' on pipeline companies.
   _Rejected a challenge to the rates being charged for
transporting oil through the Trans-Alaska Pipeline.
   _Refused to force an insurance company to help pay for cleaning
up the highly toxic chemical dioxin, disposed of in various
Missouri locations in the early 1970s.
   _Turned away arguments that the policies of the Bonneville Power
Administration are costing electricity consumers in California
billions of dollars.
   _Refused to order the government to compensate the owner of a
Barnwell, S.C., nuclear fuel reprocessing plant that was denied an
operating license due to a Carter administration decision on
curbing international nuclear proliferation.
   _Left intact a ruling that states must compensate tree nursery
owners required to destroy healthy citrus plants that may have been
exposed to an infectious disease.
   _Left intact a $48.3 million judgment awarded Trans World
Airlines against a company founded by the late billionaire Howard
Hughes. TWA charged Summa Corp., formerly called Hughes Tool Co.,
had forced it to lease jets and buy from Hughes when that company
owned 75 percent of TWA stock.
   _Refused to hear an appeal from a New York City developer who
was ordered to remove the top 12 floors of a 31-story condominium
building on Manhattan's fashionable Upper East Side.
   _Agreed to decide whether the federal government may continue to
bar newspapers from carrying advertisements for privately run
lotteries and other games of chance.
   _Agreed to decide whether New York state universities may ban
some commercial activities in dormitory rooms.
</TEXT>
