<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1540EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EnergyPoll     10-03 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Energy Poll,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Americans Favor More Fuel-Efficient Cars, Poll Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fuel Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ninety percent of Americans believe the
government should require automakers to build cars with greater
fuel-efficiency, according to a poll commissioned by
environmentalists.
   Two-thirds of the respondents believe they will see another
energy crisis that could bring back gasoline lines, but nearly
three-quarters oppose a 30-cent increase in the gasoline tax aimed
at discouraging consumption, according to the survey by the
Analysis Group Inc., a New Haven, Conn.-based polling firm.
   The pollsters telephoned 1,000 registered voters from Sept.
10-14 for The Communications Consortium, a public relations firm
representing environmental groups. The margin of error in the poll
is about three percentage points.
   The consortium released the results Monday before Transportation
Secretary Jim Burnley announced his decision to require auto
companies to average 26.5 miles per gallon for the 1989 model year.
That is up from the 26 mpg standard required for the past three
years but less than the 27.5 mpg requirement that would have
otherwise taken effect under law.
   Stanley B. Greenberg, president of the polling firm, said an
inconsistency between the poll's results and the popularity of
larger, more fuel-hungry cars is ``clearly true in this area and is
also true in almost every area of life that you can imagine.''
   Sixty-seven percent of those questioned predicted a repeat of
energy crises like those of the 1970s, 26 percent said it would not
happen and 7 percent said they did not know.
   Sixty-one percent gave a ``strongly favor'' response to the
proposition that auto companies should be required to build more
fuel efficient cars, an additional 29 percent reported a ``somewhat
favor'' answer with only 8 percent opposed.
   When asked if cars should be required to average 45 mpg in the
year 2000, a position some environmental groups have endorsed, the
poll respondents split 82-15 in favor.
   If such a requirement meant a $500 increase in the price of the
car, the split was still 77-19 in favor.
   Though 56 percent favored a 25-cent per gallon tariff on
imported crude oil ``to reduce our dependence on foreign oil'' and
37 percent opposed it, 72 percent opposed a 30-cent gasoline tax
increase while only 24 percent were in favor.
   By 64-29, the respondents favored policies that would encourage
energy efficiency over increased energy production. Only 9 percent
called for ``a new commitment to the building of new nuclear power
plants.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
