<DOCNO> AP881003-0337 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     10-03 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,0533</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of
business-related actions taken Monday by the Supreme Court.
   
   DRUG TESTS
   
   The court announced it will expand its study of drug testing in
the workplace, agreeing to decide whether a railroad may require
workers to take the tests routinely.
   The justices said they will review a ruling that barred the
Consolidated Rail Corporation, or Conrail, from imposing the tests
without permitting collective bargaining over the issue.
   The court announced earlier this year that it would review two
other drug-testing cases _ one involving railway workers and the
other the U.S. Customs Service.
   Today's action significantly expands the scope of the court's
review by including a case in which a private company _ rather than
the government _ is adopting mandatory drug tests.
   The case is Conrail vs. Railway Labor Executives Association,
88-1.
   
   TRANS WORLD AIRLINES
   
   The court left intact a $48.3 million judgment awarded Trans
World Airlines against a company founded by the late billionaire
Howard Hughes.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments by Summa Corp.
and William R. Lunnis, administrator of the Hughes estate, that the
award should be thrown out.
   The case is Summa Corp. vs. TWA, 88-149.
   
   LOTTERIES
   
   The court agreed to decide whether the federal government may
continue to bar newspapers from carrying advertisements for
privately run lotteries and other games of chance.
   The justices said they will study a Minnesota Newspaper
Association challenge to a postal law effectively prohibiting such
advertising.
   The cases are Minnesota Newspaper Association vs. Postmaster
General, 87-1943, and Frank vs. Minnesota Newspaper Association,
87-1956.
   
   DIOXIN CLEAN-UP
   
   The court refused to force an insurance company to help pay for
cleaning up dioxin, a highly toxic chemical, disposed of in various
Missouri locations in the early 1970s.
   The justices, without comment, let standa ruling that an
insurance policy held by the chemical firm responsible for the
pollution did not make the insurance company liable for clean-up
costs.
   The case is Missouri vs. Continental Insurance, 87-1953.
   
   PIPELINE FEES
   
   The court, in a case that could bear on a wide range of federal
fees and taxes, agreed to judge the validity of a 1986 federal law
imposing ``user fees'' on pipeline companies.
   The justices said they will hear a Reagan administration
challenge to an Oklahoma court ruling that struck down the law. A
pipeline company that transports hazardous liquids had attacked the
law as unconstitutional.
   The case is Burnley vs. Mid-America Pipeline, 87-2098.
   
   ANTITRUST
   
   The court, setting the stage for an important antitrust ruling,
today agreed to decide whether states may sue in behalf of those
indirectly affected by illegal price-fixing.
   The court voted to hear an appeal by four states _ California,
Minnesota, Alabama and Arizona _ seeking to participate in a
multi-million-dollar settlement of a nationwide conspiracy to fix
cement prices.
   The case is California vs. ARC America Corp., 87-1862.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
