<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MediaGeneral     10-03 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Stockholder Suit Against Publishing Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stockholder's lawsuit against Media
General Inc. involving the company's two-tiered stock structure was
dismissed Monday by a federal judge.
   U.S. District Judge Richard L. Williams agreed with arguments by
attorneys for Media General that the complaint of Harvey Jasper, a
New York lawyer who owns 100 shares of company stock, did not have
a strong enough legal basis to proceed to trial. At one time,
Jasper owned 5,000 shares of Media General.
   Williams also rejected an argument by Jasper's attorneys that
the complaint be considered a class action on behalf of other
holders of Media General Class A common stock.
   Jasper's lawsuit contended that a 1987 Media General proxy
statement was misleading about whether the company would accept a
buyout offer. Jasper bought stock after the proxy statement was
issued.
   The statement defined in some detail the relative strengths of
the company's A and B common stock classes. He contended he lost
money on his investments because those who control the stock did
not state the company never would be for sale.
   James W. Tredway, an attorney for Media General, argued that if
the proxy statement lacked any clarity, the problem was resolved in
October 1987 when the company issued a statement after the purchase
of a block of Class A stock by Hollywood producer Burt Sugarman.
   The company said it could not imagine circumstances in which
owners of the controlling stock in Media General ever would sell
their shares.
   Jasper's lawsuit was related to an unsuccessful takeover offer
from Sugarman. On Feb. 29, Sugarman proposed to buy all of Media
General's A and B stock for $61.50 a share, then raised the offer
to $70 and also sought to have himself and two associates named to
the Media General board at the May 20 annual meeting.
   At the time of the meeting, Sugarman, his associates and
companies he owns or controls held more than 10 percent of Media
General's Class A stock.
   D. Tennant Bryan, chairman of Media General, and his son, J.
Stewart Bryan III, vice chairman, in effect control the company
through their holdings in Class B stock.
   The Bryans said the firm was not for sale at any price and
opposed election of Sugarman and his associates to the board.
Sugarman lost the proxy fight but has sued the company over the
stock structure and has an appeal pending.
   Among Media General's holdings are The Richmond News Leader, the
Richmond Times-Dispatch and The Tampa (Fla) Tribune.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
