<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices sagged in light trading Monday,
starting off the final quarter of 1988 on a wary note.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 7.65 to 2,105.26.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 9 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
536 up, 954 down and 444 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 130.38 million
shares, down from 175.75 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 150.47 million shares.
   Wall Streeters were generally resigning themselves to a sluggish
week, expecting investors to back away from stocks before the
government issues its monthly report Friday on the employment
situation.
   Analysts look for the data to show a pickup in payroll
employment growth for September after relatively modest increases
in July and August.
   If those estimates prove correct, it would come as a setback to
hopes that the economy was slowing to a pace that would satisfy the
Federal Reserve, which is seeking to keep inflation from heating up.
   The Commerce Department reported Monday that new factory orders
rose 3.1 percent in August.
   With all that, however, the market finished well above its
midday lows, when the Dow Jones industrials showed a loss of as
much as 25 points.
   Losers among the blue chips included Exxon, down ] at 44];
International Business Machines, down { at 114~; General Electric,
down [ at 43\, and Coca-Cola, down | at 43[.
   In the plus column, Ford Motor gained } to 51~ and Eastman Kodak
rose ~ to 45~.
   Technology issues were broadly lower. Digital Equipment fell 1
to 92~, and Hewlett-Packard [ to 49}, while in the over-the-counter
market Intel lost 1[ to 26] and Apple Computer was down } at 42{.
   Japanese stocks also were weak following declines Saturday and
Monday in the Tokyo stock market. Honda Motor dropped 4\ to 156};
Matsushita Electrical 4~ to 181[, and Kyocera 1 to 76.
   Mylan Laboratories fell ~ to 8}. The company estimated lower
earnings for the fiscal quarter that ended last week.
   Middle South Utilities bucked the downtrend, rising [ to 15[ in
active trading. On Friday the company declared its first
common-stock dividend in three years.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $7.47 billion, or 0.28
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .34 to 153.23.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell .53 to 311.14, and S&P's
500-stock composite index was down .53 at 271.38.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
tumbled 3.23 to 384.48. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 300 even, down 1.63.
