<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Perot-EDS     10-03 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Perot-EDS,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perot Files Countersuit Against EDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wealthy entrepreneur Ross Perot has countersued
his former company, Electronic Data Systems, after the computer
services firm accused him in a lawsuit of violating a covenant
against competing with EDS.
   Perot, former chairman of EDS, filed the countersuit Friday in
U.S. District Court.
   Perot founded EDS in 1962 and sold it to General Motors Corp. in
1984.
   The relationship between Perot and GM soon soured, and Perot and
three other top EDS executives left the firm in December 1986 when
GM agreed to pay them about $850 million. Perot also stepped down
from GM's board.
   Last week, EDS filed a suit in which it claimed Perot violated
an agreement to refrain from competing with the data-processing
company for at least three years after he left the company.
   The EDS suit, filed in state court in Virginia, also named
Perot's new company, Virginia-based Perot Systems Group, as a
defendant.
   In papers filed with his countersuit in federal court in Dallas,
Perot sought an injunction to prevent EDS and GM from interfering
in Perot Systems Group's business activities.
   Perot contends the suit is groundless and will ``boomerang'' on
EDS.
   Earlier this year, Perot proposed to automate the U.S. Postal
Service and his company was awarded a no-bid contract for the job.
   But after protests by EDS and other companies, the General
Services Administration suspended Perot's postal contract.
   Perot has challenged the GSA's suspension of the contract. The
Postal Service contract is one of Perot's activities that EDS
claims violate the 1986 agreement.
</TEXT>
