<2ND_LINE>AM-Work Station,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silicon Graphics Announces Cheaper Work Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Silicon Graphics Inc. is scheduled to announce
on Tuesday a computer work station with three-dimensional graphics
that is priced at less than $16,000, a direct challenge to neighbor
Sun Microsystems Inc.
   Sun Microsystems' least expensive three-dimensional graphics
workstation starts at slightly more than $30,000.
   Work stations are fast versions of personal computers and are
used mainly by scientists, engineers and lately business and
finance professionals.
   Silicon Graphics, which like Sun is based in Mountain View,
Calif., already has a line of work stations priced from $45,000 to
$90,000. That line has captured about 25 percent of the $600
million high-end work station market, according to the current
issue of Business Week.
   The Personal Iris is the cheapest member of a new family of work
stations, including six members of the Iris Power family that start
at $54,900.
   ``This is the most significant product announcement in the
history of the company,'' James H. Clark, the chairman and founder,
said in a news release.
   In another recent boost, Silicon Graphics last month licensed
its three-dimensional graphics technology to International Business
Machines Corp.
   IBM and Digital Equipment Corp. are preparing to make major
moves into the work station market, which has been dominated by the
likes of Sun, Silicon Graphics and Apollo Computer Inc. of
Chelmsford, Mass.
</TEXT>
