<DOCNO> AP881003-0347 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1907EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankingSecurities     10-03 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banking Securities,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plan Proposed For Bill To Let Bank Holding Companies Own
Securities Firms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: St Germain, no period, is cq in 4th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Banking Committee chairman, William
Proxmire, D-Wis., on Monday proposed a parliamentary maneuver that
would, if successful, allow Congress to pass legislation permitting
bank holding companies to own securities firms.
   The Senate in March overwhelmingly passed a bill allowing
affiliates of bank holding companies to underwrite most kinds of
securities, except corporate stock.
   In the House, the Banking Committee and the Energy and Commerce
Committee have passed competing versions. Both impose more
restrictions on banks and offer fewer new powers, but the Energy
and Commerce version is the most restrictive.
   The dispute between the committees has turned into a
jurisdictional war between Energy and Commerce Chairman John
Dingell, D-Mich., and Banking Chairman Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.
   So far, House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, has insisted that the
two settle their differences before the banking bill comes to the
House floor.
   In a letter last week to Wright, St Germain said he and Dingell
had been unable to agree and he complained that the Dingell
committee's ``overly broad perception ... of its jurisdiction has
... paralyze(d) ... one of the most important banking acts of this
century.''
   With Congress planning to adjourn at the end of the week,
Proxmire is proposing that most of the Senate bill be attached to
an unrelated banking bill already passed by the House. Other parts
of the Senate bill could be passed separately or linked to an
unrelated securities bill sponsored by Dingell that toughens
penalties for insider trading.
   Under the Proxmire plan, the banking-securities legislation then
could be ironed out in a conference between leaders in both
chambers before coming up for a vote in the full House and Senate.
That way, the House Rules Committee would not have to make a
decision on the competing jurisdictional claims of Dingell and St
Germain.
   Also, in a move to meet the concerns of St Germain and of Sen.
Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, who has threatened to block the
maneuver, Proxmire added a series of ``pro-consumer'' provisions to
the bill, including a requirement that banks cash government checks
for non-customers and offer ``lifeline'' banking accounts to poor
people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
