<DOCNO> AP881003-0348 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ClaridgeSale     10-03 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Claridge Sale,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Golden Nugget Agrees To Purchase Claridge Casino</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Wynn, the flamboyant hotel and
casino operator who sold his Golden Nugget casino here last year,
has agreed to purchase Del E. Webb Corp.'s Claridge Casino Hotel
for $110 million, officials announced Monday.
   Wynn's acquisition of the financially-troubled Claridge from the
Phoenix-based company is subject to approval by New Jersey gaming
regulators and Atlantic City Boardwalk Associates, the limited
partnership that leases the Claridge's real estate.
   Del Webb, which has a 10 percent interest in the Claridge, has
the management contract for the facility.
   The company and Atlantic City Boardwalk Associates have been
seeking a possible buyer since May for the 501-room Claridge. Hotel
president Roger Wagner has said more than 170 potential purchasers
have contacted Del Webb's investment banker, Oppenheimer & Co.,
about the Claridge.
   Ed Wren, a Del Webb spokesman, said Monday the company suffered
a $96.6 million net loss in 1987, with the Claridge responsible for
78.8 percent of the loss.
   ``From Del Webb's standpoint, we think the completion of this
sale will provide benefits to investors that might not otherwise be
available,'' he said.
   Wren said Del Webb has been selling off assets in its leisure
group, which includes other casino and recreational properties. On
Friday, Wynn closed a deal to purchase the Nevada Club casino in
Laughlin, Nev., from Del Webb for $40 million.
   ``Our working relationship with the Golden Nugget on the sale of
our other hotel was excellent, so we are optimistic about the
Claridge,'' Wren said.
   Wynn could not be reached for comment. He did not return calls
to his office in Las Vegas, Nev., where he has built a gaming
empire on the city's famed casino strip.
   Marvin Roffman, a gaming analyst with the Philadelphia
investment group Janney Montgomery Scott, said Wynn's re-entry into
the Atlantic City casino market could mean intense competition for
the resort's other gaming halls.
   Roffman said that because Wynn's purchase price was relatively
low, ``his overhead will be lower than anybody else in town, so he
can give tremendous leeway to the bettor.''
   ``If he does do this, it will have serious implications for his
competitors, because casinos in Atlantic City don't like to give up
even one customer,'' Roffman said. ``Generally speaking, they tend
to match what the competition is doing to defend their market
share...but when you raise the odds, you lower what the house wins.
If you're running a high-priced operation, you can't do it.''
   Wynn left the Atlantic City casino industry in 1987 when he sold
the Golden Nugget in the resort to Bally Corp. for $440 million.
The sale was a factor in blocking rival Donald Trump's efforts to
take over Bally's Park Place Casino hotel in Atlantic City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
