<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Deere-UAW     10-03 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Deere-UAW,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deere and UAW Finalize Tentative Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of the United Auto Workers
said Monday that ratification votes on a proposed three-year labor
agreement would be held this weekend at Deere & Co. factory and
warehouse sites in five states.
   The company reached an agreement in principle early Saturday
with the union, which represents 13,400 blue-collar workers in
Illinois, Iowa, Atlanta, Minneapolis and Denver. The tentative
agreement capped a marathon 20-hour bargaining session.
   Details of the proposed contract have not been disclosed. The
contract would take effect immediately upon ratification and would
run through midnight Sept. 30, 1991.
   Deere and the UAW negotiated daily for nearly two months before
the settlement was announced at 5:08 a.m. CDT Saturday, at a
negotiating site in Moline, Ill., near Deere's world headquarters.
   Negotiators worked past a midnight Friday strike deadline with
no formal extension of the current contract or call for a walkout.
   The union did not call for a strike, but scattered pickets were
reported at Deere plants in East Moline, Ill., and Dubuque, Iowa.
   Deere and the union are trying to avoid a repeat of the bitter
five-month strike in 1986-87 that ended after 163 days with
employees' acceptance of a wage freeze and other concessions.
</TEXT>
