<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 2329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-US-Taiwan     10-03 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-US-Taiwan,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Hail Sharp Drop in U.S. Trade Deficit With Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan substantially reduced its trade surplus
with the United States the past year but can still do more, U.S.
Assistant Commerce Secretary Louis F. Laun said Monday.
   ``The best insurance against (U.S.) trade protectionism is for
you to show us that your markets are as open as ours,'' Laun said
in a greeting to the 14th ``Buy American'' mission from Taiwan.
   At a ceremony in Washington, members of the 45-member promotion
group signed contracts to buy $160 million worth of American goods.
It was the first stop of a three-week, 11-state tour expected to
make total purchases of at least $532 million.
   The island's foreign trade chief told the gathering Taiwan would
like a free trade agreement with the United States like those
arranged with Canada and Israel.
   Laun said the U.S. trade deficit with Taiwan was down by 37
percent in the first half of 1988. Taiwan officials said their
trade surplus for January to August this year was $6.4 billion,
41.7 percent less than that during the same period of 1987.
   Taiwan also has allowed its currency to gain 40 percent in value
against the U.S. dollar, making U.S. goods more attractively
priced, but ``there is still a way to go,'' Laun said.
   Taiwan has reduced tariffs on U.S. products from 28 percent to
14 percent, but here too, ``there is still a way to go,'' he said.
</TEXT>
