<HEAD>Dollar, Share Prices Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened lower against the Japanese
yen Tuesday morning, while share prices edged down on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 154.60-point
loser the previous day, was down another 81.56 points at 27,463.97
in the first 15 minutes of trading.
   The dollar opened at 133.37 yen, down from Monday's close of
133.90 yen.
   The U.S. currency inched down following its lower closing on
Wall Street overnight, according to a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   ``The dollar was moving very little between the mid-133 yen and
134-yen range, without any fresh market-affecting news,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The dealer said some participants were buying the dollar, but
dollar-selling still was stronger.
   On the stock exchange, ``the economic factors around stock
trading are almost the best they could be, and share prices should
not keep falling like this,'' said Manji Ueda with Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   Other dealers said share prices were lower in reaction to the
decline overnight on Wall Street.
