<1ST_LINE>r f BC-USAir-FlightAttendants     10-03 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-USAir-Flight Attendants,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USAir Flight Attendants Ratify 1-Year Labor Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir flight attendants have approved a new
one-year labor agreement that includes wage parity for former
Pacific Southwest flight attendants, the Association of Flight
Attendants announced Monday.
   The union said the contract approved by the 4,000 USAir flight
attendants that it represents included an across-the-board 3
percent pay raise for all USAir attendants, plus a compromise on
the divisive pay parity issue.
   USAir acquired Pacific Southwest in May 1987 but operated it as
a separate subsidiary until last April before merging the two
operations.
   The current contract was up for renewal and amendment Sept. 1.
The new contract was reached Aug. 25 in Pittsburgh after 10 days of
intense negotiations there.
   The flight attendants union said in a news release that PSA base
pay will increase by 25 percent of the difference between PSA and
USAir pay rates, beginning April 9, 1989. Full parity for PSA
attendants will occur on the date of the merger of USAir and
Piedmont Airlines, which was expected to occur in March or April.
   The contract also includes PSA attendants in USAir's pension
plan. USAir will credit PSA flight attendants with up to 15 years
of past service for its pension plan.
   The 961 former Pacific Southwest attendants had been represented
by the Teamsters but voted to switch to the Association of Flight
Attendants just prior to USAir's acquisition of PSA.
   Union officials have said said the former PSA attendants
generally were on pay scales about 10 percent less than those at
USAir. The company had offered to bring the two groups of workers
to parity over a three-year period.
   The union had wanted that accomplished faster. When the two
sides reached an impasse last spring, many attendants refused to
work overtime on the Memorial Day weekend, forcing USAir to cancel
some 170 flights then.
   The union and the company now must go through the same process
to integrate a contract covering some 3,000 flight attendants at
Piedmont Airlines into the USAir accord.
   USAir purchased Piedmont last November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
