<1ST_LINE>r f BC-REIInvestigation     10-03 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-REI Investigation,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Say They To Seek Fraud Charges Against Data Company, Some
Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors have told Recognition
Equipment Inc. that they plan to seek fraud charges against the
computer data company and some of its top officials following an
investigation into alleged procurement irregularities, the company
said Monday.
   The U.S. Attorney's office in Washington announced ``the
investigation into procurement irregularities involving multiline
sorters for the USPS (U.S. Postal Service) is nearing a
conclusion.''
   Federal officials said ``the possibility exists'' that charges
could be brought against REI ``and-or some of its employees.'' A
grand jury in Washington will be asked to consider charges this
week, REI officials said.
   The company ``has been advised that the investigation has been
completed and that the U.S. Attorney's office intends to seek an
indictment against the company; its chief executive officer,
William G. Moore Jr.; and a vice president, Robert W. Reedy,'' the
statement said.
   ``The U.S. Attorney's office advised that it expects the
indictment would charge conspiracy to defraud the United States
along with theft and fraud counts,'' according to the statement.
   A company spokesman said REI denies the allegations and intends
to vigorously defend itself.
   Prosecutors had focused on Irving, Texas-based REI's campaign in
1985 and 1986 to get a $250 million mail-sorting contract. The
company allegedly proposed a contract-sharing deal with a
competitor, according to a report compiled by postal inspectors
assisting in the investigation.
   Company officials, in a statement, said REI has had recent
discussions with the U.S. Attorney's office and Justice Department
regarding the investigation.
   ``If charges are brought against the company, they could
adversely affect the company's ability to do business with the
federal government,'' said the statement.
   In the first 10 months of its current fiscal year, REI got about
10 percent of its revenue from federal government business.
</TEXT>
