<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-CSX     10-03 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-CSX,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CSX Third Quarter Earnings Up 15.4 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CSX Corp. said Monday its third quarter
profit was up by 15.4 percent over the same period last year.
   The international transportation company posted a profit of $120
million, or 75 cents a share, for the third quarter, up from a
profit of $104 million, 67 cents per share, in the same quarter
last year.
   Third quarter operating revenue rose to $1.89 billion from $1.76
billion a year earlier.
   Operating income rose in the company's rail and properties
groups and at its Sea-Land shipping unit, but declined in its barge
unit due to drought conditions that snarled river traffic in many
areas.
   CSX is restructuring to emphasize its core businesses and reduce
labor costs.
   In September, the company announced another phase of
restructuring with the repurchasing of up to 60 million shares of
CSX common stock for not less than $28 and not more than $33 a
share.
   The CSX board of directors also ordered the liquidation of the
company's natural gas operations and resort properties.
   For the first nine months of the year, CSX posted a profit of
$25 million, or 11 cents a share, compared with $303 million, or
$1.96 per share, a year earlier. The decline stemmed from a special
pre-tax charge of $778 million taken in the second quarter to cover
the cost of early separation agreements with unions, incurred under
the restructuring.
   Without the charge, CSX said, nine-month profit would have been
$517 million, or $3.27 a share.
   Operating revenue during the nine-month period rose to $5.54
billion from $5.11 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
